<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--LongGradLine     02-28 0123</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Long Grad Line,0126</SECOND>
<HEAD>Freshman Follows Long Family Line Into College</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOUTH HADLEY, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alicechandra Fritz comes from a long
line of Mount Holyoke students, the longest, in fact, in the
college's 152-year history.
   The 18-year-old freshman from Berkeley, Calif., extended the
streak to six generations when she enrolled, said Vee Wailgum,
spokeswoman for the women's college.
   The first was her great-great-great grandmother, Mary Ballantine
Fairbank, class of 1855.
   Including aunts, great-aunts and distant cousins, Fritz' family
has sent 55 women to the school founded in 1837.
   Fritz and her mother, Margaret Conkey, insisted they were not
forced to go to the school. ``Whatever pressure there was, it did
not mandate that we go to Mount Holyoke,'' said Ms. Conkey.
</TEXT>
