<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 0112EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-CottonOutlook     02-28 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cotton Outlook,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Cotton Stockpile Growing, Demand Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. cotton stockpile is outgrowing demand
from domestic textile mills as well as from overseas markets,
according to an Agriculture Department report.
   Cotton exports in 1988-89 are forecast at 6.9 million bales, down
from 7.62 million bales last year.
   ``Aggressive pricing by major foreign exporters and heavy
movement of U.S. cotton under (government price support) loan have
been largely responsible for the decline,'' the report said Monday.
   When a farmer obtains a price support loan for cotton or another
commodity, it cannot be sold until the loan is repaid. Often when
market prices are low, a farmer will not repay the loan and forfeit
the commodity to the government.
   Despite a number of adjustments in the loan program to make U.S.
cotton more competitive in the world market, prices still remain
above those of foreign competitors, the report said.
   Meanwhile, cotton use by U.S. textile mills reached 7.6 million
bales in 1987-88, the most in 15 years. But this season's mill use
is expected to drop to 6.9 million bales.
   ``Reduced denim demand and consumer preference for more
fine-count yarn products are lowering mill use,'' the report said.
   As a result, U.S. cotton stockpiles, which were less than 5.8
million bales last Aug. 1, are expected to climb to 9.2 million by
this Aug. 1, the beginning of the 1989-90 cotton marketing year.
</TEXT>
