<FIRST>r w PM-DerwinskiConfirmation     02-28 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Derwinski Confirmation,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vets Nominee Questioned on Korean Tip-Off</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: likely to stand; closed hearing begins at 2:15 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's choice to head the new
Veterans Affairs Department faces questioning about why he tipped
off the South Korean Embassy 12 years ago that a Korean agent was
about to defect to the United States.
   Edward J. Derwinski initially denied that the tip had come from
him, only acknowledging it in 1983 in testimony before the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee. That testimony was unpublished, but it
was uncovered in the National Archives last month by The Los Angeles
Times.
   Derwinski, a former Illinois congressman and recent State
Department official, was due before the Senate Veterans Affairs
Committee today for a closed-door hearing. The committee plans to
continue considering his nomination in open session on Wednesday.
   During a 1978 investigation of the Korean case, Derwinski denied
that the tip came from him and declined to answer a grand jury's
questions about the episode.
   In 1977, the defector, Sohn Ho Young, and his family were
spirited away from his New Jersey home by the FBI just a half hour
before the arrival of agents of the Korean Central Intelligence
Agency, for whom he worked.
   Derwinski at the time was a member of a House committee
investigating the ``Koreagate'' affair involving bribes by South
Korea to members of Congress.
   In a recent interview, Derwinski talked about the Koreagate
episode: ``It was dumb of me. That's easy to say now; it's
hindsight. I didn't have hindsight then.''
   Derwinski, a vigorous defender of the Korean government at the
time, said that when he learned the Koreagate committee was planning
to call Sohn as a witness, he told the embassy: ``Another PR blow is
headed your way. I didn't know his name, rank or serial number.''
   ``I thought the committee spotlighting him was uncalled for. I
thought the committee by its grandstanding was damaging U.S.-Korean
relations,'' Derwinski said.
   Derwinski said that in his recent courtesy calls on members of
the Senate Veterans Affairs Committee, he found that ``basically,
they understand, if they put themselves in my shoes.''
   Derwinski acknowledged tipping off the Koreans in Foreign
Relations Committee testimony in 1983, when he was nominated to be
counselor to the State Department, a job he won after the redrawing
of his Illinois congressional district caused him to lose the House
seat he had held for 24 years.
   He later became an undersecretary for security assistance, the
post he held when chosen by President Bush to head the new Cabinet
department.
   The department will be created on March 15 out of the Veterans
Administration, a change long sought by veterans groups.
   In a speech Monday to the largest such group, the American
Legion, Derwinski warned against unrealistic expectations from the
change in status. ``We realize that with the budget problems facing
this administration, we're not going to be the priority group,'' he
said.
   Though medical officers of the VA have testified that their $10.8
billion budget for this year is $600 million to $1 billion short of
what is needed, Derwinski said after his speech that he did not
think he could get additional money this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
