<FIRST>r a PM-BoxOffice     02-28 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Box Office,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>`The 'burbs' Again Tops Box Office Gross</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The critically detested Tom Hanks film ``The
'burbs'' led the weekend box office charts again, and Oscar
nominations kept ``Rain Man,'' ``Dangerous Liaisons'' and ``Working
Girl'' in the top 10.
   ``The 'burbs,'' starring Hanks as a suburban home owner pushed to
the brink by unusual neighbors, collected $6 million to claim No. 1
for a second consecutive weekend.
   It was followed by ``Rain Man,'' the hit Dustin Hoffman-Tom
Cruise road drama, which has received eight Oscar nominations and
grossed $4.71 million for second place.
   In third was ``Bill and Ted's Excellent Adventure,'' a comedy
about two teen-age time travelers, with ticket sales of $4.66
million.
   ``Dangerous Liaisons,'' the drama about power-driven seductions
in pre-revolutionary France, moved up to No. 4 with $2.8 million.
The acclaimed movie, which has receved seven Oscar nominations,
played on more than twice as many screens as the previous week but
suffered a 58 percent drop in per-screen averages.
   ``Three Fugitives,'' featuring Nick Nolte and Martin Short as
outlaws on the lam with Short's young daughter in tow, finished in
fifth, grossing $2.7 million.
   It was followed by ``Beaches,'' starring Bette Midler and Barbara
Hershey, which collected $2.31 million. In seventh was ``Cousins,''
the romantic comedy with Ted Danson and Isabella Rossellini, with
$2.26 million.
   In eighth was the slimy sequel ``The Fly II,'' followed by the
corporate Cinderella story ``Working Girl,'' which has received six
Academy Award nominations, and the courtroom drama ``True Believer.''
   Here are the top movies for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor
Relations Inc., with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater
screens, average per screen, total gross and number of weeks in
release.
   1. ``The 'burbs,'' Universal, $6 million, 1,956 screens, $3,080
per screen, $18.9 million, two weeks.
   2. ``Rain Man,'' United Artists, $4.71 million, 1,590 screens,
$2,963 per screen, $116.6 million, 11 weeks.
   3. ``Bill and Ted's Excellent Adventure,'' Orion, $4.66 million,
1,228 screens, $3,793 per screen, $12 million, two weeks.
   4. ``Dangerous Liaisons,'' Warner Bros., $2.8 million, 762
screens, $3,727 per screen, $15.5 million, 10 weeks.
   5. ``Three Fugitives,'' Disney, $2.7 million, 1,354 screens,
$2,023 per screen, $29.6 million, five weeks.
   6. ``Beaches,'' Disney, $2.31 million, 1,057 screens, $2,187 per
screen, $38.9 million, 10 weeks.
   7. ``Cousins,'' Paramount, $2.26 million, 747 screens, $3,017 per
screen, $10.6 million, three weeks.
   8. ``The Fly II,'' 20th Century Fox, $2.1 million, 1,310 screens,
$1,572 per screen, $15.5 million, three weeks.
   9. ``Working Girl,'' 20th Century Fox, $1.9 million, 963 screens,
$1,926 per screen, $50.3 million, 10 weeks.
   10. ``True Believer,'' Columbia, $1.8 million, 895 screens,
$2,022 per screen, $5.4 million, three weeks.
</TEXT>
