<FIRST>r a PM-SpaceShuttle     02-28 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Space Shuttle,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Space Shuttle Discovery Could Be Launched Next Week</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Discovery could be ready for
launch as early as next week, but a high-priority military rocket
liftoff could bump the shuttle flight at least two days, officials
said.
   A decision on a shuttle launch date will be made Friday at the
conclusion of a flight readiness review.
   On Monday, Thomas Utsman, deputy director of the Kennedy Space
Center, said the center was ready for the Discovery flight, but his
statement did not give a launch date.
   Other officials said the launch target date of March 9 has not
changed.
   Sources, however, said the Air Force has scheduled a military
launch about that time and that it would have priority over a
shuttle launch for national security reasons.
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration relies heavily
on Air Force tracking facilities for a shuttle flight. Air Force
officials reportedly told space agency officials Monday they could
not support a Discovery launch before March 11, later if the
military launch is delayed on a day-by-day basis.
   The nature of the military launch was not disclosed, but there
are two flights being readied: the first submarine launch of the new
Trident 2 intercontinental range missile and a Delta rocket carrying
a payload for the Strategic Defense Initiative, or ``Star Wars,''
missile defense system.
   The conflict will have to be resolved at the Thursday-Friday
flight readiness review, during which top-level NASA managers will
examine all aspects of the shuttle mission.
   The Discovery launch had been scheduled for Feb. 23, but was
postponed after two tiny cracks were discovered in an oxygen
turbopump in one of Atlantis' main engines following a flight by
that shuttle in December.
   Because Discovery's three turbopumps went through the same
manufacturing process, NASA decided to replace them, delaying the
mission.
   Five astronauts, commanded by veteran shuttle flier Mike Coats,
are to deploy a large communications satellite and conduct medical
and technological experiments during Discovery's planned five days
in orbit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
