<FIRST>r i PM-MailedRevolver     02-28 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mailed Revolver,0195</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rightist Given 20 Months For Sending Revolver To Takeshita</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 44-year-old rightist was sentenced to 20 months in
prison today for mailing a revolver and bullet to Prime Minister
Noboru Takeshita to discourage him from running in party elections,
a court official said.
   Hideki Kashima, head of a rightist organization in Takamatsu,
southwestern Japan, was guilty of ``trying to sway the democratic
structure by forcing through his own political stance,'' the Tokyo
District Court said in handing down its verdict.
   Kashima was accused of mailing a parcel containing the firearms
and a leaflet criticizing Takeshita as a ``money-oriented
politician'' to his office in downtown Tokyo in September 1987.
   He was later arrested after investigators found his
organization's address on a separate letter sent earlier to
Takeshita's office.
   Kashima demanded that Takeshita, then secretary-general of the
governing liberal Democratic Party, not run for party president. In
Japan, the winner of the governing party's presidency also becomes
the prime minister.
   Takeshita, who became prime minister in October 1987, has
recently been plagued by a widening stock-profiteering scandal which
has toppled several ranking members in his administration.
</TEXT>
