<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     02-28 0932</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,930</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foreclosure Holdings Drop Slightly</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wave of bankruptcies and foreclosures that
engulfed thousands of financially troubled farmers during the
mid-1980s has left millions of acres in the hands of bankers,
insurance companies and other lenders, says an Agriculture
Department report.
   But the situation is slowly improving, according to the
department's Economic Research Service. As of mid-1988, about 7.93
million acres of farm property valued at $3.29 billion were held by
the primary lending groups, down from a peak of 8.98 million acres
and $3.59 billion on Dec. 30, 1987.
   The groups include the cooperative Farm Credit System, commercial
banks, Farmers Home Administration and life insurance companies.
   Lenders acquired much of the property through farm bankruptcies,
foreclosures or transfer of deed in lieu of foreclosure.
   ``The drop in lenders' property holdings reflects an improving
farm economy and rising land values,'' the report said. ``Earlier
fears that lenders would dump acquired farmland on already weak land
markets now appear unfounded. The drought last year probably had
little net effect on lenders' holdings.''
   One of the report's authors, economist Jerome Stam, said Monday
that he believed the decline in property holdings has continued but
that he had no idea what the figures might show by mid-1989.
   ``I'm not going out on a limb on that one,'' he said. ``But I
would like to think it would keep on going down.''
   Others who worked on the report include agency economists Gregory
Gajewski and Steven Koenig.
   Life insurance companies hold the most farmland, 4,125,000 acres
as of June 30, 1988, valued at more than $1.52 billion. The
companies surpassed the Farm Credit System, or FCS, in mid-1987 as
the largest holder of farm property.
   The holdings of the other major groups as of June 30, 1988,
included: FCS, 1,438,405 acres and a value of $706.1 million;
commercial banks, 882,300 acres and $428 million; FmHA, 1,487,845
acres and $628.6 million.
   Holdings by the FCS peaked at the end of 1986 at 2.7 million
acres worth about $1 billion.
   ``Most FCS institutions (which include federal land banks) have
been pursuing a more aggressive land sales strategy than the life
insurance companies,'' the report said.
   The four groups of lenders accounted for about 78 percent of the
$76.7 billion in farm real estate debt, excluding household debt, as
of Dec. 31, 1988. The remaining 22 percent was held by ``individuals
and others,'' including many who sold farms on contract or took a
mortgage as part of the sales agreement.
   Department economists said little is known about acquired or
reverted property held by this group.
   Comparatively, current farmland holdings are small compared with
those during the Great Depression. At the end of 1937, the top
lenders held about 28 million acres, compared with less than 9
million acres on Dec. 31, 1987.
   ``However, the runup in holdings during the 1980s took only a few
years,'' the report said. ``The Depression holdings grew throughout
the 1920s and 1930s.''
   Could sales of ``surplus'' farm property, including land and
buildings, be large enough to depress farmland prices?
   At the 1987 peak, lender holdings were equal to only 0.7 percent
of the total $550 billion value at that time, and represented only
0.9 percent of the roughly 1 billion acres in farms.
   But looked at another way, the lender-held property is larger in
terms of annual farmland sales. In the first quarter of 1987, lender
holdings were equivalent to about 24 percent of annual sales in
terms of acreage, and nearly 20 percent in terms of value.
   ``Lender holdings are large enough to overshadow other influences
on land prices,'' the report said. ``But sales of holdings have not
depressed prices because lenders do not sell all their holdings in
one year.''
   The life insurance companies, with their large holdings,
generally have been slow to sell, and attempts by the FmHA, an
agency of the Agriculture Department, have been hampered by Congress
and the courts. Nevertheless, the report added, the potential impact
of lender holdings is ``relatively greater'' in some regions.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department says China has been
authorized to buy an additional 2 million metric tons of U.S. wheat
at subsidized prices.
   Acting Undersecretary Richard W. Goldberg said Monday the wheat
will be available to China under the department's Export Enhancement
Program, or EEP. A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to
36.7 bushels of wheat.
   Under EEP arrangement, private exporters can sell U.S.
commodities at reduced prices in order to meet foreign competition
in selected overseas markets and then collect free government
surpluses of grain or other commodities as bonuses, or subsidies.
   The subsidies have ranged from less than $20 to more than $40 per
ton of wheat, or in the range of 54 cents to $1.09 per bushel.
   Under previous EEP authorizations, China has bought more than 7.4
million tons of wheat for delivery in 1988-89. Only 10,000 tons
remained in the previous authorization issued on Dec. 30.
   China is the biggest foreign customer of American wheat farmers
this year, and also expected to be the world's largest single
importer of wheat in 1988-89.
   According to USDA projections, China may import about 15 million
tons of wheat from all foreign sources, while the Soviet Union is
expected to import 13 million tons.
   The Soviets, as of Feb. 23, had bought about 3 million tons of
wheat from the United States, compared with the 7.4 million tons by
China. All the 1988-89 U.S. wheat sales to the Soviet Union and
China have been subsidized.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
