<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets 2ndLd-Writethru   02-28 0184</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Shares Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar gained substantially against the Japanese
yen Tuesday, while share prices plunged on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar opened at 127.00 yen and moved between 126.92 and
127.20 before closing at 127.15 yen, up 1.15 yen from Monday's
close. The dollar had declined a total of 1.15 yen on the three
previous trading days.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 166.72-point
loser Monday, lost another 300.17 points, or 0.94 percent, closing
at 31,985.60.
   Dealers said the dollar's firmness was due mainly to prevailing
sentiment of possible higher U.S. interest rates in the future.
   Last Friday, the U.S. Federal Reserve raised its discount rate,
its charge for loans to banks, from 6.5 percent to 7 percent due to
concern over inflation in the American economy.
   Higher U.S. interest rates tend to raise the value of the dollar.
   On the stock market, traders said the Nikkei index was weak
throughout the morning as institutional investors took a
wait-and-see position because of uncertainty over the trend of
interest rates abroad.
</TEXT>
