<FIRST>r w PM-Kids-Pesticides     02-28 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kids-Pesticides,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group to Sue for Lower Pesticide Levels in Fruits, Vegetables</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A private group says it will sue the
Environmental Protection Agency to make it tighten its pesticide
standards because current allowable levels in fruits and vegetables
pose a risk to preschool children.
   The group, the Natural Resources Defense Council, said in a
report released Monday that current standards fail to account for
the high amounts of fruits and vegetables children eat in proportion
to their weight.
   The study's findings were reported last week after a summary of
the two-year study became public. The group examined risks from the
use of eight cancer-causing pesticides on 27 fruits and vegetables.
   While no lawsuit has yet been filed, Al Meyerhoff, a lawyer for
the council, said the group plans to take the matter to court,
arguing that the EPA has failed to protect the public health of all
citizens.
   ``When the agency sets supposedly safe levels of pesticides in
food they ignore children,'' Meyerhoff said in an interview.
   The EPA has challenged the findings of the study.
   John Moore, acting deputy adminstrator, said last week the EPA
analysis on allowable toxicity levels of fruits and vegetables
already considers that children often consume large amounts of such
foods.
   The health threat to children also was disputed Monday by
representatives of the processed food industry, fruit and vegetable
industry, and chemical industry as well as some physicians.
   The National Food Processors Association said it routinely
conducts tests for pesticide residues in processed foods and has
always found them ``virtually non-existent in packaged foods and far
below allowable levels in the few cases when detected.''
   The group said that a recent examination of 17,843 samples of
processed fruits and vegetables showed 92 percent with no detectable
pesticide residues. It said another test of apple products showed _
with the exception of one sample with a low-level amount _ no trace
of the carcinogenic growth-regulator daminozide.
   But Robin Whyatt, an author of the council study, said the
group's findings suggest a health risk to children. She said the
findings are based on comparing government data showing consumption
of fruits and vegetables by preschool children and residue levels
that have been documented on such food products.
   The report said as many as 5,500 to 6,200 children among the
current preschool population ``may eventualy get cancer solely as a
result of their exposure before 6 years of age.'' This represents a
chance of 5 children in 20,000 getting cancer from such exposure,
250 times greater than the one in a million considered allowable by
the EPA in its risk analysis for the entire population.
   John McCarthy, vice president of the National Agricultural
Chemicals Association, called the NRDC study misleading and said it
was based on a ``worst-case scenario that does not represent real
world experience.''
   ``The chemicals in question have been widely used for more than
25 years yet available data show that the incidence of cancers that
could be attributed to overexposure to chemicals in the food supply
is not increasing,'' McCarthy said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890228-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 0302EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-IndianInvestigation     02-28 0618</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Indian Investigation,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tribal Leaders Don't Want BIA Abolished Yet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three tribal leaders told a Senate panel that
the Bureau of Indian Affairs still has a role to play despite
charges of neglect and corruption aired in a series of hearings.
   ``If your car quits running you don't discard it, you fix it,''
John Taylor, chief of the Eastern Band of Cherokee, told a special
investigative unit of the Senate Select Committee on Indian Affairs
on Monday.
   The tribal leaders were asked at the conclusion of the round of
hearings whether the bureau should be abolished.
   Taylor, whose tribe lives in the mountains of North Carolina,
said he is proud of his tribe's economic self-sufficiency, but he
doesn't think all tribes could survive without the BIA. ``We can
make the BIA accountable,'' he said.
   The bureau came under heavy criticism as the committee looked
into contracting fraud and child abuse on Indian reservations, and
organized crime infiltration into legal Indian gambling operations
such as bingo.
   BIA witnesses who testified since the hearings began Jan. 30
generally showed little knowledge of the problems, or admitted
failing to act quickly when abuse was revealed.
   Ivan L. Sidney, chairman of the Hopi tribe in Arizona, said he
believes the BIA will someday be unnecessary, ``whether it be next
year, 10 years 20 years.''
   But he said as the tribes work toward total sovereignty, they
must continue to work with the federal government.
   ``Our relationship is with the federal government, not with the
states,'' Sidney said. ``I believe a special assistant to the
president will assist us in the effort to minimize the BIA's role.''
   Last week, the three senators who comprise the special committee
asked President Bush to put a staff person in the White House in
charge of Indian affairs. There has been no response yet.
   ``I think there needs to be a presence because of our
relationship with the U.S. government,'' said John Washakie, chief
of the Shoshone and Arapho tribes in Wyoming. But he said it could
be minimized.
   In closing the session, Sen. Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz., who
chairs the committee, called the hearings on child sexual abuse ``a
case study on the shortcomings of the BIA and the IHS (Indian Health
Service).''
   ``The BIA has been grossly negligent in protecting the resource
that American Indians care about most deeply _ their families,''
DeConcini said.
   DeConcini said that he and his fellow committee members, Sens.
Thomas Daschle, D-S.D., and John McCain, R-Ariz., agree that
``increased accountability is the key to strengthening Indian
self-determination.''
   William Ragsdale, acting head of the Bureau of Indian Affairs,
told the committee he is sending a letter of apology from the
Department of Interior to the Hopi tribe and any others whose
children were sexually abused by BIA employees.
   Ragsdale said Monday that the insensitivity of some school
officials to parents whose children had been molested was
``inexcusable.''
   ``I started my career in the Indian bureau as a school teacher,''
said Ragsdale. ``It is difficult for me to understand why our system
totally broke down.''
   Ragsdale said that part of the breakdown in the BIA school system
could be blamed on Congress. He referred to a law which changed the
organizational structure of the BIA, and required that the 115 or
120 BIA schools across the country report directly to Washington.
   ``That's too much of a span of control for anyone to handle,'' he
said.
   DeConcini said that over the next few months, the special
committee will continue its probe into other aspects of Indian
affairs, including natural resource management, the Indian Health
Service, management trust funds, Indian education and HUD Indian
housing programs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
