<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     02-28 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>FCC Eases Requirements for Phone-Installation Help</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has decided to make it easier
for low-income people to qualify for subsidized telephone service.
   The Federal Communications Commission decided Monday that
low-income applicants for subsidized telephone service no longer
will have to show they've had no phone for the previous three months
or that they've received no federal phone aid for two years.
   The FCC said those requirements for ``Link Up America'' aid were
denying service to 15 percent of all applicants.
   The year-old federal assistance plan is designed to encourage
low-income households to get telephone service by helping pay for
installation.
   Qualifying households may receive up to $30 to help defray such
costs.
   Gerald Brock, chief of the FCC's common carrier bureau, said
there were 385,000 people in 37 states, the District of Columbia and
Puerto Rico in the program.
   Brock said the commission decided to loosen the requirements when
it was shown it would not cost the government very much.
   ``We are finding that it has been an effective program but it has
not been so well used that the financial requirements were
overwhelming,'' Brock told reporters.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Medicine Guidelines Issued by FDA</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Food and Drug Administration has issued
standards for expectorants in nonprescription cough-cold medicines
that allow only one proven active ingredient to remain on the market.
   Guaifenesin was the only ingredient found by the FDA to be safe
and effective in increasing sputum or phlegm volume and making it
easier to cough up.
   It is the most widely used active ingredient used in expectorants
and is contained in the major brands of cough-cold medicines, the
FDA said.
   About 20 other expectorant ingredients were found not to be
useful and products using these ingredients will have to be
reformulated or taken off the market within one year. The FDA said
eight products listed in the Handbook of Nonprescription Drugs would
fall into this category.
   Among the 20 ingredients are ammonium chloride, a plant extract
called horehound, pine tar, spirits of turpentine and squill, the
dried inner scales of a flowering plant.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Breakthrough in GATT Stalemate Seen by Australian</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Community should break its
deadlock over eliminating farm trade barriers, in response to a
softened U.S. position on the issue, an Australian official says.
   When global trade talks resume in April, the United States will
be prepared to discuss short-term agricultural trade reforms short
of its goal of eliminating all barriers by the end of the century,
Michael John Duffy, Australian minister for trade negotiations, said
after meeting U.S. officials.
   This means that ``the United States has put the ball very much in
the European Community's court,'' he added. ``They haven't hit it
hard yet, but they're having a good look at it.''
   ``I am generally more hopeful than I have been in the past 19
months because the U.S. has now made it possible'' for realistic
negotiations to take place in the ongoing Uruguay Round of GATT, the
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, he said.
</TEXT>
