<FIRST>r i PM-Hirohito-Radicals     02-28 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hirohito-Radicals,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radicals Claim Responsibility for Funeral Day Explosion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An ultra-leftist group claimed today it planted the
bomb that exploded on a highway embankment shortly before Emperor
Hirohito's funeral procession passed, according to a member of an
affiliated group.
   ``We received a communique today from the Revolutionary Army,
saying that they had set the explosion,'' a member of the Kakurokyo,
or Revolutionary Workers Association, told The Associated Press.
   He quoted the communique as saying: ``We carried out the
revolutionary ... offensive to directly attack the funeral
motorcade.''
   The group also threatened to conduct similar attacks on other
events related to the accession of Hirohito's son, Emperor Akihito,
he said. Such events are expected to continue for more than a year.
   The blast Friday occurred about 20 minutes before the motorcade
passed the site in Chofu, west central Tokyo.
   The bomb, hidden in the embankment, scattered mud and debris on
the pavement. No injuries were reported, and workers hurriedly
cleared the debris.
   Members of the imperial family, police escorts and the hearse
carrying Hirohito's body were in the 30-car motorcade that passed
the blast area without stopping en route to the imperial burial site
in Tokyo's western suburbs.
   The radical said the Revolutionary Army is closely affiliated
with Kakurokyo, believed to be Japan's second-largest ultra-leftist
group. He refused to elaborate.
   Police estimate Kakurokyo membership to be in the hundreds.
   Meanwhile, police said today that leaflets claiming
responsibility for the blast in the name of the Revolutionary Army
were distributed by radicals at universities in the Tokyo area.
</TEXT>
