<FIRST>r a PM-Mandela     02-28 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mandela,0485</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Winnie Mandela Reportedly Initiated Attacks on Three Men</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Winnie Mandela personally initiated an attack
on four young men in her home, using her fists and a rawhide whip to
beat them, including a teen-ager who later died, the surviors
reportedly said in affidavits.
   According to sources who have seen the men's affidavits, Mrs.
Mandela's live-in bodyguards _ known as the Mandela United soccer
club _ then attacked them with whips and bottles and throwing them
against the walls, the Los Angeles Times reported today.
   Mrs. Mandela, wife of jailed African National Congress leader
Nelson Mandela, has denied knowledge of the death of 14-year-old
Stompie Mokhetsi Seipei. The Times said she refused requests for
interviews.
   The Times said none of the three men making the affidavits claim
to have been seriously injured by Mrs. Mandela's attacks, although
they are said to still have scars and other marks from the alleged
beatings meted out by the bodyguards.
   The newspaper quoted the sources as saying affidavits also show
Seipei was suspended by his feet and repeatedly dropped on his head.
   He was taken from the house by the bodyguards two days later. His
body, beaten beyond recognition and stabbed twice, was found in a
field on Jan. 7.
   The graphic descriptions of the night of Dec. 29, when the four
blacks were allegedly abducted from a Methodist church hostel in
Soweto and held at Mrs. Mandela's home, are contained in the sworn
statements the surviving men made to their attorney.
   Details of the affidavits were obtained by the Times from sources
in the anti-apartheid movement familiar with the statements and the
efforts of civic leaders to win the men's freedom. The sources spoke
on condition of anonymity, the Times said.
   The allegation that Mrs. Mandela whipped the four and instigated
the beatings has been reported previously, including on Feb. 12, by
the South African newspaper The Sunday Star, which did not identify
its sources.
   Geoff Budlender, the attorney for the three men, has said they
told him in affidavits that Mrs. Mandela was involved in the events
on the night they were abducted and beaten. He has refused to give
more details or release the affidavits. He said today he did not
know the source of the Times' story.
   Five people have been charged in connection with the death.
Police said the investigation is continuing.
   According to the Times, the affidavits show Seipei and the three
men, ages 20, 20 and 29, were kidnapped and taken to Mrs. Mandela's
large home in Diepkloof Extension, a well-to-do Soweto neighborhood.
   At the house, they reported, Mrs. Mandela punched and used a whip
to hit Seipei and the oldest man, the Times said.
   She demanded that Seipei admit to being a police informant, but
he refused, the Times said.
</TEXT>
