<FIRST>r a PM-HospitalComplaint     02-28 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hospital Complaint,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Files Complaint Against Hospital Over Patient's Treatment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city's ambulance service has filed a criminal
complaint against a hospital for allegedly failing to treat an
89-year-old woman who died 17 minutes after she was brought to the
emergency room, a spokeswoman said.
   Clara Dickson was brought to the private Montefiore Hospital in
the city's Bronx borough Sunday afternoon and went into cardiac
arrest.
   Lynn Schulman, a spokeswoman for the city's Emergency Medical
Service, said Dickson was not given quick help, even though
paramedics ``told an emergency room nurse they had a patient in
critical and worsening condition.''
   ``Apparently, there was some kind of a dispute between the
hospital staff and EMS about whether or not they were going to take
the woman,'' said a police spokesman, Sgt. Edward Burns.
   Schulman said EMS filed a complaint against the hospital with the
state Health Department and a criminal complaint with the Police
Department. Both agencies are investigating the complaint.
   A hospital spokesman disputed the charges, stating that Dickson
was treated ``immediately.''
   ``We believe our treatment was aggressive, speedy and
appropriate,'' said the spokesman, Fred Yaeger.
</TEXT>
