<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 0557EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-HanfordCleanup     02-28 0599</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hanford Cleanup,0620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Praise For Nuclear Weapons Site Cleanup Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHLAND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Environmentalists, workers and lawmakers
welcomed an agreement to clean up the nation's most contaminated
nuclear weapons production site but said they would have to fight
for the billions of dollars needed to do the job.
   State and federal officials at a Washington, D.C., signing
ceremony Monday said the landmark agreement will provide a ``clear
road map'' for cleaning up the 570-square-mile Hanford nuclear
reservation and serve as a model for other Energy Department weapons
plants.
   ``It's an amiable agreement which is long overdue,'' said Mike
Fox, head of The Hanford Family, a group of about 300 Hanford
workers, relatives and supporters.
   Under the agreement, the department has promised to seek $2.8
billion for the cleanup over five years, but the appropriation has
yet to be endorsed by the Bush administration's Office of Management
and Budget and submitted to Congress for approval.
   After five years, the agreement calls for the state and the
Energy Department to come up with additional requests to finance
continued cleanup, which the department estimates could cost $57
billion.
   ``The cost ... means we need to win $1.9 billion per year in this
era of budget deficit-fighting in order for this agreement to clean
up Hanford within 30 years,'' said Gerald Pollett, who has been
lobbying for a cleanup on behalf of Heart of America Northwest.
   ``We are still going to have to fight for these funds,'' said
Rep. Les AuCoin, D-Ore., a member of the House Appropriations
Committee.
   Key provisions of the 300-page agreement include:
   _ An accelerated program for cleaning up Hanford over 30 years,
rather than 50 years as originally envisioned.
   _ Specific cleanup milestones, with fines against the Energy
Department of up to $10,000 a week if it fails to meet the goals.
   _ Clear delineation of duties between the state, the Energy
Department and the federal Environmental Protection Agency.
   _ Justice Department agreement to allow enforcement through
lawsuits filed by the state or private parties.
   The federal government also agreed to provide the state with $2.9
million during the next three years to pay for monitoring.
   The agreement followed more than a year of negotiations and state
threats to go to court if the talks failed.
   The Energy Department released documents estimating that 5
billion cubic yards of hazardous solid and liquid wastes, both
radioactive and toxic, have been dumped at Hanford, which straddles
the Columbia River about 150 miles southeast of Seattle.
   The documents said ``above-background concentrations'' of
substances such as tritium, Iodine-129, uranium and cyanide have
been found in groundwater beneath Hanford and may threaten the
river. It also said releases of hazardous compounds continue.
   Tim Connor of the Hanford Education Action League of Spokane
welcomed the agreement but said it ``does nothing to expedite the
ending of liquid radioactive waste discharges directly into the
ground at Hanford.'' He said his group might sue to stop the
discharges.
   Besides being the most contaminated of the Energy Department's 16
nuclear weapons production sites, the Hanford reservation is
expected to be the most costly to clean up and take the longest.
   The site contains more than 60 percent of the nation's high-level
radioactive waste generated by weapons programs dating to World War
II.
   Scientists at the reservation worked on the bomb that was dropped
at Nagasaki. In the 1950s, Hanford was one of the largest weapon's
production complexes.
   At present, only one commercial nuclear power plant is operating
at the reservation and the department has announced plans to phase
out all weapons production at the site.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
