<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Silver     02-28 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Silver,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Veteran Character Actor Dies at 66</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Character actor Joe Silver, who appeared in more
than 1,000 TV shows and whose Broadway career spanned almost 50
years from ``Tobacco Road'' to ``Legs Diamond,'' has died at age 66.
   He died Monday of cancer.
   Silver made his Broadway debut in 1942 in ``Tobacco Road'' and
later appeared in New York in such shows as ``Gypsy'' (1959), ``The
Zulu and the Zayda'' (1965), ``You Know I Can't Hear You When the
Water's Running'' (1967) and ``Lenny'' (1971).
   In ``Lenny,'' the story of comedian Lenny Bruce, Silver played
nine roles and was nominated for a Tony award for best supporting
actor.
   The actor also appeared in more than 1,000 television shows
beginning in 1947 as a panelist on ``What's It Worth?'' He also was
in Red Buttons' television series in the early 1950s and in ``Fay''
with Lee Grant on NBC.
   His films included ``Switching Channels,'' ``The Gig,'' ``Almost
You,'' ``Rhinoceros'' and ``The Apprenticeship of Duddy Kravitz.''
   Silver also had widespread credits off-Broadway, starring most
recently in ``Old Business'' at the New York Shakespeare Festival
Public Theater.
   He was a regular at the Burt Reynolds Jupiter Theater in Florida,
starring in ``I'm Not Rappaport'' and ``Teahouse of the August
Moon.''
   Silver's last stage role was as gangster Arnold Rothstein in
``Legs Diamond,'' the Peter Allen musical that closed Feb. 19 after
a short run.
   He is survived by his wife, actress Chevi Colton, a son,
Christopher, and a daughter, Jennifer, all of New York.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
