<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     02-28 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0558</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rain, Snow Continue in Southeast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow fell in parts of the Appalachians early today and heavy
rains soaked Alabama, flooding some roads.
   The heaviest snow accumulations were in the Blue Ridge Mountains
of Virginia and North Carolina and in north central Tennessee, where
up to 8 inches fell.
   Snow also fell from North Dakota to Wisconsin, with 2 inches
recorded at Minneapolis and 4 inches on the ground at Little Falls,
Minn.
   Showers and thunderstorms extended from central Louisiana across
the Tennessee Valley into North Carolina, where more than 1\ inches
of rain fell in Rowan County.
   Heavy rains flooded some roads in Morgan County, Ala., and a
flash flood watch remained in effect from the west central to the
northeast part of the state.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 1 a.m. EST
included nearly 1} inches at Columbus, Miss., Air Force Base and
1.36 inches at Tuscaloosa, Ala.
   Temperatures early this morning were in the single digits and
teens over the northern Rockies, the northern Plains, the upper
Mississippi Valley, the upper Great Lakes and New England.
   Temperatures were in the 50s and 60s over the Gulf Coast region,
Florida, the southern Atlantic Coast, Southern California and
southwest Arizona.
   Today's forecast called for snow over the northern Rockies, the
northern Plains, and much of the Great Lakes and Ohio Valley.
Showers and some thunderstorms were expected to prevail from the
lower Mississippi Valley to the Carolinas and the middle Atlantic
states, and over the Pacific Northwest. Fair to partly sunny skies
were forecast across much of the rest of the nation.
   High temperatures were to remain in the single digits and teens
from the northern Rockies across North Dakota and the upper
Mississippi Valley to western Upper Michigan; in the 20s and 30s in
the northern Plateau, across South Dakota and the central Plains,
much of the middle Mississippi Valley, the Great Lakes, the Ohio
Valley and the northern Pacific Coast; in the 60s and 70s from
central and Southern California across the southern Plateau, the
southern Rockies, much of southern Texas, the Gulf Coast region,
Florida and the southern Atlantic Coast; and in the 80s over the
Desert Southwest and south central Texas. Much of the remainder of
the nation was to have highs in the 40s and 50s.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 5
degrees below zero at Marquette, Mich., to 74 degrees at Key West,
Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 48 rain; Boston 28 fair; Buffalo 19 snow;
Charleston, S.C., 62 cloudy; Cincinnati 26 foggy; Cleveland 22
cloudy; Detroit 21 partly cloudy; Miami 70 cloudy; New York 29 fair;
Philadelphia 31 fair; Pittsburgh 18 foggy; Portland, Maine, 16 fair;
Washington 37 cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 8 snow; Chicago 19 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 44
cloudy; Denver 28 snow; Des Moines 24 fair; Indianapolis 23 fair;
Kansas City 30 cloudy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 14 snow; Nashville 31
partly cloudy; New Orleans 67 partly cloudy; St. Louis 28 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 33 fair; Anchorage 22 fair; Las Vegas 53 fair;
Los Angeles 55 foggy; Phoenix 64 fair; Salt Lake City 36 cloudy; San
Diego 57 cloudy; San Francisco 47 windy;
   _Canada: Montreal 16 fair; Toronto 5 fair.
</TEXT>
