<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 0718EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--SpeechDemons     02-28 0157</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Speech Demons,0160</SECOND>
<HEAD>Schools Chancellor Plans To Purge `Axe' and `Youse'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city's schools chancellor is declaring war on
bad speech with an edict to students: Don't ``youse'' guys ``axe''
any questions.
   In a memo to Mayor Edward I. Koch released Monday, Chancellor
Richard Green singled out 20 ``speech demons'' _ incorrect phrases
or pronunciations, some of them New Yorkers' own creations _ that he
means to eliminate from students' conversation.
   To wit: ``axe'' instead of ``ask,'' ``youse'' instead of ``you''
and ``he be'' instead of ``he is.'' Green's list also includes
``liberry'' instead of ``library'' _ an error Koch has acknowledged
making himself.
   ``Superb,'' pronounced the mayor, who has been nudging the
chancellor for some time to do something about the way students
speak.
   Green also plans to declare a Putting Your Best Speech Forward
Day and said he will convene educators in April to come up with a
long-term program.
</TEXT>
