<FIRST>r a PM-Marcos-Condominium     02-28 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marcos-Condominium,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marcos-Linked Condo Sold for $3.7 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Philippine government has sold for $3.7
million a Manhattan condominium said to have been owned by deposed
President Ferdinand Marcos, and it is seeking buyers for two other
properties.
   The seven-bedroom apartment on the 43rd floor of the Olympic
Towers, a glass tower next to St. Patrick's Cathedral on Fifth
Avenue, was sold Monday to an unidentified buyer, said Teresa Roxas,
spokeswoman for the Philippine Commission on Good Government.
   The property was surrendered to the Philippine government in 1986
by a Marcos associate, Antonio Floirendo, as part of a deal to avoid
prosecution.
   The condominium was among holdings allegedly purchased with some
of the $10 billion that the Philippine government claims Marcos and
his associates stole from the nation's treasury before he was ousted
and fled to Hawaii in 1986.
   Marcos' wife, Imelda, has pleaded innocent in New York to federal
racketeering charges and is free on $5 million bail. Lawyers have
argued that Marcos, 71, is too ill to appear in court. He is
hospitalized in Honolulu.
   The commission also is looking for buyers for the $4.5 million
Lindenmere estate on New York's Long Island and a $2.5 million home
in Honolulu. Both of them, like the condominium, allegedly were
owned by Marcos through fronts.
   The commission also is fighting in court to gain title to four
commercial buildings in Manhattan worth an estimated $400 million,
Roxas said.
   The condominium was the second piece of Marcos-linked real estate
in the United States sold by the commission. A home in Princeton,
N.J., sold in 1987 for $1 million.
   Nievelena Rosete, a commission member in Manila, said profits
from the sale will help finance the government's land reform program.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
