<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 0855EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-HazardousWaste     02-28 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hazardous Waste,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ban On Hazardous Waste From Other States Takes Effect Soon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRIP DuBARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than half the states may be barred
beginning Wednesday from burying hazardous waste in South Carolina
unless they supply information on their own disposal laws, officials
say.
   Gov. Carroll Campbell, who set the March 1 deadline in January,
said states would have to certify that they had no impediments to
disposal within their borders, or that the repeal of such
impediments was imminent, to be allowed to continue sending their
waste to South Carolina.
   The order affects South Carolina's GSX landfill, which holds
close to a billion pounds of hazardous waste, about 70 percent from
out of state. Some 33 states, Puerto Rico and the District of
Columbia used the facility in 1987.
   State environmental officials sent letters to all 50 states and
Puerto Rico, informing them of Campbell's order. By Monday
afternoon, only 23 states had responded.
   ``Our policy has to be flexible enough to work with a state that
is genuinely moving to eliminate prohibitions,'' Campbell said
Monday. But, he said, ``I look for us to reach a point where there
will be some states that will be cut off.''
   Campbell said he hoped to see regional agreements that eliminated
impediments to waste treatment or burial and arrangements where one
state might handle a material that another state doesn't.
   ``The question is do you have a fair load sharing. That's the
kind of fairness we're looking for in this area,'' he said.
   Nine states _ North Carolina, Florida, Massachusetts, Rhode
Island, Pennsylvania, New Jersey, Kentucky, Louisiana and Kansas _
accounted for about 40 percent of the waste going to GSX, officials
said.
   Hartsill Truesdale, head of the Department of Health and
Environmental Control's hazardous waste divison, would not say which
states had replied.
   GSX is one of only two commercial hazardous waste landfills in
the Southeast and accepts roughly 135,000 tons of chemical garbage
annually. The other landfill is in Alabama.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
