<FIRST>r a PM-Lukens     02-28 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lukens,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lukens Says He was `Set Up'; Predicts Exoneration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES HANNAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENVILLE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. Donald Lukens denied having sex
with a teen-ager and said she set him up and asked him for money.
   The conservative Republican appeared publicly Monday in his
mostly rural district for the first time since the allegations
surfaced a month ago. He met with constituents at his office here
and gave several interviews.
   ``I was approached for money on the basis of the general
allegation,'' Lukens said. ``I said, `Hey, I'm not going to pay any
money. Nothing happened.'''
   A grand jury last week indicted the 58-year-old congressman on a
misdemeanor charge of contributing to the delinquency of a child by
having sex with the girl in November, when she was 16. The offense
carries up to six months in jail and a $1,000 fine.
   Lukens, who is divorced, did not deny he knew the girl and said
he met with her on occasion.
   ``Did you have sex with (the girl)?'' he was asked in an
interview with Dayton TV station WDTN.
   ``No,'' Lukens replied.
   Lukens told the Dayton Daily News the girl approached him on more
than one occasion for money and that she threatened to go to police
and the news media.
   ``I believe that I was set up, and I know for a fact because I
was the person they asked for money,'' Lukens said in an interview
with The Associated Press.
   He vowed to complete his fourth term, which expires in 1990.
``The last reason I would ever think about resigning is because the
press wanted me to,'' he said.
   Columbus TV station WSYX secretly videotaped a meeting with Anna
Coffman at a fast-food restaurant in November in which she asked why
Lukens was ``messin' around'' with her daughter. Lukens told the
woman he thought her daughter was an adult, according to the
videotape, in which he also apparently offered the woman a job.
   The FBI said it found no evidence of bribery or extortion.
   The videotape was broadast Feb. 1.
   ``I didn't do it,'' Lukens told constituents during the office
meeting Monday. ``I'm going to be found innocent.''
</TEXT>
