<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 0940EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-NightStalker     02-28 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Night Stalker,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyer's Stress Illness Threatens `Night Stalker' Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The murder trial of ``Night Stalker''
defendant Richard Ramirez may be aborted because his attorney is
suffering from nervous exhaustion after working on the case for 3{
years, a prosecutor said.
   Superior Court Judge Michael Tynan disclosed Monday that a doctor
has recommended psychological counseling for defense attorney Daniel
Hernandez. The physician said the lawyer needs four to six weeks off
to recover.
   ``The doctor feels he is not presently able to function
effectively as trial counsel,'' said Tynan, who would not disclose
the doctor's name.
   Testimony in the case began Jan. 30 after six months of jury
selection.
   ``Probably the chances of a mistrial are good,'' Deputy District
Attorney P. Philip Halpin told reporters. ``We can't keep this jury
hanging around indefinitely.''
   The judge scheduled a hearing on Hernandez' health for Wednesday
and ordered the lawyer to appear along with his co-counsel, Arturo
Hernandez, who is no relation.
   Arturo Hernandez left the trial without public explanation during
jury selection. Halpin said it was unlikely that he would be ordered
to take over for his ailing colleague.
   Ramirez, a 28-year-old drifter from El Paso, Texas, is charged
with 13 murders and 30 related felonies in grisly nighttime attacks
that terrorized Southern California in the summer of 1985.
   The press dubbed the killer, who often left behind drawings
associated with devil worship, the ``Night Stalker.''
   The cost of the case to Los Angeles County so far was not
available, but as of July it was $1.28 million in court and
investigatory fees, not including the $15,000 a month it cost to
keep Ramirez in a private jail cell.
</TEXT>
