<HEAD>More Than 200 Fires Burn in Parched Florida Grasslands</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 8 grafs to UPDATE firefighting effort, arson determination,
power lines back on; PICKS UP 13th graf pvs, `In 1985 ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 200 fires have contributed to the deaths
of two firefighters, forced the temporary shutdown of a major power
line and scorched more than 6,000 drought-parched acres of brushland
across Florida.
   Wind of 10 to 25 mph Monday hampered hundreds of firefighters
trying to cope with the consequences of the months-long dry spell,
officials said.
   ``This is one of the worst years that I've seen, and we still
have a lot of dry months ahead of us,'' said David Utley, a state
forestry duty officer.
   The largest blaze was burning out of control today in the
Everglades west of Fort Lauderdale after blackening 2,700 acres
Monday and threatening power lines carrying electricity to South
Florida.
   At 8 a.m., a wall of fire 5{ miles long was heading away from
power lines and toward a highway, which firefighters hoped would act
as a fire break, officials said.
   Authorities have determined the blaze was set, said state
firefighter Michael Greenstein, adding that it began deep inside the
Everglades.
   ``There's just too much of the grasslands in the state'' to let
the fire burn itself out, said Jim Whitson, state forestry officer
in charge of the 400 foresters who have coordinated the battle
against the more than 200 fires since Sunday.
   Two volunteer firefighters who had just arrived at a grass fire
in the median of Interstate 75 in central Florida were killed when a
tractor-trailer slammed into their smoke-obscured pickup truck, the
Highway Patrol said.
   The deaths were the first by firefighters battling a wildfire in
Florida in more than four years, officials said.
   Three 500,000-volt transmission lines owned by Florida Power &amp;
Light were turned off when about 10 miles of lines were threatened
by fire near the Palm Beach-Broward County line, Utley said. ``We
had a helicopter up in the air dropping water on it and we had no
success whatsoever,'' he said.
   All three power lines were turned back on when the blaze died
down Monday night, and no blackouts were reported, said Stacey Shaw,
a utility spokeswoman.
   In 1985, an Everglades fire burned power lines and caused
blackouts from Lake Okeechobee to the Florida Keys, she said.
   Fires also covered 1,100-acres in Palm Beach County and 800 acres
near Fort Myers on the Gulf coast, Whitson said. A 500-acre brush
fire near Palatka in northern Florida forced the evacuation of
nearly 200 people for several hours and closed a highway Sunday.
   Showers may bring some relief to Central Florida on Thursday and
thunderstorms were expected Saturday for the northern two-thirds of
the state. No rain was in sight for South Florida through the
weekend.
   Most of the state has received only about half the normal
rainfall since November, the beginning of the six-month dry season.
The Miami area has received 7.5 inches of rain since September,
compared with an average rainfall of 24 inches for that period, the
weather service said.
</TEXT>
