<FIRST>r a PM-BostonSchoolDeseg 1stLd-Writethru a0493 02-28 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boston School Deseg, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0493,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plan Adopted, But Vote Follows Racial Lines</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with blacks threatening lawsuit over new
plan, background on busing order.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A racially divided Boston School Committee has
adopted a plan allowing parents to choose the schools their children
attend, but blacks vowed to fight it, charging it will mean
resegregation of the city's schools.
   The nine whites on the committee voted for the plan Monday night.
The four blacks voted against, and one of them, John O'Bryant, said,
``We're going to end up where we were _ in court.''
   Opponents said it may resegregate schools. Supporters said
resegregation is not an issue because less than 25 percent of the
system's 55,000 students are white.
   U.S. District Judge W. Arthur Garrity Jr. ordered Boston's
schools desegregated in 1974, resulting in many students being bused
outside their neighborhoods to achieve racial balance. The busing
resulted in violent protests by whites.
   Garrity relinquished control over the nation's oldest school
system in 1985, but the busing plan has remained in effect.
   The new plan divides the city into three zones, each designed to
include people of all backgrounds.
   Parents will be given a choice of schools within the zone in
which they live, and will get their choice unless it causes
overcrowding or upsets a school's racial balance.
   The plan calls for all schools to reflect the racial breakdown in
its zone.
   Black members of the School Committee threatened to file a
federal lawsuit to block the plan.
   The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People,
the main plaintiff in the 1974 desegregation case, said the plan
does not ensure that schools will improve.
   Louis Elisa, vice president of the Boston chapter of the NAACP,
called the plan ``the moral equivalent of a cheap coat of paint on
an old, rusted, broken-down car of segregation.''
   ``The car cannot move forward, and the paint will not last,'' he
said.
   School Committeeman Daniel Burke said, ``This plan is no panacea,
but it's a start.'' Charles Willie, a consultant hired by Mayor
Raymond L. Flynn to draft a student assignment plan, said it is
``light years ahead of what we have now.''
   The plan becomes effective in September for students entering
kindergarten through grade 6, and the following September for other
students.
   The original busing order was prompted by a lawsuit filed by
black parents. Garrity had found that the School Committee was
operating an unconstitutional, segregated system, with black
students often going to inferior schools.
</TEXT>
