<FIRST>r w PM-WaterDanger     02-28 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Water Danger,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Weather Service Assesses Chances of Droughts, Floods</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drought poses a serious threat for California
and the next month or two could be crucial to the state's water
picture, the National Weather Service reported today.
   The snowpack in California is well below normal, posing the
potential for significant water supply problems in the state this
summer, said Dr. Michael D. Hudlow, director of hydrology for the
weather service.
   The potential for drought also exists in the Missouri Valley, in
the Boston and New York metropolitan areas and in the Delaware River
Basin, Hudlow said.
   On the other hand, saturated soils pose the danger of severe
flooding in the Ohio and Mississippi valleys, he warned.
   In addition there is a danger of snowmelt flooding in the
northernmost portions of North Dakota, Wisconsin and Minnesota, the
Upper Peninsula of Michigan and in northernmost New York and New
England, Hudlow said.
   But the spring flood and water supply report from the weather
service singled out California as the region for the greatest
concern because of the low mountain snowpack, the source of the
majority of the state's water supply.
   A continued drought in California this summer would bring the
state its third consecutive dry year, Hudlow said. That has not
occurred before in this century.
   There was some good news included in the report, however, with
the 30- and 90-day forecasts giving California a slightly above
normal chance of precipitation in the coming months.
</TEXT>
