<SECOND>PM-Tenn Bingo,0181</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tennessee Supreme Court Outlaws Bingo Games</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tennessee Supreme Court has outlawed
charity bingo, dealing a setback to churches, veterans organizations
and other groups.
   The high court Monday said that the state Constitution bars the
Legislature from authorizing lotteries and that bingo _ for charity
or any other reason _ is a lottery.
   State Sen. Steve Cohen said he will push a bill to let voters
remove the section of the Constitution.
   Charitable bingo first was authorized in 1973, the Supreme Court
said.
   Secretary of State Gentry Crowell began a crackdown in 1987 on
what he contended were violations of bingo regulations, citing a
study that concluded only about 2 percent of the $44.7 million taken
in in 1986 could be traced to charity.
   ``I wouldn't anticipate that there will be enforcement at this
point,'' Nashville District Attorney Torry Johnson said of teh
ruling.
   ``I think it will take some time for the state attorney general's
office to review the opinion and recommend what steps must be
taken.''
