<FIRST>r w PM-DC-Guns 1stLd-Writethru a0520 02-28 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DC-Guns, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0520,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mandatory Prison Terms Proposed for Criminals Who Use Guns</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 5 grafs new with official saying council needs more time
to study proposal. Picks up 5th graf pvs, The proposal comes.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The District of Columbia City Council needs
more time to study a proposal by Mayor Marion Barry Jr. requiring
five-year prison terms for criminals who use guns to commit crimes,
the council president said today.
   However, Council President David Clarke left open the possibility
that the legislation could be passed as early as Wednesday in a
special session.
   Barry's proposal would toughen the city's current misdemeanor gun
law. It includes a maximum penalty of one year in jail and a $1,000
fine for those caught with unregistered weapons. Barry wants the
city to pass the legislation on an emergency basis.
   ``We're not going to let these gun-carrying thugs, dope dealers,
scourge of the earth...feel that because we have some difficulties
in our jail population, that there's no room,'' Barry told a
citizens group Monday night. ``We will find room _ find places for
them to stay in jail.''
   At a news conference earlier, Barry said the city is starting
``an all-out assault on weapons.''
   The proposal comes as the city struggles to slow the pace of
drug-related killings in Washington. Police blame about 60 percent
of last year's record 372 killings on drugs. So far in 1989, 90
people have been killed in the district, 36 more than at the same
time last year.
   The city's prison system is operating under court orders
requiring a reduction in overcrowding. Inmates have been sent to
several states to help alleviate the overcrowding.
   Barry's bill also proposes redefining the city's bail laws so
that those caught carrying an unregistered weapon, selling drugs or
using a weapon in an assault could be denied pre-trial release.
   Barry also wants to create a ``drug-free zone'' covering areas
1,000 feet or less from city schools. Under that bill, those caught
using or selling drugs in those areas would face an additional
three-year jail term.
</TEXT>
