<FIRST>u w PM-HijackingTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0444 02-28 0865</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hijacking Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0444,860</SECOND>
<HEAD>Witnesses Identify Younis as Skyjacker</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 11 grafs new with third witness identifying Younis in court,
picking up in 5th graf pvs, William L.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A third witness pointed today to Fawaz Younis
and identified him as the sky pirate who led a June 1985 hijacking
in Lebanon.
   His testimony came a day after federal prosecutors showed a
videotape of Younis reading a statement at the foot of the
aircraft's stairs before an explosion rocked the jetliner.
   Mouin Ajam, 24, a Lebanese passenger aboard the plane, pointed to
Younis across the courtroom and said he was``100 percent sure'' that
the defendant was the man who led a team of five heavily armed men
aboard Royal Jordanian Airline flight 402 as it loaded passengers
bound for Amman.
   Landry T. Slade, a vice president of the American University of
Beirut, and his son William testified Monday that the other
hijackers called Younis ``Nazeeh'' and treated him as their leader.
   While four of the men overwhelmed and bound Jordanian sky
marshals, Younis went to the cockpit, where he remained for most of
the 30-hour incident, all three witnesses testified.
   The other four hijackers stayed in the passenger compartment and
spent much of their time beating the five security guards, despite
Younis' instructions that they stop, the Slades said.
   Ajam testified that one of the hijackers, not Younis, pointed to
one of the bound marshals and asked one of the female passengers
``which one do you want us to kill first?''
   ``Do you want us to kill the one with the red shirt first?,''
Ajam said the hijacker asked the female passenger.
   ``She said, `No. Don't kill anybody,''' testified Ajam, who was
sitting one seat in front of the woman.
   The hijacker, apparently ``showing off,'' also told the young
woman that ``We've hijacked three airplanes. This is our third. We
always go into Palestinian camps and plant bombs. I've been in a lot
of fighting. I've killed lots of people,'' Ajam said.
   Federal marshals, acting under orders from U.S. District Judge
Aubrey E. Robinson Jr., asked media artists not to sketch Ajam,
apparently in order to protect him from possible reprisal.
   William L. Slade, now 22, said the hijackers, members of the
Lebanon's Amal militia, a Shiite Moslem group, hung pictures of Amal
leader Nabih Berri and Iranian leader Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini on
one of the aircraft walls.
   William Slade testifed that the hijackers pushed the sky marshals
down in the main aisle, beat them, kicked them, dropped bayonets on
their backs and burned them with cigarettes.
   Younis came out of the cockpit several times, ordered the other
hijackers to stop abusing the marshals, and returned to the front,
at which point the beatings resumed, both Slades testified.
   Younis, 30, has pleaded innocent to a six-count indictment.
   The trial in U.S. District Court is a test of a 1984 law in which
the United States asserts ``long-arm'' jurisdiction over cases
involving Americans taken hostage overseas. Slade and his son were
the only two Americans among the approximately 70 passengers and
crew members.
   More than two years after the hijacking, on Sept. 13, 1987,
Younis was lured to a yacht in international waters off the coast of
Cyprus in the Mediterranean Sea with the promise of a narcotics deal
and a party, according to evidence presented before the trial.
   Defense lawyer Francis D. Carter said in his opening argument to
the jury that Younis had given FBI agents a confession while he was
seasick and suffering, without medical attention, after the agents
had broken both his wrists.
   A federal appeals court has ruled that the confession may be used
as evidence, but Carter told jurors: ``You will have to determine
whether the statement that my client gave to the FBI was voluntary
or involuntary.''
   Carter argued that during the hijacking his client was acting
under orders from Amal, and that the incident involved a political
dispute among Arabs and was not aimed at the United States.
   ``No passenger received so much of an injury that could be
covered by a Band-Aid,'' he said.
   The hijackers tried to fly the plane to Tunis to read a statement
complaining about Palestinians in Lebanon, but Tunisian authorities
denied it permission to land and the aircraft returned to Beirut,
where the hostages eventually were released.
   Slade testified that as he and his son were led off the plane,
they saw two hijackers planting explosives.
   ``They were putting hand grenades into the seats,'' said Slade.
   Younis was standing at the foot of the aircraft stairs, shaking
hands with the passengers as they left and headed toward an airport
bus.
   Asked why he shook hands with Younis, William Slade said:
   ``I shook his hand because I was afraid that if I had not shaken
his hand, he might have taken offense and done something bad to me.''
   The prosecution produced as evidence a videotape of the last
minutes of the hijacking, in which Younis was standing at the foot
of the aircraft stairs reading a statement in Arabic.
   The videotape later showed an explosion at the front of the
jetliner.
</TEXT>
