<FIRST>u i PM-Salvador 1stLd-Writethru   02-28 0702</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0427,0723</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Say They Will Take Part In Peace Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with rebel response to Duarte's proposal,
fighting continuing; EDITS througout to tighten. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist rebels said today they
would participate in peace talks with the government, but that the
negotiations must be in San Salvador ``in full view of the people.''
   They also said the agenda must be broader than the one proposed
Sunday night President Jose Napoleon Duarte.
   Salvador Samayoa, a rebel chief now in Mexico, read the
guerrillas' response during a broadcast on radio YSU in San Salvador.
   Duarte proposed that peace talks begin today in Guatemala and
coincide with a three-month cease-fire. He also proposed that the
March 19 presidential election be postponed until April 30.
   The leader of the rightist party that controls the legislature
rejected the proposals Monday.
   The communique by the guerrilla group _ the Farabundo Marti
National Liberation Front _ said the talks should be begin March 4
at the headquarters of the Roman Catholic archdiocese in San
Salvador.
   If both sides agreed to a cease-fire, the talks should ``be held
among and in full view of the people,'' the communique read by
Samayoa said.
   It also said the rebels rejected Duarte's election date of April
30 and that his government must state beforehand that it would
discuss postponing the balloting until September.
   The rebels said negotiations must include their demand that the
government's armed forces be reduced from 56,000 men to the 12,000
level of a decade ago, before the civil war began. Another issue
that must be addressed is prosecution of military officers
implicated in gross human rights violations, they said.
   The insurgents gave Duarte 48 hours to respond.
   On Monday, Ricardo Alvarenga, a leader of the Republican
Nationalist Alliance and president of the Legislative Assembly, told
a news conference that ``the election date is set, and it must be
fulfilled. It is not by altering the constitutional order that
problems are resolved.''
   The rightist alliance, known as Arena, controls the unicameral
assembly and is favored to win the presidency from Duarte's
Christian Democrats. It has adamantly rejected any postponement of
the vote.
   Washington hailed Duarte's proposal as presenting the most
significant opportunity ever for peace in El Salvador. The United
States has been backing the government in a 9-year-old civil war
that has claimed more than 70,000 lives.
   Meanwhile, the rebels continued their attacks.
   The Armed Forces press office said today that a rebel attack on
the 6th Infantry Brigade headquarters in Usulutan province, 68 miles
east of the capital, wounded three soldiers and a civilian.
   In the town of Berlin, 70 miles east of San Salvador in Usulutan,
two police officers and four civilians were injured when police
tried to deactivate an explosive device.
   The military also said that three rebels died attacking a
military position at Nueva Concepcion, 42 miles northeast of the
capital in Chalatenango province. Rebel radio said 28 soldiers were
killed or wounded but the military denied the claim.
   The rebels said last month that they would participate in the
election and respect its outcome if the vote were postponed at least
four months. That was seen as a major turnabout by the Marxist-led
rebels, who have condemned the five previous national elections this
decade as shams.
   Duarte suggested Sunday that constitutional problems with
delaying the election could be resolved either through an accord
involving the three branches of government or by a plebiscite.
   He had originally rejected the guerrilla proposal, saying
postponement of the election past March 31 would be unconstitutional.
   He did not explain Sunday why April 30 could be considered a
legal date. The constitution says elections must be held at least
two months before the end of the incumbent's term.
   Duarte's term expires June 1. The 63-year-old president, who is
suffering from terminal liver cancer, is expected to survive until
then.
   Alvarenga noted that the legislature must analyze Duarte's
plebiscite proposal but said he opposed it.
   ``Why have a plebiscite? The presidential election is a
plebiscite, a consultation of the popular will, and it must be
carried out as scheduled,'' he said.
</TEXT>
