<FIRST>r a PM-GunOffer     02-28 0224</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gun Offer,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Priest Finds Bounty Offer On Guns Backfires</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A priest who offered $100 for every handgun turned
in at his church has been stung by a political gadfly who exchanged
a cheap pistol to help pay for an assault rifle.
   The Rev. Marshall Gourley said 14 guns had been surrendered at
Our Lady of Guadalupe Catholic Church as of late Monday in response
to the offer announced during Mass on Sunday.
   Robin Heid, a 35-year-old private investigator and free-lance
writer, exchanged a 5-year-old gun, then went before a waiting TV
crew to say he would use the $100 as a down payment on an AR-15, the
civilian version of an M-16 assault rifle.
   ``This is a capitalist country _ when you have a chance to make a
good deal, you make it,'' Heid said.
   He said the .22-caliber revolver he exchanged was worth no more
than $40.
   The priest, who presided over the funerals of two gunshot victims
in the past month, called the move a betrayal of his effort to
remove as many guns as possible from the streets of Denver. ``I'm
disappointed in him,'' he said.
   The bounty came from a $2,000 donation from a parishioner who
requested that the cash be used for something worthwhile other than
church repairs or the annual budget, Gourley said.
</TEXT>
