<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 1230EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-SchoolBoards     02-28 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-School Boards,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey Says They're Often Rubber Stamps for Superintendent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   School boards often are rubber stamps for
district superintendents instead of reflecting the communities they
are supposed to represent, concludes a first-time survey of board
presidents released Tuesday.
   The findings, based on questionnaires completed by 1,217 school
board presidents, show large gaps between the board presidents and
the public on issues ranging from school ratings and problems to sex
education and parental choice.
   Fully 81 percent of the board presidents said they were greatly
influenced by their superintendent, compared to 4 percent who
reported being greatly influenced by the PTA and 3 percent by
individual parents. The longer they are board members, the more
resistant they are to change, the survey found.
   ``The study shows that people come in energetic and interested in
reform ... but very quickly they are discouraged or it's just easier
to go along with the ride,'' said Emily Feistritzer, an education
analyst and director of the private National Center for Education
Information.
   The widest opinion gap came in the area of public school choice,
a concept championed by President Bush and supported by 71 percent
of the public in a 1987 Gallup poll. But only 36 percent of the
school board presidents said parents should have the right to select
which local school their child attends; 51 percent were opposed.
   Other areas of difference with the public:
   _A 1988 Gallup poll found the public considered drug use and lack
of discipline the two most serious problems faced by schools. School
board presidents overwhelmingly cited lack of proper financial
support as their schools' biggest problem.
   _Eighty percent of the school board presidents favored sex
education in grades 4-8. But only 55 percent of the public felt that
way in a spring 1987 Gallup poll.
   _Forty percent of the public graded their local schools A or B in
a Gallup poll last year. A full 79 percent of school board
presidents gave their own schools an A or B, even while agreeing
with the public that, nationally, schools aren't doing too well.
   The board presidents did reflect prevailing public views in their
strong support for paying teachers on the basis of performance and
requiring them to pass competency tests before they can teach.
   Asked what would improve education, 84 percent said requiring
students to perform at grade level to attain promotions. The next
most popular suggestion, winning 75 percent, was recruiting teachers
from other career fields.
   Two-thirds of the board presidents also favored giving individual
schools greater flexibility in determining what and how students are
taught and in deciding how the school will operate. Only one-third,
however, said teachers should have greater authority in running
schools.
   The survey found that 97 percent of school board presidents are
white, 71 percent are male, and 68 percent have never worked in an
education system. Nearly half are in their 40s, 94 percent are
married, and almost two-thirds have children at home. The presidents
are better educated, make more money and are more conservative
politically than the average American.
   There are 40 million students enrolled in public schools in more
than 15,000 school districts across the country. Responses to the
Feistritzer survey were weighted to reflect all districts and the
results had a margin of error of 3 percentage points.
</TEXT>
