<HEAD>Four Convicted of Plotting to Assassinate President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COTONOU, Benin (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court has convicted four men, including
two army officers, of plotting to assassinate President Matthieu
Kerekou, and sentenced to prison terms ranging from five to 20 years.
   Prosecutors in the trial, which ended Monday night, had demanded
the maximum penalty of life imprisonment for all four.
   Witnesses at the trial said the former Libyan ambassador, Mostafa
Aboucetta, had inspired the June 1988 plot. Aboucetta hurriedly left
Benin shortly after the four were arrested.
   Capt. Amadou Abdouramane and Ahmed Kadi Youba, a Mauritanian
Moslem holy man, were given 20-year sentences. The prosecution
described them as the ringleaders.
   Capt. Fousseini Gomina was sentenced to 10 years in prison and
Hama Bio Soumailia was sentenced to five years in prison. A fifth
conspirator is still at large.
