<HEAD>Zambia Airways Flight to New York Makes Emergency Landing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUSAKA, Zambia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bird flew into an engine of a Zambia
Airways jumbo jet as it was taking off for New York, forcing the
aircraft to return to the airport after circling for an hour,
airline officials said Tuesday.
   The DC-10 landed on two engines after the pilot dumped a full
load of fuel and there were no injuries to the more than 100
passengers and 15 crew members in the incident late Monday, said
Capt. Godfrey Mulundika, the general manager of the state-owned
airline.
   The engine was seriously damaged, he said.
   Zambia Airways operates a once-weekly service to New York via
Monrovia, capital of the West African nation of Liberia.
