<SECOND>AM-BRF--Turkey-Inmates,0170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inmates End Hunger Strike of 19 Days</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist inmates ended a 19-day-hunger
strike Tuesday after winning more prison privileges, a spokesman for
a human rights group said.
   The 207 inmates, held in a high-security prison in Eskisehir, a
central city, began the strike to gain permission for more frequent
visits by their relatives and access to various publications,
including books and newspapers.
   Fevzi Argun, of the independent Turkish Human Rights
Organization, said the inmates ended the hunger strike when their
requests were granted. Relatives will be allowed to visit inmates
once a week, a change from once every other week, he said.
   Argun said at least two inmates were hospitalized during the
hunger strike.
   Eight people, including the wives and parents of inmates, also
held a hunger strike for one week at the headquarters of the Human
Rights Organization in the capital city of Ankara in support of the
prisoners. They also ended their hunger strike Tuesday, Argun said.
