<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Italy-Water     02-28 0161</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Italy-Water,0165</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pollution Leaves 150,000 People Without Drinking Water</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROVIGO, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayors of 24 towns along the Adige River on
Tuesday renewed warnings not to drink tap water because local
supplies have been contaminated by toxic chemicals.
   An estimated 150,000 people in the Rovigo area, 35 miles
southwest of Venice, have been without potable tap water since
Sunday. Residents have had to stand in long lines at mobile water
tanks set up by the army and municipal authorities to get water for
drinking and cooking.
   Italian newspapers reported the aqueduct that supplies drinking
water for the area has been contaminated by heavy metals and toxic
chemicals discharged by factories into the Adige, Italy's
second-longest river.
   Some cities, including Chioggia, on the Venetian lagoon, and
Cavarzere, have had their tap water turned off since Feb. 22.
   Local and regional councils have declared a state of emergency
and have asked that all toxic discharges into the Adige be stopped
immediately.
</TEXT>
