<SECOND>AM-BRF--Train-Bomb,0135</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomb Scare on the Orient Express</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Tuesday evacuated all
passengers from the Orient Express from Romania after receiving a
telephoned bomb threat, the official MTI news agency reported.
   The train was stopped for nearly two hours while police conducted
a thorough search, but no bomb was found, MTI said.
   Police arrested Istvan Attila Kiss, 20, who admitted he said he
placed a bomb, but meant it as a joke, MTI said.
   The call was received at police headquarters in Bekescsaba, a
town near the Romanian border, and the train was stopped at
Nagylapos before being allowed to continue on to Budapest.
   The Romanian section of the train missed its connection in
Budapest, meaning a seven-hour delay in Vienna, a railway spokesman
said.
