<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 1236EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-NewspaperFire 3rdLd-Writethru a0534 02-28 0584</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Newspaper Fire, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0534,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede NEW YORK</HEAD>
<HEAD>Newspaper Office Firebombed; Link to `The Satanic Verses' Suspected</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with bookstore owner saying bombings probably
related to uproar over novel, new quotes, other bookstore owner saying
no definite link to novel; No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A New York newspaper office and two California bookstores were
firebombed early today in attacks possibly related to Moslem anger
over the novel ``The Satanic Verses,'' officials said.
   ``I can't imagine any other reason why people would be lobbing
bombs through bookstores,'' said bookstore owner Andy Ross as he
helped clean up the damage at his Cody's Books in Berkeley, Calif.
   Both Cody's, a Berkeley landmark near the University of
California campus, and a branch of the Waldenbooks chain a block
away were damaged when bottles filled with a flammable liquid were
tossed through windows, their owners said.
   The blaze at the Riverdale Press in the Bronx section of New York
City heavily damaged the building, authorities said. No one was
inside at the time.
   Witnesses said a station wagon drove by the offices about 4:40
a.m. and someone in the car tossed an incendiary device through a
window, police said. The firebombing may have been in retaliation
for an editorial the weekly paper ran last week supporting the right
to read Salman Rushdie's novel, said firefighter Tom McTigue.
   The novel has sparked violent protests among Moslems who consider
it blasphemous. Iran's Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini ordered a death
sentence for Rushdie and his publisher.
   ``My guess is that it had something to do with something that was
printed in the paper,'' Riverdale Press co-publisher Richard Stein
said. ``But I don't know what.''
   McTigue and Stein stressed that no motive had been established
and that there was no definite link to ``The Satanic Verses.''
   ``I honestly feel it is nothing but speculation,'' Stein said.
``We have not received any telephone or written threats. No one has
taken credit for this.''
   Stein said the 39-year-old community newspaper, which has a paid
circulation of 14,000, would print its Wednesday edition despite the
damage.
   He said the paper, which was a Pulitzer Prize finalist last year
for the second time, is known for its activism and outspoken
editorial page, but he said he could not recall anything recently
that could be considered of ``incendiary import.''
   In an editorial last week, the newspaper criticized bookstores
that removed ``The Satanic Verses'' from display, he said.
   ``I cannot imagine why our paper would be singled out among the
thousands of newspapers around the country'' that published similar
thoughts, he said.
   In Berkeley, Waldenbooks manager Bob Gammon wasn't ready to blame
the firebombing on the furor over Rushdie's book.
   ``We've had no threats, no one claiming to have done it,' Gammon
said. ``So there's no evidence that it was due to `Satanic Verses.'
''
   Gammon and Ross said they had been told by police that the fires
resulted from a kerosene-type firebomb. Police would not confirm the
report but said arson investigators were sent.
   ``We had a broken window and a carpet caught fire,'' Gammon said.
   Ross estimated damage at less than $1,000. Ross had put out a
flyer Wednesday denouncing ``the intellectual terrorism that is
being directed against Mr. Rushdie.''
   Both men said their stores had sold all copies of the novel.
Waldenbooks, one of the nation's largest bookstore chains, pulled
the book off shelves for a week before announcing Friday that
managers could display it at their discretion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890228-0079 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 1238EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Economy     02-28 0680</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Economy,0702</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Than a Third of City Residents See Incomes Decrease</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than one-third of China's city residents saw
their real incomes decline in 1988, a year of impressive economic
growth tempered by disturbingly high inflation and serious supply
shortages.
   The State Statistics Bureau, in an annual report announced
Tuesday, said per capita income in urban areas was $302, up only 1.2
percent from 1987 after deducting price increases.
   It said the spending power of 34.9 percent of urban families
declined because their incomes failed to keep pace with inflation.
In 1987, 20 percent of urban residents reported declines in their
living standards.
   Among the hardest hit were government employees on fixed salaries
and construction workers affected by policies intended to slow down
the overheated economy, bureau spokesman Zhang Zhongji said at a
news conference.
   In rural areas, where more than three-fourths of China's 1.1
billion people live, per capita income rose 6.3 percent after
inflation to $147.
   ``It was a year of joy and worry, with many difficulties,'' Zhang
said.
   The main worry was the highest rate of inflation in communist
China's history. Retail prices in December were up 26.7 percent over
the same month in 1987. The bureau said the prices of meat, poultry
and eggs, fresh vegetables and aquatic products were all up by more
than 30 percent.
   Among basic materials, the general price index for rolled steel
was up 21 percent, copper was up 50 percent and aluminum was up 38.6
percent.
   Zhang said the gross national product rose 11.2 percent to $374
billion, and national income totaled $312 billion, an increase of
11.4 percent.
   But growth, he said, was uneven, and ``the gap widened between
social supply and social demand.''
   Industrial output value shot up 20.7 percent to $489 billion.
Among consumer goods, production of color TV sets rose by 52.8
percent, refrigerators by 84.4 percent and motor vehicles by 37.1
percent.
   Industries such as coal and steel, however, showed relatively
slow growth, and 20 percent of enterprises can't operate at full
strength because of power shortages.
   Agricultural output value grew only by 3.2 percent, and grain
production, the crucial measure of the nation's agricultural health,
declined by 9 million tons to 394 million tons.
   Zhang said grain output fell about 22 million tons short of need
and that 40 million people in rural areas are short of food. About
11 million tons was taken from reserves and another 11 million tons
imported, he said.
   Zhang also said that 14,400 investment projects had been
suspended or cancelled since the government embarked last fall on a
tough austerity program to cool down economic growth and bring
inflation under control.
   He said that represented about 10 percent of all ongoing projects.
   Zhang could not give a figure for how many jobs had been lost in
the building clampdown, but estimated that unemployment will rise
from the current 2.1 percent of urban workers to about 3 percent by
the end of 1989. He said there are now 135.7 million urban workers,
up 3.6 million from the end of 1987.
   Zhang said the austerity program has shown results, with the
retail price index going up only 1 percent in January compared to
December.
   But despite the clampdown on projects in the last quarter of the
year, overall spending in projects under construction rose 12
percent over the year to $351 billion.
   ``This was mainly because too many unimportant projects were
started, and investments outside the budget increased greatly.''
   Zhang said the problems China faces are ``more complicated and
difficult'' than in 1984 and 1985, when there was a similar
situation of too rapid growth.
   China is saddled with stagnation in grain production; four years
ago, it was coming off bumper harvests.
   Another difference, he said, is that the government has less
control over the economy because it has relinquished some authority
under market-oriented reforms. The reforms have also allowed
enterprises to keep more of their profits, and price rises have not
translated into increased revenues for the state.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
