<FIRST>r w AM-Laos-MIA     02-28 0178</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Laos-MIA,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S., Laos Agree to Have Excavation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and Laos have agreed to
conduct an excavation in the Laotian countryside at a site where
American servicemen may have died during the Vietnam War, the
Pentagon said Tuesday.
   The site in southern Laos ``may be associated with an incident
involving one or more Americans missing in Southeast Asia,'' the
Pentagon said in a statement.
   The Pentagon, without elaboration, said the site was discovered
and initially surveyed by a joint Laotian-American team of experts
last December. Previous excavations have been mounted only when
evidence of an aircraft crash has been found.
   The excavation will begin Saturday and will take from 10 to 14
days to complete, the Pentagon said.
   It will be the fifth excavation allowed by the Laotian government
since the war ended.
   ``The United States government appreciates this further step by
the Lao government in our cooperative effort to resolve the issue of
Americans still missing or otherwise unaccounted for in Laos as a
result of the war,'' the Pentagon said.
</TEXT>
