<HEAD>Pickering Among Nominees Approved by Senate Committee</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Foreign Relations Committee
recommended on Tuesday that the Senate confirm five of President
Bush's nominees for diplomatic posts including his choice of veteran
diplomat Thomas Pickering to be U.S. ambassador to the United
Nations.
   Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., the committee chairman, said the
action by voice vote and without debate left the panel with no
further nominations before it.
   Bush has said he intends to send other nominations to the Senate
soon but has yet to do so. The delay apparently has been caused by
lengthy background checks each person must undergo before the
nomination can be made.
   The Senate panel approved Pickering, the current U.S. ambassador
to Israel, and four other nominees:
   _Robert M. Kimmitt, former general counsel of the Treasury
Department, to be undersecretary of state for political affairs.
   _Janet Gardner Mullins, who served as media director for the
Bush-Quayle campaign and formerly was chief of staff for Sen. Mitch
McConnell, R-Ky., to be assistant secretary of state for legislative
affairs.
   _Margaret Tutwiler, formerly spokesman for the Treasury
Department and a member of the Bush-Quayle campaign team, to be
assistant secretary of state for public affairs.
   _Robert B. Zoellick to be counselor of the State Department.
