<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Defection     02-28 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Defection,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Head of Renowned Meissen Porcelain Company Defects to West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   BONN, West German
(AP)_ The head of East Germany's renowned
Meissen porcelain company has defected to West Germany, security
sources said Tuesday.
   Reinhard Fichte had been director of the company, founded in 1710
and known around the world for its artistic craftmanship.
   The mass-circulation newspapers Bild and Hamburg Abendblatt
reported Fichte had remained in the West after attending a Frankfurt
trade fair.
   In addition to his duties at Meissen, Fichte was also a close
adviser to Guenter Mittag, an economist and member of the East
German Communist Party's Politburo, the Abendblatt reported.
   The Abendblatt said Fichte himself ``was to advance to the
Politburo.''
   ``He also was accorded many special privileges'' by the communist
authorities, the newspaper said.
   West German security officials confirmed that Fichte, 47, decided
to remain in West Germany after attending a Feb. 18-22 trade fair in
Frankfurt.
   The security officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
would not disclose Fichte's whereabouts and they also did not say
whether he may have had access to any East German security secrets.
   The Abendblatt reported the defection ``came as a complete
surprise to Meissen employees.''
   The newspaper said the porcelain firm in Meissen, East Germany,
did not know what had become of Fichte until informed by the West
German newspaper.
   Company officials had ``exhausted all possibilities ... and had
not excluded that Fichte might have been killed or kidnapped,'' the
newspaper said.
   The Abendblatt did not identify its sources at the Meissen firm.
   The newspaper said Fichte was one of the few East German
businessmen allowed to travel freely outside the East bloc.
   Abendblatt said that Fichte's wife, Jutta, was ``disturbed'' when
informed by the West German newspaper of her husband's plans to stay
in the West.
   Bild reported that Fichte failed to show up at a news conference
at the close of the Frankfurt exposition.
</TEXT>
