<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Britain     02-28 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Britain,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran-Britain Relations At A Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Satanic Verses, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Except for a brief thaw late last year,
British-Iranian relations have been troubled for the past 8{ years.
Here is a summary:
   September 1980 _ With Iran's relations with the West in turmoil
over the seizure of the U.S. Embassy hostages, Britain closes its
embassy in Tehran and withdraws its staff for their protection. Four
diplomats stay behind to run a British interests section in the
Swedish Embassy.
   November 1985 _ British businessman Roger Cooper is arrested in
Iran and accused of spying, but is not charged or tried.
   May 1987 _ Police arrest an Iranian diplomat in Manchester on
shoplifting charges. In Tehran, a British diplomat is abducted and
beaten up, apparently in retaliation.
   June 1987 _ Over the years Britain has slowly built up a
19-member staff in its Tehran Embassy. But after a series of
tit-for-tat diplomatic expulsions triggered by the Manchester
incident, London recalls all its diplomats in Iran and reduces the
Iranian diplomatic presence in London to a lone charge d'affaires.
   September 1987 _ Iran attacks a British tanker in the Persian
Gulf. Britain hits back by closing the London headquarters of Iran's
worldwide arms-purchasing operation.
   June 1988 _ Iran and Britain have talks in London on compensation
for damage done to each other's embassies in political violence in
1979 and 1980. The successful negotiations lead to broader talks on
British-Iranian relations, and agreement is reached to resume full
diplomatic ties.
   December 1988 _ The British Embassy in Tehran reopens. Nicholas
Nicola, a British tourist held in Iran for more than two years is
freed and comes home. Hopes rise for the release of Cooper, as well
as British hostages believed held by pro-Iranian abductors in
Lebanon.
   February 1989 _ Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini passes a death
sentence on British novelist Salman Rushdie, claiming his novel
``The Satanic Verses'' blasphemes Islam. Rushdie's apology is not
accepted in Tehran. Cooper is given a ``heavy'' but unspecified
sentence. Britain and its 11 European Economic Community partners
withdraw their heads of mission from Tehran. Britain goes further by
withdrawing all its diplomats from the newly reopened Tehran
Embassy, and ordering out Iran's two diplomats in London.
   Feb. 28 _ Iran's Parliament votes to sever diplomatic ties with
Britain.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
