<FIRST>u a PM-IllegalAliens 2ndLd-Writethru a0586-a0471 02-28 0630</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Illegal Aliens, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0586-a0471,0645</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Illegal Aliens Arrested On Cross-Country Flight</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines pvs.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Immigration officials overnight seized 69
illegal aliens about to board the same cross-country flight on which
79 undocumented immigrants were taken into custoday the night
before, authorities said.
   The 69 were trying to board an Eastern Airlines flight to New
York by way of Atlanta, said Immigration and Naturalization Service
spokesman Joe Flanders.
   He said 54 were from Mexico, seven from El Salvador, four from
Colombia and four from Guatemala. Most will be allowed to go home or
request a deportation hearing, he said.
   Flanders said one man was arrested and may have been the
principal smuggler.
   On Monday, authorities seized 79 illegal aliens during Flight
80's 5:35 a.m. stopover in Atlanta, acting on tips from airline
sources and someone who often traveled the route and became
suspicious of fellow passengers.
   Investigators believe illegal aliens have been aboard the Eastern
overnight flight nearly every day for the past 30 days, said Tom
Thomas, an INS spokesman in Atlanta.
   Thomas said the flight might have been used because no plane
tranfers are involved and rates might have been cheaper.
   ``There's a commuter who regularly flies from Los Angeles to
Atlanta who called our office. ... and said, `Hey, it seems there's
an awful lot of Hispanic people who fly this flight. You might want
to check into it,''' Thomas said.
   Thomas said some of the aliens indicated they had paid up to
$4,000 for a package, but authorities don't know what that deal
included other than air fare from California to New York. The
package could have included living arrangements, phony documents and
a job, he added.
   On Monday, the cheapest fares available for the flight were $433
to $577, including taxes, according to a travel agent.
   One of the 79, Elias Quevedo-Gonzalez of Pachalun, Guatemala,
said he borrowed $1,400 from neighbors to make the trip so he could
earn money in the United States to send back to his wife and seven
children.
   ``About four people in my town have done that, and when they came
back I could see their families were much better off,'' the
39-year-old man said. ``They had better clothes and good food.''
   Thomas said Eastern has cooperated fully in the investigation.
   ``We don't in any way connect Eastern and don't want to intimate
that they were even remotely involved at this point,'' he said.
   In Miami, Eastern spokeswoman Virginia Sanchez said, ``All I know
is that the INS had told us they'd be monitoring a flight this week
and, of course, we cooperated with them.''
   In addition to Guatemala, the aliens taken off Monday's flight
came from Mexico, the Dominican Republic, El Salvador, Honduras and
Ecuador, Thomas said. He said they would be transferred to INS
processing facilities in Florida and Texas for deportation.
   But one of the aliens, Juan De La Cruz-Rodriguez, 34, said he
would do whatever he could to stay in this country ``because if I go
back, they'll put me in prison. They'll kill me if I don't pay what
I owe.''
   De La Cruz-Rodriguez, who said he was trying to make money to
send to his wife and three young sons in the Dominican Republic,
said a smuggler in Mexico helped him and about a dozen others cross
the border, then arranged to have them transported by flatbed truck
to Los Angeles.
   ``I always had the image of America having a lot of money and a
lot of wealth, and that I could find work without any problem,'' he
said.
   He said he sold his truck to raise part of the money and gave the
smuggler almost $1,000. Holding up a quarter, he said, ``That's all
I have left.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890228-0091 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 1331EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SuperBarrio     02-28 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Super Barrio,0244</SECOND>
<HEAD>Masked Crusader Wrestles With Mexican Politics</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A yellow cape, red tights and leather
mask might not be enough to draw a crowd in this freewheeling
college town, but Super Barrio has more than his costume, he has a
message.
   Professor Raul Hinojosa said he invited Super Barrio to the
University of California to speak Monday to a class on Latin
American politics because he is a symbol of social change in Mexico.
   Super Barrio, who is rapidly becoming a folk hero in Mexico and
among Mexican immigrants in the United States, first appeared in
1987 in Mexico City, persuading a landlord not to evict poor tenants
behind on their rent.
   Since then, he pops up regularly when there's trouble, traveling
in his Barriomobile. He has allied himself with the Assembly of
Barrios, a union of groups opposing the one-party dominance of the
Institutional Revolutionary Party, which has ruled since the 1920s.
   Super Barrio's costume is a blend of Mexican wrestling lore and
the trappings of U.S. super heroes. But Super Barrio was quick to
point out that he is not Superman.
   ``Superman has super powers,'' he said. ``I do not. I am merely
human.''
   Super Barrio _ like comic book heroes _ keeps his identity
secret. He will only say that he lives in a housing project, is a
former professional wrestler, and is now a street vendor in Mexico
City.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890228-0092 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 1331EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-CoalRoyalties     02-28 0659</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coal Royalties,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lujan Says He Intends to Reverse Lowered Royalty Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interior Secretary Manual Lujan Jr. said
Tuesday he intends to reverse his predecessor's plan to lower
royalties on coal taken from mines beneath federal lands.
   Lujan, testifying before the interior subcommittee of the House
Appropriations Committee, also said he would try to get Congress to
raise sharply the $2.50 per acre fee charged for converting oil
shale and other mining claims into outright ownership.
   But Lujan said he found he could not stop a change in the method
of valuing coal that lowers royalties, and it might be Nov. 1 before
he could promulgate a new regulation to revoke it.
   Former Secretary Donald P. Hodel had approved proposals to lower
the royalty on underground coal from 8 percent to 5 percent, and to
exlude state and federal taxes from the value of coal when
calculating royalties.
   While the rate change has not become final, Lujan said, the
valuation method change takes effect Wednesday. He said the
department's lawyers have told him he could not stop that change,
although he intends to try.
   Lujan said he would begin a study immediately of the change in
valuation methods and if production and royalty payments increase,
the aim of the change in the first place, ``then, of course, we
don't want to rescind'' the rule.
   Conceding final defeat in a lawsuit begun in 1920 that the
government had lost twice in the Supreme Court, Hodel issued deeds
of ownership at $2.50 an acre to 82,000 acres of shale land in
Colorado that the new owners promptly sold at a large profit.
   The department resolved to start processing other shale
applications while it decides on rules for determining the validity
of the claims _ a decision that brought much protest in Congress,
protest that Lujan clearly agreed with.
   There are 11 applications and 1,592 claims to 241,000 acres of
shale land in Colorado, Utah and Wyoming.
   ``I can't tell you I'm going to deny these groups (of claimants)
their rights,'' Lujan told the subcommittee. ``I can tell you I'm
going to develop red tape, or whatever the government does so well
... in a process by which we determine if they're valid and that is
going to take at least a year.''
   During that year, he said he would work with Congress to raise
the fee. He said department lawyers had told him his idea that the
fee be pegged to the value of the land could not stand legal
scrutiny.
   He did not mention a specific figure for a new fee, except to say
it should be much higher than $2.50 an acre, a fee that has remained
unchanged since 1872.
   Proposed rules for deciding on the validity of claims were sent
to the Office of Management and Budget in December, and department
spokesman Tim Locke said Lujan had written OMB asking that the draft
be returned ``so he can put it under his own microscope.''
   Half of all federal royalties are returned to state governments,
with just about all going to Wyoming, Montana, Colorado, Utah, New
Mexico and North Dakota. Lujan said the states had protested both
planned changes.
   The Western Organization of Resource Councils estimated that
Wyoming would lose $11 million a year from the change in valuation
methods, Colorado would lose $1.3 million, Montana $4.7 million, New
Mexico $650,000, North Dakota $462,000 and Utah $710,000.
   The loss to the federal government would be roughly the same,
$18.8 million a year.
   In all, the federal government received $153 million in coal
royalties in fiscal 1987, the last year for which figures are
complete, and an estimated $246 million in 1988, according to
preliminary estimates.
   The reduction in royalty rate from 8 percent to 5 percent for
underground mines would cost the government $18.2 million to $20.2
million a year if production did not change, the department has
estimated.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
