<FIRST>r a AM-Bush-Libraries     02-28 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Libraries,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rice, Texas A&amp;M, Yale Already Trying to Land Bush Library</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least three universities are ready for George
Bush to become a former president.
   Rice University, Texas A&amp;M University and Bush's alma mater, Yale
University, already have expressed interest in becoming the site of
his presidential library.
   In a typical case, funds for construction of a presidential
library are raised from private sources, and an institution, such as
a university, provides a site.
   ``Rice is certainly interested in the presidential papers, and we
have initiated conversations with the Bush administration on the
matter,'' Rice President George Rupp said in a statement. ``We are
continuing to work on the opportunity but no one has made a
commitment.''
   Rice partisans note that Secretary of State James Baker, a native
Houstonian and a close friend of Bush's, has begun depositing his
papers at Rice's Fondren Library.
   They also note that in 1978 Bush was an adjunct professor of
administrative science at Rice, teaching a graduate-level course in
``organization theory'' based on his experience as an oilman, member
of Congress, chairman of the Republican National Committee, director
of the CIA and U.S. envoy to China.
   Bryan Jones, head of Texas A&amp;M's political science department,
and a colleague, presidential scholar George Edwards, drafted a
memorandum urging the university to explore the possibilities of
gaining the presidential library.
   Newsweek magazine quoted Bush as saying he has already decided
his presidential papers should go to a Texas university. That has
not deterred Yale.
   ``I'm sure Yale will be making an effort to persuade the
president to locate his library here or at least some place near
here,'' said Jack Siggins, an administrator of Yale's library.
   ``I believe that possibility has been mentioned to President Bush
_ in fact, before he was President Bush _ by Yale's president, Benno
Schmidt.''
</TEXT>
