<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Kidnap     02-28 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Kidnap,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Caller: Soldier Will Be Killed Unless Palestinians Released</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An anonymous caller who said he belonged to a
group that claims to hold a missing Israeli paratrooper threatened
on Tuesday to kill the soldier unless Israel releases 1,500
Palestinian prisoners.
   The anonymous caller told Israel radio his group would release a
cassette to prove they were holding the soldier, Avi Sassportas,
according to radio reporter Elihu Ben-On.
   ``He said: `We are the organization that is holding the soldier
and we want you to release 1,500 prisoners. If not, the soldier will
die,''' Ben-On told The Associated Press.
   He said the caller, who spoke Hebrew with an Arab accent, read
from a prepared statement and refused to answer questions. He hung
up after about 15 seconds and did not name the group he claimed to
represent.
   On Monday, a similar call to the Agence France Presse news agency
said a group called the Palestinian Arab Army was holding
Sassportas, who disappeared 13 days ago. The caller said the group
was not linked to the PLO.
   The Palestinian Arab Army was not publicly known before Monday's
call. West Bank Commander Amram Mitzna told the Haaretz daily it has
been operating since the start of the Palestinian uprising, but
later said on radio nothing was known of the group.
   On Israel radio, Mitzna said the army was treating Tuesday's call
seriously but did not plan to comply with the demand to release
prisoners.
   The caller did not say which prisoners should be freed; army
figures indicate as many as 9,000 Palestinians have been jailed in
connection with the uprising.
   Sassportas was last seen Feb. 16 near Ashkelon after leaving his
base in southern Israel to hitch a ride home to Ashod. He was
wearing his uniform and armed with an M-16 assault rifle. The area
is close to the Gaza Strip.
   Thousands of people have participated in searches since then.
   Proof that he was kidnapped by a Palestinian group could
undermine a current shift in public opinion toward negotiations with
the PLO.
   Army officials said Monday the Democratic Front for the
Liberation of Palestine, a radical Marxist PLO faction, had claimed
it abducted Sassportas.
   Israeli warplanes on Tuesday bombed and rocketed a base in
Lebanon belonging to the front. Lebanese police said two guerrillas
were killed and 33 people injured.
</TEXT>
