<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Virginia Kruse wasn't going to let a little
setback like two broken arms keep her from going to work Tuesday on
her last day before retirement.
   Ms. Kruse showed up as the Hamilton County sheriff's secretary
with both arms in partial casts that leave her fingers exposed so
she can work.
   ``She's taking it in stride,'' a fellow employee said.
   Ms. Kruse broke her arms when she slipped and fell Friday at her
retirement party while dancing with her former boss, former Sheriff
Lincoln Stokes.
   She said she came to work this week because she did not want to
miss her final two days with co-workers after 23 years with the
sheriff's department.
   ``She's a great lady,'' sheriff's spokesman Frank Weikel said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A February half-price sale on fines has
cleared driving records, and perhaps consciences, for many
motorists, a judge said Tuesday.
   Traffic Judge Bill Watt estimated that payments increased by a
third during the month-long drive to reduce a backlog of more than
5,000 traffic warrants and 3,500 parking tickets.
   Little Rock Municipal Traffic Court told violators that they had
until Tuesday to clear their fines for half the amount owed. The
offer covered fines dating from 1986 to January 1989, Watt said.
   Many of the warrants included a charge of failure to appear in
court, which adds $100 to the original penalty.
   The cut rate is not costing the city money, because many of the
warrants would be uncollectible without the expense of sending
officers out to contact the violators, Watt said.
   ``If we get $1 in revenue off a warrant from someone voluntarily
surrendering themselves, we are not losing $2, which we might not
get anyway, we are gaining $1,'' he said.
</TEXT>
