<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 1437EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-GunBan     02-28 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gun Ban,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>San Diego Bans Assault Weapons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Overriding opposition from gun owners and the
city attorney, the City Council approved a ban on possession and
sale of assault weapons like those used in a Stockton schoolyard
shooting last month.
   The ordinance was approved 7-2 Monday.
   Council members also empowered police to impound for up to three
days semiautomatic assault weapons found during patrols. The
ordinance would allow police to determine whether the guns are
stolen or can be linked to a crime.
   Police previously could confiscate a gun only during an arrest.
   Several proposals to ban or restrict assault weapons have been
introduced in the Legislature since last month's schoolyard attack,
in which Patrick Purdy killed five children and wounded 30 people
with an AK-47 rifle before killing himself.
   Los Angeles, Stockton and Compton and Santa Clara County have
also passed bans on assault weapons, but National Rifle Association
members last week asked the state Supreme Court to overturn the Los
Angeles and Stockton ordinances.
   San Diego City Attorney John Witt argued that his city's
ordinance would probably be struck down because the state has sole
authority to legislate firearms.
   Councilman Wes Pratt, however, said the city needs to take such
weapons out of criminals' hands.
   ``Now is the time to act, and this is a reasonable approach,'' he
said.
   Semiautomatic assault weapons fire one round with each squeeze of
the trigger until the ammunition clip is expended.
</TEXT>
