<FIRST>r a AM-FreeMan'sHome     02-28 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Free Man's Home,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mississippi Working to Preserve Pre-Civil War Home of Free Black
Man</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON HARRIST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NATCHEZ, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A movement is under way to preserve the
home of a black writer whose violent death went unpunished because
of pre-Civil War legal discrimination.
   William Johnson, a successful barber, businessman and diarist, is
considered by historians the most prominent free black man in
antebellum Mississippi.
   Freed from slavery by his white owner in Louisiana, Johnson built
a three-story brick home in this bluff-lined Mississippi River town
in the early 1840s. It remained in his family until purchased in
1976 by a garden club.
   ``What many people do not realize is that Natchez had almost half
of the state's entire free black population before the war,'' said
Mimi Miller, a historic preservation consultant. ``What made Johnson
so important was that he kept a diary that represents the most
complete and accurate account of a free black man during this period
of our history.''
   Miller, who has worked with the Natchez Garden Club to preserve
the home, said that through Johnson's writings, ``historians were
able to learn that, just as in the white society, different levels
of social class existed within the free black society. This society
was separate and distinct from blacks who were slaves.''
   The diary and other information indicates Johnson was ``accepted
and respected'' by the community, and when he died in 1851, ``he
received a very large obituary but the great and tragic thing is his
death went unpunished because he was black,'' Miller said.
   Johnson apparently was shot by a man named Baylor Winn after a
long dispute over land boundaries.
   Only blacks witnessed the shooting, and under Mississippi law at
the time a black man could not testify against a white man. Miller
said Winn represented himself as white, but prosecutors, in hopes of
allowing the testimony of black witnesses, argued he had some black
ancestry.
   ``Natchez was so outraged they had to move his trial to another
town so Winn could get an impartial jury,'' she said. ``The Johnson
family hired an attorney, Will T. Martin, who later became one of
Mississippi's highest ranking Confederate generals.''
   Despite Martin's efforts, Winn went free.
   Johnson's house proved to be a historical treasure trove
containing much more than the 16-year diary, which was published by
the Louisiana State University Press in 1951.
   In the attic were nearly 1,400 legal and financial documents,
personal and business correspondence, volumes of account books and
old newspapers and sheet music dating from 1793, said Margaret Moss
of the Natchez Garden Club.
   Miller said preservationists hope to use the home's ground floor
for an exhibit on Natchez's black history, and restore the living
quarters upstairs with period furnishings.
   In 1987, the Legislature authorized the state's Archives and
History Department to buy, restore and administer the home once
sufficient funds are secured, said director Elbert Hilliard. The
effort will require a $1.5 million endowment, Hilliard said.
   An advisory committee has been formed to study ways to raise
money from private sources. Meanwhile, the National Trust for
Historic Preservation and the Jack Daniel Foundation for Preserving
American Landmarks and Traditions is working on raising $4,000 to
make immediate repairs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890228-0102 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 1434EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-PlaneEmergency 2ndLd-Writethru a0543 02-28 0717</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Plane Emergency, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0543,0733</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jet's Cargo Door Repaired Several Times Recently</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with two grafs to CLARIFY that flight was to be his last
round trip, but next-to-last flight; PICKS UP 3rd graf a0480, `After nine
...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The cargo door that ripped off a Boeing 747 over
the Pacific had electrical problems in recent months and a seal on
the door was repaired in January, an investigator said.
   For the pilot who safely landed the damaged jetliner, Capt. David
M. Cronin, the flight was to be his next-to-last before retiring,
and ``now, we will have another reason to celebrate,'' said his
daughter, Kelly Hart of Hawaii.
   After nine people were sucked out of the jumbo jet to their
deaths, the 59-year-old United Airlines pilot managed to turn the
plane around and land safely in Honolulu on only two of the four
engines.
   Her father ``gives all the credit to the Heavenly Father watching
over him,'' another daughter, Karen Twigg-Smith, told The Honolulu
Advertiser.
   Investigators looking into Friday's accident have focused on the
latching mechanism of the cargo door that tore off and left a
10-by-20-foot hole in the side of the 18-year-old plane.
   In December, electrical problems were reported more than once in
the airline's maintenance logs and the forward cargo door had to be
closed manually, National Transportation Safety Board investigator
Lee Dickinson said late Monday.
   In January, a seal on the cargo door was repaired, he said.
   Dickinson said he did not know whether those incidents required
reports to the Federal Aviation Administration. He also refused to
characterize the seriousness of the problems.
   ``We don't know what's normal,'' he said, but added, ``it is
proper to close this door manually.''
   Airline spokesman Rob Doughty also refused to comment on the
repairs, saying he needed to look at the records.
   U.S. Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner said Monday that
although preliminary investigation indicates the cargo door opened
in flight, it was too early to speculate on the cause of the
accident.
   The cargo bay door closes down, electrically and manually. The
hatch is hinged at the top and has eight latching mechanisms along
the bottom, attached to the plane's frame, as well as a latching
mechanism and a hook pin on each side, Dickinson said.
   Boeing Co. on Sunday told the operators of 712 Boeing 747s
worldwide to check the cargo doors, but Boeing spokesman David
Jimenez said the notices were ``by no means'' speculating on the
cause of the accident.
   Dickinson said Monday's inspection revealed the plane's oxygen
system failed after the accident on the New Zealand-bound flight.
The accident occurred 100 miles south of Honolulu at 22,000 feet,
but none of the survivors appeared to suffer long-term affects from
lack of oxygen, officials said.
   Of the 354 people aboard Flight 811, 27 were treated at
hospitals, mostly for minor injuries caused by flying debris. Two
remained hospitalized Monday.
   A preliminary review of the cockpit voice recorder showed the
pilot had no warning of the accident and the cockpit crew discussed
only emergency procedures afterward, not a possible cause or
warning, Dickinson said.
   He refused to quote the recorder, but described it as a ``good
tape'' that captured the accident and its aftermath.
   United has refused to allow Cronin or the rest of the 18-member
crew to talk to reporters about the flight.
   Twigg-Smith said Flight 811 to New Zealand and Australia and the
return flight were to be her father's last after 34 years with
United.
   ``He said to me, `There were a couple of times I didn't think we
were going to make it.''' Twigg-Smith, who also lives in Hawaii,
told the newspaper. ``I'm pretty sure he told me he was scared. The
problem of losing altitude, of keeping the airplane up, scared him.''
   Hart said her father told her, ``I felt like I needed a cold
beer,'' when describing his feelings as he flew the crippled
jetliner.
   Cronin's daughters said the retirement party is still scheduled
for March 11 in Hawaii. Hart said her father, who has returned to
his home in North Lake Tahoe, Nev., has expanded the guest list.
   ``He wants to invite all the flight attendants who were aboard
Flight 811,'' Hart said.
</TEXT>
