<FIRST>u w AM-US-Mideast     02-28 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Mideast,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Gives PLO Its Negative Appraisal of Raid in South Lebanon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department confronted the Palestine
Liberation Organization Tuesday over a raid near Israel's border but
withheld any judgment on whether Chairman Yasser Arafat had broken
his pledge renouncing terrorism.
   Seizing on a PLO request for a meeting in Tunis, the U.S.
designated contact, Ambassador Robert Pelletreau, criticized last
Thursday's raid as having a negative impact on the two-month-old
U.S.-PLO dialogue and on prospects for Israel-Palestinian talks.
   ``There is no ambivalence how we feel,'' spokesman Charles E.
Redman said. ``We don't condone this type of operation.''
   Three guerrillas from the Democratic Front for the Liberation of
Palestine, a radical faction of the PLO, attacked Israeli soldiers
and Christian militiamen in southern Lebanon about a mile from the
Israeli border. They were gunned down without other loss of life.
   The Israeli government said the guerrillas were attempting to
infiltrate Israel itself.
   In a similar incident, five guerrillas from two other factions of
the PLO were intercepted and slain in southern Lebanon on Feb. 4.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III and spokesman Redman
criticized that attack, as well. Baker said on Feb. 11 that
``actions such as this _ directed against civilian or military
targets, inside or outside of Israel _ were something that gave us
trouble.''
   After the incident the State Department said it was conducting an
investigation. Israeli Ambassador Moshe Arad charged the attack was
evidence that Arafat had never given up terrorism.
   Pelletreau's meeting with the PLO official, Hakam Ballaoui, in
Tunisia was the fifth with the organization since Arafat issued
statements urged on him by the Reagan administration in mid-December
renouncing terrorism and accepting Israel's right to exist.
   At the time, Richard W. Murphy, who was then assistant secretary
of state for the Near East, and other senior U.S. officials said the
new U.S. dialogue with the PLO would be suspended if terrorism
recurred.
   Asked if either of the two incidents in southern Lebanon were
instances of terrorism, Redman said: ``We have said from the very
start there are going to be things that would have to be addressed
on a case-by-case basis. That's what we are doing. And as we see
these various cases that arise we are making our views known to the
PLO.''
   He said Pelletreau had given Ballaoui the view of the latest raid
Redman issued on Monday. It was that the PLO ``cannot escape
responsibility'' for the attack and that ``we do not condone this
type of activity.''
   Redman said the raids and Israel's attack Tuesday on Palestinian
guerrilla positions in the Chouf Mountains of Lebanon underscored a
need for security arrangements to protect the people of both
countries.
   ``We deplore the loss of life and needless suffering of innocent
people on both sides,'' the spokesman said.
   Lebanese police said two guerrillas were killed and 38 people,
including 26 children, were injured in the Israeli bombing.
</TEXT>
