<FIRST>r w AM-NuclearSafety     02-28 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nuclear Safety,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commissioner Says Budget Restraints Hurt Nuclear Safety Effort</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tight limits on the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission budget during the Reagan administration seriously hurt
the agency's search for ways to improve nuclear plant safety, the
commission chairman told Congress on Tuesday.
   Lando W. Zech Jr. told a House Energy and Commerce subcommittee
that since 1984 the agency's budget had declined, even as attention
to safety needs had increased.
   ``The reductions have had a significant impact on our safety
research program over the years,'' Zech said. ``We believe this
trend must be reversed.''
   The NRC's current budget is $426 million, compared with $466
million in 1984.
   In presenting the commission's request for an 11 percent overall
budget increase, to $475 million for the year beginning Oct. 1, Zech
said half the extra money was ``urgently needed'' to strengthen
safety programs.
   Zech told the panel the safety record of the nation's 108 fully
operating nuclear power plants had improved in recent years, but
stressed that more work was needed _ by regulators as well as plant
owners _ to make nuclear power more reliable.
   ``We have not yet achieved excellence across the board,'' in
nuclear plant operations, he said, although plant owners are taking
safety requirements more seriously.
   Zech said the NRC, with a bigger budget for safety programs,
would increase the number of agency staffers assigned as resident
inspectors at nuclear plants. The commission currently has at least
one such inspector at each plant.
   ``We believed that the NRC resident inspection program has played
a significant role in improving industry safety performance and that
the expansion of the program is necessary to achieve further
improvements,'' Zech said.
   The commission chairman also said an agency decision was due as
early as next week on a proposed rule change aimed at speeding up
licensing for nuclear plants.
   The change would allow utilities to get federal approval for a
construction permit and an operating license before starting the
project. Under current rules, the NRC does not consider the
operating license application until after the construction has
begun. As a result, utilities in some cases have completed plants
but been unable to win approval to operate them.
   Zech called the proposed change an ``historic ruling,'' although
he added that he was still reviewing the proposal and had not
decided whether to vote for it. Several members of the committee
told Zech they strongly favored the change.
   Rep. Bob Clement, D-Tenn., said the commission should move
quickly to adopt the streamlined licensing system in order to
encourage expansion of nuclear power.
   ``Without standardization and licensing reform, it is very
unlikely that there will be additional orders of commercial nuclear
plants,'' Clement said. No orders have been placed for nuclear
plants since 1979, the year of the Three Mile Island reactor
accident in Pennsylvania that raised new safety concerns.
   Zech also told the panel the NRC was preparing to adopt shortly a
regulation requiring random drug and alcohol testing of employees at
all nuclear plants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890228-0108 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 1536EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Dam     02-28 0633</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Dam,0651</SECOND>
<HEAD>Intellectuals Blast Government Dam Proposal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than a dozen eminent Chinese intellectuals on
Tuesday criticized a proposed dam on the Yangtze River as an
ill-considered, wasteful project that would serve only as a memorial
to its builders.
   In a move extremely rare in this authoritarian society, the
informal alliance of of writers, engineers and former government
officials held a news conference to issue a book criticizing the
hydroelectric project.
   ``There is only one Yangtze River, and it belows to the entire
nation and all mankind,'' said Dai Qing, a newspaper editor who
compiled the book of essays. ``Mankind should not abuse it.''
   ``We have discussed this back and forth for more than 30 years
and still cannot resolve'' the problems, said 96-year-old Sun Yueqi,
who heads the economic committee of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Committee, a prestigious but powerless body of
intellectuals.
   ``When it comes to producing electricity, the dam is no good, and
it will destroy (river) shipping,'' he said.
   The government is in the final stages of studying the proposed
Three Gorges Hyroelectric Project, which calls for a 610-foot-high
dam in central China where the mighty Yangtze passes through
towering cliffs eulogized by Chinese poets for centuries.
   The project would generate up to 17,000 megawatts of electricity.
Cost estimates range from the official one of about $10 billion to
some critics' estimate of $30 billion.
   The idea of harnessing energy from the river's turbulent passage
through the Three Gorges in Hubei province first was suggested in
the 1920s. It has been considered repeatedly over the years but
never acted upon because of the huge expense, engineering difficulty
and what critics say would be serious damage to the environment and
river shipping.
   Nearly 1 million people would have to be moved to make way for a
vast new reservoir. The area also has been hit by earthquakes in the
past, and some critics say a quake could crack the dam and cause a
massive disaster.
   Leading writer Zhang Jie told the news conference that backers of
the project have not evaluated it scientifically but look on it as a
sort of personal monument. ``We don't want to put up a memorial
plaque that will win much fame but little benefit,'' she said.
   Premier Li Peng, formerly Minister of Power, is believed to be
one of its main supporters. Proponents say the project would help
solve China's energy shortage, control flooding and make the upper
reaches of the river accessible to larger ships.
   A Canadian consortium of government and corporate experts
concluded after a two-year study that the project is feasible and
rejected many of the objections of the critics. However, the critics
noted that several companies in the consortium are potential bidders
for dam contracts.
   Tuesday's news conference was the first time a group of
intellectuals dared to band together and express their opposition
publicly.
   Ms. Dai said the debate had to brought out into the open.
   ``Ordinary people know that many large projects ... have a direct
impact on them individually,'' she said. ``If the project goes well
it is called government funded, but in reality everyone who pays
taxes pays for it out of his own pocket. Ordinary people cannot
afford not to hear all the viewpoints.''
   Li Rui, who was vice minister of hydroelectric power in the 1950s
and vice minister of water conservancy in the early 1980s, said
instead of building one massive dam, smaller dams should be built on
tributaries of the Yangtze.
   Wu Jing, a senior government engineer who came to listen, agreed.
   Wu said that across town several hundred government experts were
holding one of a series of meetings to discuss the latest official
feasibility study.
   ``We're having competing meetings,'' he chuckled.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
