<FIRST>r a AM-SpeechDemons-Examples     02-28 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Speech Demons-Examples,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>This Be Talkin' Terrible? Yup, You Betcha</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Speech Demons, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An example of the ``speech demons'' targeted for
extinction in the New York City schools:
   ``Fred says he wasn't doin' nuttin'. So, I says to him, `I'm
goin' to da liberry, I'll meetcha there.' But he didn't know where
da liberry was at. I axe him, `Are youse foolin' round? It's like,
in midtown, you know. Pacifically, at da cau-nuh of 41st and Fifth.'
He axes me if I was on'y goin' to da liberry. No, I says. `What-cha
doin' next?' he axed. `First,' I says, `I'm goin' to da museum to
see some pitchers. Then, I'm goin' to see Lorenzo _ he be sick, and
he ain't got no food. I brang some soup for him.' I says I think
this is da right thing to do. `Yup, you betcha,' Fred says.''
   Now, the same encounter rendered in proper English.
   ``Fred said he wasn't doing anything. I told him, `I'm going to
the library. I'll meet you there.' He didn't know where the library
was. I asked him, `Are you fooling around? It's in midtown.
Specifically, it's at the corner of 41st Street and Fifth Avenue.'
He asked me if I was going only to the library. No, I said. `What
are you doing next?'' he asked. `First,' I said, I'm going to the
museum to see some pictures. Then, I'm going to see Lorenzo _ he's
sick and he has no food. I brought some soup for him.' I said I
thought this was the right thing to do. `Yes, you're right,' Fred
said.
</TEXT>
