<FIRST>r i AM-China-Dissident     02-28 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Dissident,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S.: No Plans For Further Action on Fang Flap</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Embassy said Tuesday it had ``no specific
plan'' to remonstrate further after China rejected any criticism of
its treatment of a well-known dissident.
   ``Our position stands,'' said embassy spokesman Sheridan W. Bell
after the Chinese Foreign Ministry said it resented the United
States' inviting Fang Lizhi to a dinner given by President Bush.
   Chinese police stopped Fang en route to the dinner Sunday night
and refused to let him attend.
   ``We expressed our regret two times. We've made our position
clear,'' Bell said in an interview. ``I'm sure we will continue to
bring up the issue of human rights in appropriate forums in the
future as we have in the past.''
   Bush told Vice Premier Wu Xueqian as he left Beijing on Monday
that he regretted the police action against Fang. U.S. Ambassador
Winston Lord met later Monday with Vice Foreign Minister Zhu Qizhen
and repeated the message.
   Bell said Tuesday that ``to my knowledge'' the ministry had not
formally responded to the U.S. statements. However, late Monday the
ministry issued a statement via the official Xinhua News Agency
saying China resented the invitation to Fang and regretted that a
fuss was made over his absence.
   ``There is no specific plan'' for the embassy to make further
remonstrances, Bell said, adding: ``We have said many times that we
don't always see eye-to-eye on many issues.''
   He defended the embassy for not having anticipated the Chinese
anger and escorted Fang to the dinner.
   ``We were all surprised,'' he said. ``There were 250 Chinese
guests. We don't go out and pick up 250 people.''
   Fang, a 53-year-old astrophysicist, is China's best-known
dissident. He has criticized Marxism as a failure and said that
economic development is impossible without democracy and respect for
human rights.
   On Monday, Fang refused to criticize Bush for not having raised
human rights issues during his China visit. But he said he believes
the United States holds China to a lower human rights standard than
it does the Soviet Union, and said he hoped this would change.
   Other dissidents have called on the United States and other
foreign countries to stop investing in China until the Communist
Party ceases human rights abuses.
</TEXT>
