<DOCNO> AP890228-0112 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 1555EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Scotus-Lawyer     02-28 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Lawyer,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Scotus Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Justices Weigh Lawyers' Ethical Obligations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Whether lawyers may be forced to represent poor
people in non-criminal federal cases was the subject of a lively
debate in the Supreme Court on Tuesday.
   John A. Mallard, a lawyer from rural Iowa who specializes in
business cases, told the justices he did not feel qualified to
represent prison inmates in a civil rights suit assigned by a judge.
   ``In my estimation, I was not competent to provide the services
required,'' Mallard said.
   Justice John Paul Stevens said Mallard seemed perfectly capable
of representing himself before the nation's highest court even
though he had no experience there.
   ``You had the exact same experience'' in federal civil rights
cases, said Stevens. ``Is that it? You don't need the skills up
here, but you did down there?''
   Mallard said he believed ``the skills are very different ... to
elicit testimony before a jury'' or argue an appeal before the
Supreme Court, where there are no witnesses to question.
   Opposing Mallard was Deputy Attorney General Gordon Allen of
Iowa, who said Mallard has a responsibility as a lawyer to do his
share of ``pro bono'' work _ representing the poor without
compensation.
   ``Lawyers have an ethical obligation,'' Allen said, adding,
``When the court calls, I answer.''
   Mallard of Fairfield, Iowa, was ordered to represent two current
inmates and a former inmate at the Iowa state prison in Fort
Madison. The inmates said prison guards and officials had filed
false disciplinary reports against them, physically mistreated them
and endangered their lives by revealing they were informants.
   A federal judge picked Mallard in 1987 from a list of more than
100 lawyers compiled by the Legal Services Corp. of Iowa and that
state's bar association.
   In addition to saying he lacked experience in trial work, Mallard
said the federal courts do not have power to require an unwilling
attorney to represent someone in a civil case.
   The possible penalties Mallard faces for his refusal to take the
case were not discussed. But presumably he could be held in contempt
and be fined or jailed.
   Courts routinely assign lawyers to represent indigent defendants
in criminal cases and the lawyers are paid, at taxpayer expense,
generally a fraction of what they would receive normally.
   In civil rights cases, lawyers are paid expenses and may receive
a share of any damages won by their clients.
   U.S. District Judge Harold D. Vietor denied Mallard's motion to
be excused from the inmates' suit. The judge said Mallard was
competent and had litigation experience.
   Some justices expressed sympathy Tuesday for one of Mallard's key
points _ that the federal law authorizing legal help for poor people
in civil cases says a judge only may ``request'' any attorney to
take the case.
   Allen said a request is sometimes a demand, for example, when a
general in the Army issues it.
   ``Words have no meaning if we start talking like that,'' shot
back Justice Antonin Scalia.
   Scalia said a lieutenant who refuses a general's request may
forfeit the opportunity for promotion. But, the justice added, that
does not mean the lieutenant can be court-martialed for refusing.
   The court is expected to announce a decision in Mallard's appeal
by July. The case is Mallard vs. U.S. District Court, 87-1490.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
