<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     02-28 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tamils Raid Village, Kill Dozens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tamils dressed in military uniforms
raided a village of Sinhalese rice paddy farmers and shot, stabbed
and hacked at least 37 people to death, survivors and officials said
Tuesday.
   At least 10 children and five women were among the victims of
Monday night's attack by the 20 militants in Welikande village in
the Polonnaruwa distict, about 100 miles northeast of Colombo.
   A military official in Colombo, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said soldiers patrolling the area discovered five bodies
Tuesday, raising the toll to 37.
   ``We have a total of 37 corpses: 22 males, five women and 10
children, most of them hacked to death. Some of the males had
gunshot injuries,'' the military official said. Under briefing
rules, he cannot be identified.
   Police who were contacted by telephone in Polonnaruwa town and
spoke on condition of anonimity blamed the attack on the Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam, but a Tiger leader telephoned The Associated
Press and denied his group was responsible.
   An official statement by the Tigers said, ``We condemn this as an
act of terrorism.''
   The Tigers are the most powerful of the Tamil separatist groups
that have been waging a bloody separatist war since 1983. The ethnic
struggle against the island nation's Sinhalese majority has claimed
more than 8,500 lives.
   The Welikande attack was the third massacre of Sinhalese
civilians in northeastern Sri Lanka this month. At least 80 people
were killed in the three attacks.
   On Feb. 11, 36 Sinhalese were shot and stabbed to death in
Dutuwewa. On Feb. 22, seven Sinhalese were killed at Sinhapura.
   The Tigers' information office in London denied the first two
attacks were the work of their people.
   Indian troops have been deployed in northeastern Sri Lanka since
July 1987 when Sri Lanka signed an agreement with India aimed at
ending the Tamil insurgency. Tamils were given a limited measure of
autonomy while Indian troops were deputed to disarm militants among
the Tamils.
   After initially agreeing to the accord, the Tigers reneged and
returned to opposing the Sinhalese-dominated government.
   Welikande is in predominantly Sinhalese North Central Province
near the border with Eastern Province, which has a mixed Sinhalese,
Tamil and Moslem population.
   A former militant Tamil leader-turned-legislator said the Tigers
were on ``a headline-hunting exercise.''
   The chief minister of the northeastern administrative council,
Varatharaja Perumal, said the Tigers had been ``badly mauled'' by
Indian troops and were ``showing off their fangs by killing innocent
Sinhalese.''
   Perumal earlier headed the Eelam People's Revolutionary
Liberation Front, a rebel militia and former ally of the Tigers. The
front surrendered its arms and contested provincial elections in an
effort to politically realise Tamil aspirations.
   Mostly Hindu Tamils comprise 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million
people. Militants claim they are discriminated against in education,
employment and culture by the predominantly Buddhist Sinhalese, who
make up 75 percent of the country's population and control the
administration and military.
</TEXT>
