<TEXT>
   Here is a look at Tuesday's mayoral primary in
Chicago to decide the Democratic and Republican party candidates for
the general election in April when the winners face Alderman Tim
Evans running as an independent.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   At stake: Mayoralty of the City of Chicago, population 3 million.
   Registered voters: 1,549,367.
   Projected turnout: 68 percent.
   General election: April 4.
   Term: two years, expiring in 1991; to fill rest of four-year term
left by Harold Washington, the city's first black mayor. Washington
died of a heart attack Nov. 25, 1987.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>DEMOCRATS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Richard M. Daley, 46, Cook County state's attorney and son of
legendary Chicago Mayor Richard J. Daley. Daley lost his first bid
for mayor in the 1983 primary.
