<FIRST>r i AM-MappaMundi     02-28 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mappa Mundi,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hereford Cathedral Abandons Plan to Sell Medieval Treasure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HEREFORD, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governors of Hereford Cathedral, who
caused a national uproar by putting a 13th-century map on the
auction block, said Tuesday that the medieval treasure is no longer
for sale.
   The dean and chapter, the governing authority of the cathedral,
said several alternate plans had been proposed to raise about $12.3
million for repairs and programs.
   ``There are negotiations with a good many people, but if any were
named or mentioned, they might withdraw from the package,'' said
Canon Leonard Moss.
   ``We are at a fairly delicate stage at the moment, but we did
want people to be aware that we are sufficiently confident to feel
we do not have to press ahead with the auction in June.''
   The cathedral had hoped to raise $4.4 million from the sale of
the map, which shows Jerusalem at the center of the world and
Hereford on the edge. Historical events, Bible stories, animals,
plans and 420 cities are shown on a sheet of vellum measuring 65
inches by 53 inches.
   The map, known by its Latin name ``Mappa Mundi,'' was drawn and
painted by Richard of Haldingham in 1275.
   Moss said the controversy had made the map so famous that it
could no longer be safely displayed in a dark corner of the
cathedral, and a separate building might be required.
   Emma Nicholson, a Conservative member of Parliament, said in
London that the news was ``a miracle among miracles.''
   ``I was appalled at the idea that a national treasure should be
auctioned at Sotheby's as if it was a cracked cup and saucer,'' Miss
Nicholson said. ``It is a pearl among pearls, beyond price.''
   Lord Gowrie, the chairman of Sotheby's and an adviser to the
cathedral, said he felt no regret at losing the sale.
   ``I am particularly happy that the conclusion which I personally
have always been striving for _ that the Mappa Mundi will remain in
Hereford _ has been achieved,'' he said.
</TEXT>
