<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 1659EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Oxy-FuelsProgram     02-28 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oxy-Fuels Program,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>Colorado's Second Oxygenated Fuels Program Ends</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colorado's four-month oxygenated fuels program to
cut carbon monoxide pollution ended Tuesday without having created
the stir that clouded the mandatory program's debut last year.
   ``There just wasn't the attention on it this year since everybody
had gone through it once,'' said Ted Hollman, senior air pollution
control specialist for the state health department.
   ``Once people found out all the doomsday predictions didn't come
true, they stopped thinking about it,'' he said.
   Mechanics in the Denver area reported few problems as a result of
the oxygenated fuels, although older cars had more trouble than
newer ones.
   As for suppliers, John Augustine of Conoco said the program ``was
much smoother this year because we had a lot of lead time. ... We
had the whole year to know it's coming and get the tanks and
everything ready.''
   Conoco even plans to continue offering an ethanol-blended
gasoline after the program ends ``and see how the sales go,''
Augustine said.
   State Rep. Tom Ratterree, a critic of the program mainly because
it is mandatory, said he still believes the fuels are creating
problems in people's cars and motorists simply aren't aware of the
cause.
   ``The car may not run but they don't know why,'' Ratterree said.
``If I were to generate an awareness level out there, then people
would come out of the woodwork again.''
   The program was in effect along Colorado's Front Range from Fort
Collins and Greeley in the north to Colorado Springs in the south,
including the Denver area.
   The oxygenated fuels are actually blends of ordinary gasoline and
either grain alcohol (ethanol) or the ether-based MTBE. Nearly 2
million cars and trucks ran on the fuels every day, Hollman said.
   At Denver's mile-high altitude, ordinary fuel burns incompletely
in engines, and the unexpended fuel emitted into the air adds to
pollution, especially during winter months when temperature
inversions trap the smog. High-oxygen fuels burn more cleanly.
   Last year, the oxygenated fuels program ran just two months and
cut carbon monoxide emissions an average 9.5 percent, officials said.
   This year, the goal was 12 percent. The amount of oxygen required
in the fuels was increased from 1.5 percent to 2 percent, resulting
in the use of more ethanol, Hollman said.
   Preliminary results of the oxygenated fuels program and the
three-month Better Air Campaign, which ended in January and included
voluntary no-drive days and voluntary and mandatory woodburning
bans, were expected later this week.
   The combined programs last year dropped Denver from first to
seventh place on the Environmental Protection Agency's list of worst
cities for carbon monoxide pollution.
   The Rocky Mountain Oil and Gas Association, a trade association
for the industry, opposes the program's mandatory provisions and
disputes its environmental benefits.
   ``As far as consumer satisfaction, consumers are relatively
satisfied because there has been a choice of oxygenated fuels,''
said special projects director Pam Oldham.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890228-0118 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 1722EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-GehrigStamp     02-28 0143</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gehrig Stamp,130</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iron Man to Get Postage Stamp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iron man Lou Gehrig will be featured on a new
commemorative postage stamp this summer, the Postal Service reported
Tuesday.
   The stamp honoring the former New York Yankees hitter will be
issued June 10 at the Baseball Hall of Fame in Cooperstown, N.Y.
   Gehrig played a record 2,130 consecutive games, batting cleanup
behind slugger Babe Ruth in the Yankees' famous ``Murderer's Row''
lineup.
   During his career, Gehrig hit 493 home runs, driving in 100 or
more runs 13 seasons in a row and batting .340 lifetime.
   Gehrig took the field for the Yankees June 2, 1925, and didn't
miss a game until May 2, 1939, after he was diagnosed as suffering
from the fatal disease amyotrophic lateral sclerosis. That disease
has since come to be known as Lou Gehrig's disease.
</TEXT>
