<DOCNO> AP890228-0119 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 1726EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Governors     02-28 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Governors,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governors Talk `Fiscal Insanity,' Government Responsibility</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal budget deficits were decried Tuesday as
``fiscal insanity'' as the nation's governors wound up a meeting
marked by grudging acceptance of a steady drop in federal aid to the
states.
   ``A fundamental shift has taken place in American government,''
Gov. Gerald Baliles of Virginia, chairman of the National Governors'
Association, told a news conference at the end of the group's annual
midwinter meeting.
   The Democrat said that ``a large measure of the responsibility
for governing this country has shifted from Washington down to the
states.''
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, told the closing
session of the conference that the budget crisis was ``so critical''
the Democratic Congress and the Republican president had to ``summon
the resolve'' to come up with a plan together to reduce the deficit.
   Mitchell was responding to Democratic Gov. Cecil Andrus of Idaho
who referred to ``the fiscal insanity that presently prevails in
this city'' and who asked, ``Does the Congress have the will this
year to return us to some form of fiscal sanity.''
   ``It cannot be done alone by the Congress,'' replied Mitchell. He
said any progress would require the cooperation of the
administration.
   The Maine senator described the budget as ``a statement of our
nation's priorities,'' and he pointed out to the governors that they
had approved policy statements ``that call for increased federal
spending in a large number of areas.''
   At the same time, he said, the governors' association also had a
policy position ``which calls for meaningful deficit reduction.''
   Mitchell said he had attended a breakfast meeting with President
Bush and that they ``reaffirmed this morning our commitment to a
cooperative effort on the budget and other areas.''
   The governors put off until their summer meeting action on an
updated position on the the budget deficit.
   ``There are such a lot of unanswered questions about the details
of the president's budget, it's easy to understand why the governors
are not yet ready to adopt a budget policy position,'' Baliles said.
   He said the governors had supported past congressional efforts to
reduce the deficit and ``we will support Congress this year.''
   Among the policy positions adopted by the governors were:
   _ Endorsement of self-determination for Puerto Rico;
   _ Support of legislation to require uniform poll closing times
throughout the continental United States;
   _Tougher emissions standards for automobiles and reauthorization
of the Clean Air Act;
   _ Appropriation of $2.4 billion in federal assistance to the
states for construction of wastewater treatment plants. The proposed
federal budget would appropriate only half that amount.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
