<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 1743EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-DanceHallDispute     02-28 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dance Hall Dispute,0600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Freedom of Association Key In Supreme Court Dance Hall Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLEY SHANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owner of a defunct roller skating rink says a
city law setting age limits at teen dance halls ruined his business.
He sued, and now the U.S. Supreme Court is reviewing the issue as a
freedom of association case.
   ``The court has never really squarely faced the issue of an
individual's right to associate for a purely social or cultural
purpose,'' said Daniel Sheehan, an attorney for rink owner Michael
Stanglin.
   Craig Hopkins, the assistant city attorney handling the case,
said he believes the justices want to go on record stating that
freedom of association in social settings is not covered by the
Constitution, a ruling that could effect civil rights as well as
protecting the recreational gathering places restricted to
teen-agers that have sprung up around the country.
   The Supreme Court is to hear the case Wednesday.
   Stanglin's Twilight Skating Rink fell under the dance hall law
because its floor, divided with traffic cones, had skating and
dancing sections. A city ordinance enacted in 1985 allows only
youngsters ages 14 to 18 and their parents or guardians in dance
halls that serve teen-agers.
   ``I think the city was well-intentioned with this, but they just
went over the line,'' Stanglin said. He contends the ordinance
unfairly singles out dancing establishments, while other gathering
places, such as parks or ice cream parlors, allow people of any age
to associate.
   ``That means that a 19-year-old guy cannot come in with his
18-year-old girlfriend,'' he said. ``If you had a 13-year-old in
there, you're in violation.''
   When he began complying with the ordinance, Stanglin said, his
crowd dropped from 800 one week to about 200 the next, then less
than 20 the third week.
   ``It has cost me a considerable amount of financial tragedy,''
said Stanglin, who closed the Twilight in 1986 but owns a second
rink in a Dallas suburb.
   Stanglin sued the city in July 1986, and a trial court ruled
against him.
   In October 1987, a state Court of Appeals ruled in Stanglin's
favor, striking down the part of the ordinance dealing with age. The
court said it interfered with young people's constitutional right to
associate with whom they please.
   ``It is primarily the responsibility of the parent, not the city,
to tell the minor how old his dance partner may be,'' the appeals
court said. ``The answer lies in supervision, not in strict
segregation by age group.''
   The Texas Supreme Court declined to hear the case.
   The city's request that the U.S. Supreme Court reinstate the
ordinance said, ``The potential harm comes from the association with
persons who may influence the behavior of the children not only at
the dance hall where supervision exists but also away from the dance
hall.''
   Hopkins said the ordinance does not limit freedom of association.
If anything, it expands it by creating a special category of dance
halls where teen-agers are allowed, he said.
   The Supreme Court already has defined freedom of association in
political and sex discrimination cases. In the 1950s the justices
upheld the right of the National Association for the Advancement of
Colored People to withhold its membership list from Alabama
authorities.
   In 1984, the Supreme Court ruled that the Jaycees could not
exclude women. The court has ruled that civic groups and private
clubs may only exclude people by sex or religion when it is
essential to the organization's purposes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890228-0121 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 1544EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Trade     02-28 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trade,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Deficit Grows 10 Percent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. trade deficit worsened in the final
three months of the year, climbing to $32 billion, as both U.S.
exports and imports hit record levels, the government reported
Tuesday.
   The Commerce Department said the deficit from October through
December swelled by 10 percent from a third quarter deficit of
$29.17 billion.
   The trade deficit had shown steady improvement through the first
three quarters of 1988, helping to push the deficit for the entire
year down to $126.5 billion, 21.7 percent below the all-time high of
$160.28 billion set in 1987.
   While economists were pleased with the big improvement for the
year, they expressed fears that the improvement has now stalled and
will hold back overall economic growth in 1989.
   ``The trade deficit has stopped improving,'' said David Wyss, an
economist with Data Resources Inc., of Lexington, Mass. ``We made
some big gains in exports in 1987 and 1988 but they haven't been
enough to balance our big appetite for imports.''
   Tuesday's trade figures confirmed an improvement already noted in
the Commerce Department's monthly merchandise trade reports. Those
figures showed the deficit declining to $137.34 billion in 1988,
down from $170.3 billion in 1987.
   The new report, which measures trade on a balance-of-payments
basis, has smaller figures because it subtracts shipping costs and
military sales from the monthly numbers.
   Another measure of trade, contained in the report on the gross
national product released Tuesday, also showed a worsening in the
deficit for the fourth quarter of 1988. Unlike the other trade
figures, the GNP report removes the effects of inflation from the
import and export numbers.
   The report on merchandise trade on a balance-of-payments basis
showed that exports rose $2 billion to a record level of $83.6
billion in the fourth quarter while imports climbed $4.8 billion to
a record $115.7 billion.
   The trade deficit with Japan also set a record, rising by $3.2
billion to $15.5 billion in the fourth quarter.
   The largest increase in imports came in autos, up $1.8 billion,
reflecting higher shipments from South Korea, Japan and Mexico.
Imports of consumer goods, including apparel and household goods,
rose by $1.6 billion.
   On the export side, shipments of manufactured goods rose 4
percent while farm shipments fell by 6 percent.
   For the year, the decline in the deficit to $126.5 billion
reflected a 28 percent surge in export sales and a 9 percent rise in
imports.
   But Wyss said he expected little further improvement in 1989,
saying the trade performance will not move off current high levels
until the dollar weakens further, making imports even more expensive
and U.S. goods more competitive on overseas markets.
   Non-farm exports rose 28 percent to $61.6 billion in 1988, with
the largest increases in sales of U.S. capital equipment and
industrial supplies.
   Agricultural exports shot up 30 percent to $38.3 billion, their
highest level since 1984.
   The largest increases were in sales of corn, which were up $1.9
billion, reflecting higher sales to the Soviet Union, Japan and
Taiwan; and in wheat, which also climbed by $1.9 billion, reflecting
higher shipments to China and the Soviet Union.
   The farm sales increase reflected in part higher prices caused by
the severe drought. The average price of corn was up 38 percent for
the year, while the price of soybeans rose by 33 percent, wheat
prices were up 20 percent and cotton prices rose 20 percent.
</TEXT>
