<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 1928EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-AlcoholPuzzle     02-28 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Alcohol Puzzle,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Experts' Advice on Tower's Pledge: Believe it When You See it</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tower Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary-designate John Tower says
he'll stop drinking if the Senate confirms him to the Cabinet, but
experts on alcohol abuse say: Believe it when you see it.
   Professionals who deal daily with drinkers' rationalizations say
vows of sobriety are easily made, but rarely kept.
   ``I'm sure he intends every word that he says. The question is,
can he do it?'' said Marc Hertzman, professor of psychiatry and
behavioral sciences at George Washington University. ``I think the
Senate would be ill-advised to draw conclusions from that vow.''
   Tower, whose nomination comes before the Senate this week, has
admitted to heavy drinking in the past. But in an extraordinary
television interview on Sunday, he said he drinks less now and he
vowed not to drink ``beverage alcohol of any type or form, including
wine, beer or spirits of any kind'' if he is confirmed to the
Cabinet position.
   Hertzman denounces the idea that the urge to drink can be
controlled so easily.
   ``Let's assume that only a very small part of what has been
rumored about the gentleman has any validity to it at all,'' said
Hertzman. ``The notion that he could just stop is about 180 degrees
counter to anything that anybody knows about the problem of dealing
with drinking alcohol.''
   He said that in some cases, six months of total abstinence would
be convincing, but with other people it could take two years or
more, or even be a struggle that lasts a lifetime.
   ``If I were a senator, I think at the very least I would defer
his confirmation until he proves that he can go six months,'' said
the psychiatrist. ``That's a minimum figure to establish that you
don't need it. A year and a half is more like it.''
   Dr. William E. Flynn, director of the alcohol and drug abuse
clinic at Georgetown University, said that Tower's sobriety vow
alone is not persuasive to professionals in the alcohol treatment
field.
   He said if senators have to base their confirmation decision on
Tower's drinking history, ``it would be a tough one.''
   ``What a corporation would do (for an executive in a similar
situation) is decide that there must be an evaluation. But that's
not possible here,'' said Flynn. ``One would feel a lot more
comfortable if you get an evaluation and a clean bill of health.''
   Tower did release a letter from Dr. Warren Lichtliter, a Dallas
physician who examined the former senator recently in connection
with a surgical procedure. Lichtliter said Tower had a normal liver
function and showed no evidence of alcohol withdrawal.
   ``Based on these facts, it can be stated with relative certainty
that Senator Tower shows no evidence at all of alcoholic impairment
or alcoholism,'' the Texas doctor wrote. ``It is my professional
view that there is little basis for statements made concerning the
possible impairment by alcohol of his ability to perform his duty as
secretary of defense.''
   Hertzman scoffs at that reasoning.
   ``That's baloney, pure and simple,'' he said. The statement, he
said, ``doesn't tell us everything we need to know in order to
answer the questions that are relevant.''
   Flynn agrees, saying, ``The question is, would it be possible to
present these findings (from Lichtliter) and there still be an
alcohol problem? The answer is yes.''
   Tower said that he once drank scotch heavily, but gave it up 12
years ago and ``essentially has been a wine drinker'' only at meals
since then.
   ``All that tells me is that someone shifted their alcohol intake
from one form to another,'' said Flynn.
   ``A glass of wine is roughly equivalent in alcohol content to a
jigger of scotch,'' said Hertzman. ``Everything we know about
alcohol abuse suggests that it doesn't matter in what form you get
the alcohol. What matters is how much alcohol you get.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
