<DOCNO> AP890228-0124 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 1934EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Poland     02-28 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0624</SECOND>
<HEAD>Party Leader Warns That Reforms Cannot Derail Communism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski has
issued a strong warning that he won't let introduction of greater
freedoms threaten the country's communist system.
   Jaruzelski, emphasizing that he was addressing army officers,
decried ``noisy, confrontational and anarchy-prone pluralism leading
nowhere,'' according to excerpts of a speech Monday to the Communist
Party organization for the Pomerania army district. The excerpts
were published Tuesday.
   Jaruzelski spoke the same day Prime Minister Mieczyslaw F.
Rakowski apologized to the Soviet ambassador to Poland for student
demonstrations over the weekend in which officials say students
desecrated a monument to Soviet soldiers.
   Authorities have been cautiously introducing increased openness
and freedom in recent weeks, but appear anxious about the
possibility that the liberalization could lead to chaotic strikes or
demonstrations that could get out of control.
   ``A question appears here about safeguards so that we will not be
pushed off the road of socialism. That is out of the question,''
Jaruzelski said in the speech to army officers in the northwest city
of Bydgoszcz, according to the official PAP news agency.
   ``Whoever has such an intention, let him put it out of his head.
The fact that I state this at just this place, at just this time,
also will be a warning,'' he said.
   Jaruzelski, who imposed 1{ years of martial law in Poland
beginning Dec. 13, 1981, said the return of social stability has
made possible the current talks between the government and the
opposition.
   But he said questions were emerging, ``whether the 13th of
December 1981 and all of our joint, tremendous effort to save Poland
will be threatened and lost by the developing situation. This is a
justified question.''
   Since a January decision by the Communist Party to permit trade
union pluralism, which cleared the way for the talks on making legal
again the banned trade union Solidarity, Polish reforms have entered
a ``profoundly expanded'' phase, he said.
   The talks with Solidarity leader Lech Walesa and other opposition
leaders began Feb. 6.
   Now, ex-political prisoners routinely sit at negotiating tables
across from representatives of the authorities who put them in jail,
underground press reporters question government ministers at news
conferences, and the once-forbidden Solidarity emblem is seen in
public places.
   The openness has also been accompanied by dozens of small strikes
and frequent demonstrations by students and other groups.
   ``There can be an enlightened pluralism, creative, constructive
and mobilizing national energy,'' Jaruzelski said. ``But there can
also be a noisy confrontational and anarchy-prone pluralism leading
nowhere.
   ``We intend to expand and consolidate the first one, but we
should and we will condemn and fight the latter.''
   The party leader, who is also commander-in-chief of the army,
said Poland is threatened by ``a strike-and-protest `festival''' and
by ``attempts at creating anarchy in social life.''
   Apparently referring to recent student protests in Krakow,
Jaruzelski said, ``I have always been and I still am an advocate of
reacting with patience and understanding to the emotions of young
people. However there are certain limits and they must not be
exceeded.''
   He said the police and education ministries should ``draw
appropriate conclusions.''
   Jaruzelski criticized as ``cowardly'' some previously silent
critics who are taking advantage of the new liberalized atmosphere
to attack authorities verbally.
   ``Some blows the party has been suffering are below the belt,''
he said. ``Some methods, be it publications, statements or
declarations, closely resemble what we had in 1981 (before martial
law) when the `rats' hurriedly abandoned ship.
   ``That ship, socialist Poland, has been unsinkable and so it will
stay.''
</TEXT>
