<FIRST>u a AM-BostonBusing Bjt   02-28 0682</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boston Busing, Bjt,0698</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boston Desegregation Fight Could Head Back To Court</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifteen years after the fierce battle began to
desegregate its schools, Boston appears to be back at square one
with school board members split along racial lines over plans to
improve integration.
   Civil rights leaders said Tuesday they're ready to go back to
court unless changes are made in a plan that would end court-ordered
busing by allowing parents to shop around for a school of their
choice.
   ``It's a back door into segregation, an old tired rusty car with
a new coat of paint,'' said Louis Elisa, president of the Boston
branch of the NAACP. ``If there isn't substantial change in this
process, (which is a) resegregation of the public schools, the NAACP
does not feel compelled to sit on the sidelines and let that
happen.''
   Supporters of the school assignment plan say the competition
would spur improvements, lure back whites to the system they fled
during busing, and cut long bus rides.
   Opponents say the plan could open the door to a further exodus of
white students, and that it could not work without more money to
improve the overall system.
   Monday night, the nine white members of the School Committee
voted for the plan. The four black members voted against it.
   Ellen Guiney, education adviser to Mayor Raymond Flynn, who is
supporting the plan, said city officials hope to work out an
agreement with the plan's foes, but are confident the assignment
plan will withstand any legal challenge.
   Under the assignment plan, the city would be divided into three
geographical zones and parents would be allowed to choose within the
zones, provided it did not upset racial balance and there is space.
The plan is scheduled to be implemented this fall for students in
kindergarten through grade 6. Other grades would be assigned in
September 1990.
   Thomas Atkins, an attorney who represented black parents in a
1972 suit demanding that Boston schools desegregate, said he's not
surprised that the city still hasn't laid the desegregation issue to
rest.
   ``Boston and the school committee has never been without those
whose most fervent desire was to return the system to the mode it
had before the federal court intervened,'' he said.
   Busing was imposed in Boston in 1974 by order of U.S. District
Judge W. Arthur Garrity Jr., triggering rock-throwing violence and
white flight. Boston schools went from a 1972 population of 96,000
students, 60 percent of them white, to the current 59,000 students,
24 percent of them white.
   The system is plagued by a perennial budget crunch and a 40
percent high school dropout rate.
   Its poor academic reputation is well known. Boston University
basketball coach Mike Jarvis, for example, said recently that some
college recruiters told him they don't recruit players from Boston
because they feel they are a poor bet to keep up academically in
college.
   Guiney acknowledged that the school system is in trouble, but
said the assignment plan has at least focused attention on its
problems.
   ``We do know that the education in the Boston schools now is
generally unsatisfactory to everybody,'' she said. ``The problems
are serious. There is consensus that it's a system very nearly in
crisis.''
   Garrity returned some control of the system to the School
Committee in 1985. In 1987, a federal appeals court ruled that
Boston was complying with desegregation orders.
   Despite the continuing legal battle, Atkins said there has been
progress during the past 15 years, with desegregated schools and
more minority faculty members systemwide.
   He said the assignment plan prevents students from transferring
to a new school if that would upset the racial balance, but it does
not address the effect a student's departure would have on the first
school. He said in trying to balance Boston's schools, any risk of
imbalance cannot be taken.
   ``It's like a rubber band. So long as you keep it stretched
between your two hands it maintains its shape, but as soon as you
let go it snaps back,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890228-0127 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 1615EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Senate-Trip Bjt   02-28 0733</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senate-Trip, Bjt,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Subcommittee Members Shy Away from Chairman's Proposed Trip</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most members of a Senate panel are shying away
from a six-nation foreign trip that their chairman says is not a
junket but will combine work with visits to ``museums, art
galleries, and religious and historical sites.''
   In a letter dated Feb. 7, Sen. Daniel Inouye, D-Hawaii, new
chairman of the Senate Appropriations defense subcommittee, invited
17 colleagues to join him on a trip to Germany, Italy, Turkey,
Egypt, Israel and Spain.
   ``Far from being a `congressional junket,' this trip will take us
to areas which I believe we need to visit to understand the
dimensions of the problems confronting U.S. national security and to
meet the responsibilities we face as members of the subcommittee on
defense,'' Inouye wrote. The Associated Press obtained a copy of the
letter.
   The trip is scheduled during the Senate's Easter vacation in the
last two weeks of March.
   ``I also intend to make a special effort to allow time for visits
to museums, art galleries, and religious and historical sites in the
capitals and the countryside of these countries,'' Inouye wrote.
   Such broad tours are crucial to understanding the ``shared
values'' which link the United States to its friends and allies, the
senator said.
   The itinerary calls for three nights in Munich, three in Rome,
two in Istanbul, three in Cairo, three in Jerusalem and one in
Madrid.
   The route was designed to allow members to see ```fracture
zones'' of the geopolitical world, said Inouye, whose subcommittee
oversees spending for the Defense Department and the CIA.
   Along the way, the senators would share Easter services with
American forces aboard a ship in the Persian Gulf and review
fundamental changes under way in the Middle East peace process.
   Inouye urged the senators to bring along their wives because of
``certain responsibilities in the areas of protocol and diplomacy''
associated with meetings with heads of state and high-level
officials abroad.
   Congressional spouses travel free with their mates on military
aircraft, but they must pay their own expenses. The government picks
up all expenses for members of Congress. They receive daily per diem
at the same rate as U.S. diplomats abroad. For example, the daily
rate is $163 in Munich and $98 in Cairo.
   The congressional party will fly on an Air Force jet ``to ensure
that we accomplish the objectives of our trip and to add a measure
of security,'' Inouye said.
   So far, only Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., has accepted Inouye's
invitation, according to an informal head count. ``He's new on the
committee and he wants to see all the installations,'' said his
spokesman, Steven Schlein.
   Sens. Arlen Specter, R-Pa.; Bennett Johnston, D-La.; and Jake
Garn, R-Utah, are undecided about whether to go.
   At least 13 subcommittee members said they have no plans to go,
most of them citing prior commitments and more pressing business at
home.
   But Sen. Warren Rudman, R-N.H., isn't going in part because he
doesn't like being in a ``large delegation. ... He tends to prefer
trips that are more focused,'' said his spokesman, Paul Jacobson.
   Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, said he didn't have problems with the
trip, but wasn't planning to go because ``I took those trips when I
was the chairman'' of the subcommittee. Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt.,
declined because he recently returned from the Middle East, an aide
said.
   A State Department official familiar with the trip, speaking on
condition of anonymity, said arrangements, such as the exact dates,
are not yet firm.
   In the Senate, foreign trips on behalf of a committee must be
approved full committee chairman, while those on behalf of the full
Senate must have the approval of the chamber's majority and minority
leaders.
   Inouye has yet to formally request the approval of Sen. Robert
Byrd, D-W.Va., chairman of the appropriations committee, according
to Marsha Berry, the committee spokeswoman.
   Byrd, also a member of the defense panel, will not accompany
Inouye. ``He plans to travel to West Virginia; that's the only
traveling he'll do in March,'' said Tina Evans, a spokeswoman.
   These senators have other plans for the recess, according to the
members or their aides: Ernest F. Hollings, D-S.C.; Jim Sasser,
D-Tenn.; Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz.; Dale Bumpers, D-Ark.; Tom
Harkin, D-Iowa; James McClure, R-Idaho; Bob Kasten, R-Wis.; Alfonse
D'Amato, R-N.Y., and Thad Cochran, R-Miss.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
