<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 1623EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Senate Bjt   02-28 0701</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Senate, Bjt,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Risks Much in Tower Battle, but Defeat Won't Spell Disaster</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stakes are substantial for President Bush
in the John Tower confirmation struggle, but lawmakers say a defeat
in his first major political battle may have no major lasting effect
on his ability to deal effectively with the Democratic majorities in
Congress.
   A victory would be an unquestioned personal achievement for the
president, particularly after his decision to take command of the
lobbying battle at a time when Tower's chances of confirmation as
defense secretary were in jeopardy.
   ``The president isn't going to rise or fall on the issue,'' said
Sen. William Armstrong, R-Colo., who is undecided on the Tower
nomination.
   ``I don't think it sets the stage for the next four years,''
agreed Sen. John Breaux, D-La., who is leaning against confirmation.
   ``You can read more into it'' than is warranted, agreed Sen.
Richard Shelby, D-Ala., a conservative southerner opposed to Tower.
He said if the nomination fails, Bush would ``take a solid lick. But
it is early in the presidency. It depends on how resilient he is.''
   That is not to say the struggle over Tower is without cost,
particularly since it has become a partisan struggle with most
Democrats opposed and most Republicans in support.
   Bush is faced with two equally unpleasant alternatives if it
becomes clear that Tower is not going to be confirmed, either to
withdraw the nomination without a vote or to go down fighting.
Either way, he comes out a loser.
   The administration has been functioning without a defense
secretary for a month. It will be weeks more until one can take
office if Tower is rejected.
   For their parts, Senate Democrats are wary of the possible costs
to themselves of sinking Tower's nomination. They had hoped to avoid
a showdown with the new president until a later date, and Democrat
after Democrat was eager to point out to reporters on Tuesday that
Bush's other Cabinet appointees have all been confirmed without a
single negative vote.
   One senior Democratic senator, speaking anonymously, said
Majority Leader George Mitchell and Armed Services Committee
Chairman Sam Nunn, were ``worried about the appearance of
partisanship'' in dealing with a newly elected president.
   The Senate Armed Services Committee has devoted practically all
of its time to the nomination, with hearings on defense strategy,
spending, procurement reform, and other matters been pushed aside.
   Nunn, D-Ga., who has spent years nurturing an image as a
bipartisan leader of the Senate on defense issues, has found himself
squarely in the middle of an issue that has become polarized almost
entirely along party lines.
   Sen. William Cohen, R-Maine, says he has ``not seen passions
inflamed over an issue such as this one'' in several years, and says
it will hinder chances of formulating bipartisan defense and foreign
policy.
   Democrats and some Republicans whisper that Jimmy Carter was
ill-advised to withdraw Ted Sorenson's nomination as CIA director in
1977 in the face of Senate opposition _ and believe Bush would be
wiser to stand and fight than to cut his losses and signal Tower to
withdraw.
   But there are other senators who have publicly or privately
suggested that Bush withdraw the nomination _ a move that would
spare them the need to make an extremely tough decision on how to
vote.
   The effect on Bush's ability to deal effectively on other issues
isn't as easy to calculate.
   Sen. James Sasser, D-Tenn., said, ``I think the president is
upping the stake substantially. I think if Tower is defeated it is
going to diminish his prestige here in Congress.''
   But Sasser, who is chairman of the Senate Budget Committee and
thus most likely to become the senator leading the Democrats into
battle with Bush, says budget concerns ``are independent of Tower.
   ``I think the administration can recover from the Tower problem
if the nomination is defeated but I think the real question is
whether the Tower problem is symptomatic of the failure of the
administration to get its program and its policies in a coherent and
convincing way.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITORS NOTE: David Espo has covered Congress since 1978.</NOTE>
</DOC>
