<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 1626EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Budget     02-28 0647</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Budget,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Greenspan Says Deficit Cut Would Bring Lower Interest Rates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan said
Tuesday that President Bush's proposed 1990 budget, if adopted,
would trigger lower interest rates even if it eventually produced a
deficit higher than $100 billion.
   Greenspan told the Senate Budget Committee that Bush has proposed
significant deficit reduction, but he also said the chance of
bringing the deficit under the congressional target of $100 billion
by the end of fiscal 1990 ``is really quite small.''
   ``I may say I would like to see Gramm-Rudman-Hollings targets met
literally (but) I don't think that is required to bring a
significant reduction in interest rates,'' he said.
   ``If, after the fact, the real number is $110 billion or $120
billion, in that vein, I would think that would be a major
improvement which the markets would take very positively,'' the
Federal Reserve chairman said.
   In his first congressional appearance since the central bank on
Friday escalated its fight against inflation by raising its key bank
lending rate, Greenspan said the Federal Reserve is trying to slow
economic growth to a pace sustainable without increased inflation.
   He told the senators they could help ease strains in the economy
and trigger lower interest rates with a credible plan to cut the
deficit from its 1989 level of about $165 billion. However, he
warned against resorting to accounting tricks that reduce the 1990
deficit without the prospect for further substantial cuts.
   ``What cannot have a positive effect is finding some set of
bookkeeping gimmicks which largely meet Gramm-Rudman for fiscal 1990
and then paper over `91, `92, `93,'' he said.
   Democratic members of the committee tried several times to prod
Greenspan into criticizing the ecnomic assumptions underlying the
Bush budget, which forecasts sharply lower interest rates and brisk
economic growth.
   Greenspan said he would have been more cautious in his
projections, but also said the differences between the Federal
Reserve and administration were ``within the range of forecasting
error.''
   His response drew a rebuke from Sen. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C., who
told him, ``You lose your credibility by the platitudes of that Bush
budget really doing anything to the deficit. It's a sham.''
   Meanwhile, Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady told the House
Budget Committee that both the administration and the Federal
Reserve have a firm commitment to fighting inflation.
   ``If there's a difference ... it's two people looking at the same
statistic and coming to a slightly different conclusion,'' Brady
said, in an attempt to soften previous criticism of the central bank.
   ``I am already convinced that interest rates will come down''
once Congress and the administration agree on a deficit-reduction
package, Brady said. In turn, he added, such an agreement would
allow the economic assumptions on which Bush's budget are based to
be met.
   At the Senate Appropriations Committee, White House budget
director Richard Darman came under fire from Democrats angry with
Bush for failing to specify the spending levels he would like to see
for hundreds of programs.
   The focus of the criticism was the more than 1,000 mostly
domestic programs that Bush has proposed limiting to $136 billion in
spending next year, the same amount as this year. Democrats have
complained that Bush has not revealed how he would accomplish this
freeze.
   ``It makes me wonder if the administration is leading us into the
age of Joe Isuzu federal budgeting,'' said committee chairman Robert
Byrd, D-W.Va., referring to the transparent liar portrayed in a
series of television commercials.
   Darman said that except for areas in which Bush had advanced
specific initiatives, the administration's starting point in budget
negotiations with Congress would be support of the proposals made by
former President Reagan.
   He also said the administration has given Congress hundreds of
pages of explanatory materials since Bush unveiled his spending plan
on Feb. 9.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
