<FIRST>r w AM-FarmPrices     02-28 0737</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Farm Prices,740</SECOND>
<HEAD>Despite Small February Dip, Farm Prices 14 Per Cent Above A Year
Ago</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices farmers got for raw products declined
0.7 percent from January to February but still averaged 14 percent
more than a year ago, the Agriculture Department said Tuesday.
   The department's Agricultural Statistics Board said in its
preliminary report that lower prices for soybeans, lettuce, milk and
corn were mostly responsible for the decline from the January
average.
   Higher prices for tomatoes, strawberries, potatoes and hay partly
offset the decline in the other commodities.
   ``Prices of food grains increased from January to February while
feed grains and oilseed prices decreased,'' the report said. ``The
all-wheat price moved to the highest level since April of 1981, but
the average corn and soybean prices dropped from January to
February.''
   Tomato prices moved up sharply during the month, and the February
average for cattle and calves was the highest since May 1979.
   The report also included revisions showing that prices received
by farmers actually rose 2.8 percent from December to January
instead of the 1.4 percent gain reported a month ago.
   Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter, meanwhile, told Congress
that the farm economy as a whole ``is continuing to make real
progress in recovering'' from the hard times of the early and mid
1980s.
   Last year's drought helped reduce supplies of major crops,
including corn, soybeans and wheat, which has resulted in higher
prices.
   ``The higher prices have helped maintain a high cash income level
for those farmers with supplies to sell and for the sector as a
whole,'' Yeutter told the House Budget Committee.
   ``However,'' he added, ``the drought dealt a severe blow to many
producers in drought areas who lost much of their crop and who did
not have prior-year crops to sell. It also placed a heavy burden on
livestock, poultry and dairy producers who were faced with higher
feed costs.''
   According to the preliminary February price figures, based mostly
on midmonth averages, the index for livestock and livestock products
as a group declined 0.6 percent from their January average but was
still up 5.4 percent from February 1988.
   The department's all-crops price index for February was down 1.4
percent from January but averaged 27 percent above a year ago.
   No new price figures for farm production costs were included in
the February report. Those have been confined to quarterly averages
because of budget cutbacks.
   In January, however, new quarterly figures showed that prices
paid by farmers to meet expenses were up 1.2 percent from last fall
and were 6.1 percent higher than a year earlier.
   Although the projections are subject to change, USDA economists
say that net cash income of farmers may be in the range of $48
billion to $52 billion this year, compared with a near-record of $57
billion in 1988. That is the difference between cash receipts and
cash expenses during the calendar year.
   Department economists say cash expenses are expected to rise
moderately in 1989 with expanded crop acreages and costlier
production items.
   Food prices in 1988 rose an average of 3.7 percent. USDA analysts
say another increase of 3 percent to 5 percent is likely in 1989.
   The report said:
   _Cattle averaged $70.70 per 100 pounds of live weight nationally,
up from $70.60 in January and $67.40 in February 1988. Those are
averages for all types of cattle sold as beef.
   _Hogs averaged $40 per 100 pounds, compared with $40.90 in
January and $45.80 a year earlier.
   _Corn, at $2.54 a bushel, was down from $2.60 in January but up
from $1.83 a year in February 1988.
   _Wheat prices at the farm, according to preliminary figures,
averaged $4.03 per bushel, compared with $4.01 in January and $2.79
a year earlier.
   _Rice averaged $6.55 per 100 pounds, up from $6.47 in January.
Rice was $9.37 a year earlier.
   _Soybeans were $7.23 per bushel, compared with $7.69 in January
and $5.96 a year earlier.
   _Upland cotton was reported at 53.1 cents per pound, down from
53.9 cents in January and 57 cents in February 1988.
   _Eggs were 62.1 cents per dozen, compared with 63.9 cents in
January and 46.9 cents a year earlier.
   _Milk was $13.10 per 100 pounds, compared with $13.40 in January
and $12.30 a year earlier.
   _Broilers were 35.2 cents per pound, live weight, compared with
35.3 cents in January and 25.7 cents a year ago.
</TEXT>
