<FIRST>r a AM-FloridaWildfires     02-28 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Florida Wildfires,0461</SECOND>
<HEAD>Firefighters Drop Incendiary Bombs To Block Everglades Blaze</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Helicopter-riding firefighters dropped incendiary
bombs along the route of a 10-mile-long Everglades wildfire Tuesday
to corral the spreading blaze and prevent it from damaging nearby
interstate power lines.
   Meanwhile, state forestry workers battled scores of other brush
fires around the state, including a 4,000-acre blaze just east of
Naples on Florida's southwest coast, and a 500-acre fire brought
under control just south of Jacksonville.
   The largest wildfire was burning sawgrass in the Everglades,
moving north along U.S. 27 toward the Palm Beach County line, and
running parallel to utility transmission lines that were shut down
again Tuesday to avoid blackouts.
   Firefighters initially tried to enter the swampy grassland in
all-terrain vehicles to pack down the sawgrass and create a
firebreak, but on Tuesday flames spread to 6,500 acres, burning an
area a mile across and 10 miles in length along U.S. 27.
   ``Our people were getting stuck _ it's very wet out there,'' said
David Utley, duty officer at the fire. ``We've decided to change
tactics, and use the helicopter to fight fire with fire, instead of
water.''
   The firefighers dropped small ping-pong-size balls filled with
potassium permanganate and ethylene glycol under the transmission
lines and along the western edge of the fire. Florida Power &amp; Light
Co. shut off power through the wires for four hours during the
backfire operation.
   ``The balls drop out, and when they hit the ground a chain
reaction starts and they catch on fire in about 45 seconds,'' Utley
said.
   The plan is to funnel the fire toward a canal blocking its path
to the north, he said.
   The fire _ which he said was apparently set sometime Sunday
morning _ did not directly threaten the 500,000-volt utility lines
or any inhabited areas, and firefighers hoped their new tactics
would have it under control within 24 hours, Utley said.
   Arson also figured in many of the other 65 fires the forestry
division was fighting Monday and Tuesday, said Charles Maynard,
spokesman for the agency in Tallahassee.
   Rainfall averaging only a third to a half of normal since the
fall has made the fires much more dangerous, as in 1985 when fires
burned over 100,000 acres around the state and caused a Miami
blackout.
   ``It's not as bad as in 1985, but it has the potential for
getting worse'' he said. ``We have certainly not had the rainfall
across the state that we need.''
   The National Weather Service was forecasting scattered showers in
some parts of the state over the next few days, but nothing that
would alleviate the growing fire danger, Maynard said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
