<FIRST>r i AM-Mexico-BogusCash     02-28 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Bogus Cash,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authorities Investigating Millions Of Forged `Coke' Dollars In Mexico</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ISAAC A. LEVI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mysterious man linked to the Medellin
cocaine cartel acknowledged he forged millions of dollars in
greenbacks and passed thousands along the U.S.-Mexico border, a top
law enforcement official said Tuesday.
   The man passed at least $100,000 worth of the phony money at an
unidentified bank in El Paso, Texas, before he was arrested Saturday
across the border in Ciudad Juarez, officials said.
   Deputy Attorney General Javier Coello Trejo told a news
conference that Mexican and American treasury experts are trying to
determine where the rest of the near-perfect fakes went.
   ``The U.S. Treasury experts we brought in were scared when they
saw the bills, which were in $10, $20 and $50 denominations. They
were almost perfect,'' Coello said, passing a couple of fake $100
bills to journalists.
   Coello said the man's identity is still a mystery despite
extensive questioning. He said the suspect had given the names of
Newton Peter von Gramm and Newton Peter von Shultz, among others.
   ``He went under many aliases and he operated in Canada for quite
awhile before coming to Mexico,'' Coello said, adding it is not
clear if the man is a German, Canadian or U.S. citizen.
   The man was arrested Saturday along with eight Mexicans when
Federal Judicial Police received a tip and raided a number of
clandestine engraving shops. Police seized at least $11 million
worth of U.S. bills.
   ``The man came to Mexico and hired two people from Tlaxcala
state, specialists in printing, and set up the engraving shops in
Juarez. They did some top work,'' he said, holding a fake bill up to
the light.
   ``We don't know yet how much money was forged. We are still
counting. Up until today we have counted about $11 million,'' Coello
said.
   The nine suspects were flown to Mexico City on Sunday for further
questioning and possible indictment. Forging currency is a federal
offense in Mexico.
   Coello said the man admitted he ``was connected to the Medellin
cartel'' and he had sent a sum of money to Colombia ``through some
traffickers in Monterrey, which federal agents are investigating.''
   ``We have already advised them and sent the information we have
to authorities in Colombia about that,'' Coello said.
   The Medellin cartel, named after the Colombian city which is it
home base, is considered the world's largest cocaine trafficking
ring.
   A source at the Attorney General's Office who insisted on
anonymity said the cartel may be running out of dollars as a result
of a crackdown on money laundering in Colombia, Mexico and the
United States and may be resorting to fake currency to meet expenses.
</TEXT>
