<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 2032EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ParentalLeave     02-28 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Parental Leave,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mandatory Leave Bill Clears First Hurdle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House subcommittee approved legislation
Tuesday to require large employers to provide up to 10 weeks of
unpaid leave for parents to spend with new children.
   The measure also would require employers to make 15 weeks leave
available to workers who need time off to care for a seriously ill
parent or child.
   The bill, which cleared the Education and Labor's subcommittee on
labor-management relations on a 11-5 vote, is similar to Senate
legislation strongly pushed for the last two years by Sen. Chris
Dodd, D-Conn.
   The House bill now goes to the full Education and Labor
Committee, where approval is considered certain.
   The Dodd bill reached the Senate floor for debate last year, but
died for lack of action. The full House did not debate its version
of the legislation last year.
   The House bill would apply to employers with 50 or more workers
for the first three years and to those with 35 or more workers after
three years.
   Backers estimate the House measure would cover about 39 percent
of the U.S. labor force the first three years and 43 percent
thereafter.
   The Dodd bill would apply to employers with 20 or more workers,
or about 47 percent of the total workforce.
   Although employers would not have to pay salary to workers on
leave, business generally opposes the legislation on grounds it
would be disruptive to planning and because employers would have to
continue paying any health insurance premiums for the employee on
leave.
   While the Senate took the lead last year, the informal plan now
being worked out among proponents for parental leave legislation is
for the House to go first this year while the Senate concentrates on
child care subsidies.
   However, Democratic leaders in both houses have said their first
priority on labor-management issues this year is raising the current
$3.35 an hour minimum wage.
   Bills on the minimum wage, child care and parental leave all
received extensive debate last year. Democratic leaders on both
sides of the Capitol are moving quickly to get bills on the floor
again this year with only minimal time for rearguing the issues in
the committees.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
