<DOCNO> AP890228-0135 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 1644EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-DCGuns 3rdLd-Writethru a0653 02-28 0620</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-DC Guns, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0653,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>D.C. Council Votes for Curfew, Decides More Time Needed to Study
Gun Bill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs graf 3, bgng ``The council,'' to CORRECT age to 18; inserts
graf 4, ``Parents of,'' with penalty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The District of Columbia Council, in a new
attack on drug-related crime in the nation's capital, voted Tuesday
to bar many teen-agers from congregating on street corners and other
public areas late at night and during the early morning hours.
   But it refused to act immediately on Mayor Marion Barry Jr.'s
proposed emergency city legislation to create a mandatory five-year
prison term for anyone using guns to commit crimes. The council
decided more time is needed to study that proposal.
   The council approved a curfew that would bar those under age 18
from gathering on street corners, parks or other public areas
between 11 p.m. and 6 a.m. on Sunday through Thursday and from
midnight to 6 a.m. on Friday and Saturday.
   Parents of a curfew violator would face no penalty in the case of
a first offense but would pay $100 if there is a second offense,
$200 for a third one, and $500 for additional violations.
   The emergency measure came as the city attempted to slow the pace
of drug-related killings. Police blame about 60 percent of last
year's record 372 killings on drugs. So far this year, 90 people
have been slain in the district, 36 more than during the matching
period last year.
   However, Frederick Cooke, the city's chief attorney, said the
bill may not slow the growth of drug-related homicides.
   ``The fact of the matter is the average age of the homicide
victim in the District of Columbia is (30) years of age and the
average age of perpetrators of these homicides is in excess of 18
years of age,'' Cooke said. ``It's not going to really address the
problem significantly.''
   The council decided to study Barry proposal to require five-year
prison terms for people who commit crimes with guns.
   The council agreed with its chairman, voting to delay action
until the proposal Barry submitted late Monday can be examined.
   ``We just need some time to review this matter,'' said Council
Chairman David Clarke. ``We've had some comments from (U.S. Attorney
Jay Stephens) and requests for more time.''
   Clarke has scheduled a briefing from city officials on the bill
and indicated he could convene a special session to enact the
legislation, perhaps as early as Wednesday.
   ``We're not going to let these gun-carrying thugs, dope dealers
... feel that because we have some difficulties in our jail
population, that there's no room,'' Barry told a citizens group
Monday night. ``We will find room _ find places for them to stay in
jail.''
   At a news conference earlier, Barry said the city is starting
``an all-out assault on weapons.''
   Barry's proposal would strengthen the penalty in the city's
misdemeanor gun law which already provides for a maximum punishment
of one year in jail and a $1,000 fine for those caught with
unregistered weapons.
   Barry's bill also proposes redefining the city's bail laws so
that those caught carrying an unregistered weapon, selling drugs or
using a weapon in an assault could be denied release before trial.
   Barry wants to create a ``drug-free zone'' of up to 1,000 feet
from city schools. Under that bill, those caught using or selling
drugs in those areas would face an additional three-year jail term.
   Barry acknowledged that his measures would add still more
prisoners to the city's jail system, which is already operating
under court orders requiring a reduction in overcrowding. Inmates
have been sent to several states to help alleviate that problem.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
