<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 2034EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Bush-Asia     02-28 0773</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Asia,0794</SECOND>
<HEAD>Asians Welcome Sign of High Priority in U.S. Eyes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With few exceptions, officials and newspapers in the
Far East rated President Bush's fast-paced visit a success in
showing the importance the new U.S. administration puts on relations
with Asian countries.
   Bush returned to Washington on Monday night after a five-day
swing to Japan, China and South Korea, his first overseas trip as
president. Asian commentators said it was the first time a new
president had visited Asia before Europe, and said the trip was
extraordinary in coming so early in Bush's tenure.
   The official Xinhua news agency in China called it an ``unusual
diplomatic initiative'' and said, ``China looms large in Bush's
foreign policy. Over the years, he has attached importance to
China's role in world affairs and cared for the expansion of
U.S.-China relations.''
   In Tokyo, Bush met leaders of 20 foreign countries in the swirl
of ``funeral diplomacy'' among dignitaries paying respects to the
late Emperor Hirohito. His stop in Seoul let him reassert the U.S.
determination to maintain its troop strength in South Korea and
support for democratic reforms. And in Beijing his presence lent a
counterbalance to the warming of Sino-Soviet relations.
   ``His visit ... clearly indicates the importance the Bush
administration attaches to Asia,'' the liberal Japanese daily Asahi
Shimbun said in an editorial.
   Bush's talks covered hot spots such as the Korean peninsula and
Cambodia as well as the softer issues of trade and human rights,
with a notable flap in Beijing when Chinese police prevented
dissident Fang Lizhi from attending a banquet to which Bush had
invited him.
   The Chinese, while saying Bush's visit would enhance Sino-U.S.
friendship, were angry at what they saw as U.S. interference in
their affairs.
   Communist Party leader Zhao Ziyang said, ``The fact that some
Americans support those Chinese who are not satisfied with the
Chinese government will be detrimental not only to China's policial
stability and the progress of its reforms but also to the Sino-U.S.
friendship.''
   The conservative Hong Kong daily, South China Morning Post, said
Bush had been ill-advised to invite Fang.
   ``It was a rash and provocative gesture,'' it said in an
editorial. ``China, in turn, overreacted foolishly by physically
ensuring that the outspoken activist was not able to attend.''
   In Thailand, the conservative English-language Bangkok Post said
the Fang incident showed China was as authoritarian now as in the
1970s when Bush served as U.S. envoy to Beijing. It also showed the
Americans ``that their road to Chinese favor is just as bumpy as
that of the Russians,'' the Bangkok Post said.
   Thai government spokesman Suvit Yodmani said Bush's talks with
other world leaders gave them a ``good opportunity to reaffirm their
commitments and promote relations with more countries.''
   South Korean President Roh Tae-woo, after talks with Bush, said
they would work to resolve ``various problems resulting from the
rapid expansion of economic relations between our two countries'' _
a reference to trade frictions.
   Roh said he had briefed Bush on efforts to reduce tensions with
North Korea. That country's official media sounded a sour note in
denouncing Bush's visit to Seoul and demanding that U.S. troops be
withdrawn from South Korea.
   The Rodong Sinmun daily of the ruling North Korean Workers
(Communist) Party said Bush's visit would be marked by ``aggression
and treachery between the new master and the new servant.''
   The liberal Australian daily, the Sydney Morning Herald, said
Bush's trip was ``a welcome reassurance of the continued U.S.
commitment to the Asia-Pacific region.'' It suggested that
Washington propose a reversal of the arms buildup in the northern
Pacific and also measures to reduce the risk of regional conflict.
   ``That would test the sincerity of (Soviet President Mikhail)
Gorbachev's stated desire to reduce tensions in Asia and the
Pacific. It would also give the U.S. an edge in the disarmament
debate in the region and may lead to agreements easing the security
concerns of Japan, South Korea and China,'' the Sydney paper said.
   The independent Indonesian daily Kompas, commenting on Bush's
call for progress in removing Vietnamese troops from Cambodia, said
Washington has less at stake in Cambodia than China and the Soviets
but still ``can contribute to the efforts to find a political
solution to the problem.''
   Japan's largest daily, the middle-of-the-road Yomiuri Shimbun,
welcomed the U.S. intention to play an active role in Asia.
   ``Asia is undergoing dynamic economic development,'' the Yomiuri
said. ``It is also in the process of the rearrangement of
multilateral relations, which was set in motion by Sino-Soviet
reconciliation. The United States must play its part.''
</TEXT>
