<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 2037EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Sweden-Arms     02-28 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sweden-Arms,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Acquitted in Arms Smuggling Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KARLSKOGA, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two businessmen were acquitted Tuesday
of smuggling munitions to Iran and other countries in the Middle
East, the first verdict in a series of weapons sales scandals.
   The district court absolved Mats Lundberg, a former marketing
director of Swedish arms manufacturer Nobel Kemi, of charges that he
sold 1,300 tons of explosives worth $12 million to blacklisted
countries, including Syria and Egypt.
   Sweden, a neutral country, forbids weapons sales to countries at
war or in areas of conflict.
   The court also acquitted Karl-Erik Schmitz, an independent trader
who reputedly is Sweden's biggest private arms merchant, on charges
of mediating illegal arms sales.
   The court ruled the weapons were sold legally and exported again
to the banned countries without the knowledge of Nobel Kemi or
anyone in the government.
   Both Lundberg and Schmitz were convicted, however, of sending
samples of merchandise to Iran and fined the equivalent of $1,000
and $2,500 respectively.
   On Monday, Justice Chancellor Hans Stark released a report
accusing a state-owned munitions factory of violating the export
regulations for 20 years.
   In another case awaiting trial, former executives of another
Swedish company, Bofors AB, have been accused of selling
sophisticated missile systems to Iran through third parties. Bofors
owned Nobel Kemi during the 1981 to 1985 period Lundberg had been
accused of making the illegal sales.
   Partly as a result of the disclosure that Swedish weapons were
being used in the Iran-Iraq war, Sweden last year tightened its
export regulations.
</TEXT>
