<FIRST>r w AM-Bennett     02-28 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bennett,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Hearings Open Wednesday for Bush's Nominee for Drug Czar</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drug czar-designate William J. Bennett spent
several weeks studying briefing books on the nation's drug situation
and expects few problems at Senate confirmation hearings, an aide
said Tuesday.
   ``No one's led us to believe this will be a hostile or circuslike
affair,'' said David Tell, Bennett's deputy chief of staff. Two days
of Senate Judiciary Committee hearings begin Wednesday.
   Although declining to say whether aides tossed tough questions at
Bennett to prepare him for the worst, Tell said: ``We've made sure
he's ready. ... He's looking forward to it.''
   Bennett has kicked his habit of smoking two packs of cigarettes a
day.
   Sen. Joseph R. Biden Jr., D-Del., the committee chairman, said he
doesn't care about the smoking. But Bennett made a commitment Jan.
12, when nominated by President Bush to become the nation's first
director of the Office of National Drug Control Policy, to stop
smoking.
   Bennett attended a stop-smoking clinic, called ``Breathe Free,''
when he, his wife, Elayne, and son John went to a resort in Berkeley
Springs, W.Va., last week.
   ``It was the final vacation with his family before he starts the
new job,'' Tell said.
   ``I went in his office and there's no ashtray,'' said Tell,
although there are some crutches _ a bowl of fruit and lollipops.
   Biden said Tuesday that while he believes Bennett could be a good
drug czar, he'll have some tough questions for Bennett about the job.
   The director is to compile in his first 180 days a comprehensive
drug-control strategy covering all aspects of the battle against
illegal drugs.
   ``I'm going to be looking for a clear statement from Bennett that
he fully understands what the law says, what it is intended to do,
and how he believes he can and will wield his authority relative to
the remainder of the federal government, which has not had anybody
... in that job before. I'm sure he is going to meet some
resistance,'' Biden said.
   ``I'm looking for him to demonstrate a clear understanding and
agreement with the rationale for the creation of the office, the
requirement of coming up with a plan and how he intends to go about
that, an understanding of the authority and willingness to exercise
the authority to implement that plan from a budget standpoint as
well as a broader administration position standpoint,'' the senator
said.
   Biden added: ``Does he need a top-flight, well-known law
enforcement officer to make up for his lack of law enforcement
background? Does he think he needs someone in one of his two deputy
spots with background in existing programs, education as well as
treatment?''
   Paul Smith, an aide to Sen. Orrin G. Hatch, R-Utah, said the
senator ``expects the Democrats to bring up Bennett's lack of law
enforcement background.'' Still, he added, Bennett is ``going to get
out of the hearings without major problems. It should be smooth
sailing for him.''
</TEXT>
