<FIRST>r w AM-US-Jamaica     02-28 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Jamaica,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Manley Government Hires Washington Lobbyist</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jamaica's new prime minister, Michael Manley,
has hired a Washington lobbying firm, Neill and Company, to promote
U.S. economic aid to his Caribbean island, a lobbyist for the firm
said Tuesday.
   The lobbyist, speaking on the condition of anonymity, said his
company has been asked to seek more direct congressional aid for
Jamaica as well as possible loans and guarantees from U.S.
government institutions.
   In addition, Manley wants the lobbyists to pursue private U.S.
investment in Jamaica, the lobbyist said. Neill and Company's other
clients include Pakistan, Kenya and Morocco.
   Manley's election earlier this month raised some concern in
Washington because of his past socialist policies. As prime minister
from 1972 to 1980, Manley forged close ties with Cuba's Fidel Castro
and brought in scores of Cuban doctors and technicians.
   His successor, conservative Edward Seaga, closed Cuba's embassy
in Kingston and turned to Washington.
   Manley has decided to reopen Cuba's embassy but has promised the
United States he will limit the Cuban presence in Jamaica.
   ``Obviously we're not in agreement with that policy,'' said a
State Department official, also requesting anonymity. ``We feel Cuba
should be isolated in the Caribbean. But Jamaica is a sovereign
nation and has the right to conduct its diplomacy.''
   Manley is planning an official trip to Washington in the spring
or summer, and the White House is trying to work out a meeting with
President George Bush.
   ``We want to get off to a good start with him,'' the State
Department official said.
   The United States has given Jamaica more than $150 million in
recent months for reconstruction of the damage from last September's
Hurricane Gilbert. Jamaica received $47.6 million in U.S. food and
development aid in 1988.
</TEXT>
