<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Armenia     02-28 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Armenia,0321</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands March in Armenia to Mark Anniversary of Riot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Armenians marched in their capital of
Yerevan on Tuesday to mark the first anniversary of ethnic riots in
neighboring Azerbaijan in which at least 26 Armenians died, local
sources said.
   An editor with Armenpress, the official Armenian news agency, put
the number of marchers at 800,000, which would be two-thirds of
Yerevan's population of 1.2 million. There was no way to verify his
estimate.
   Rem Ananityan, deputy director of Armenpress, said in a telephone
interview that demonstrators carrying flowers gathered at a monument
on a Yerevan hillside commemorating victims of the 1915 massacre of
Armenians by Turks.
   Demonstrations are banned in Yerevan to reduce ethnic tensions,
but Ananityan said military authorities there allowed Tuesday's
demonstration to take place. He said no incidents were reported.
   Riots flared in Sumgait, Azerbaijan, on Feb. 28, 1988, weeks
after Armenians began demonstrating for annexation of the
Nagorno-Karabakh region of Azerbaijan, where most residents are
ethnic Armenians.
   Soviet officials say 32 people _ 26 Armenians and six
Azerbaijanis _ were killed, but Armenians insist the toll was much
higher.
   Further violence broke out in Armenia and Azerbaijan last June,
July and November, with more than 60 people killed. In January the
Kremlin imposed direct rule on Nagorno-Karabakh.
   In an interview printed Tuesday by the military daily Krasnaya
Zvezda, the Kremlin's special envoy to Nagorno-Karabakh, Arkady
Volsky, said tension there remains high.
   ``Mutual suspicion and mistrust persist, while reproaches and
accusations do not cease,'' Volsky told the newspaper, according to
a summary carried by the official Tass news agency.
   He said more than 200,000 people from Armenia and Azerbaijan fled
their homes because of the strife.
   Though populated largely by Armenians, who are traditionally
Christian, Nagorno-Karabakh was turned over by Soviet officials in
1923 to Azerbaijan, where most residents are Moslems.
</TEXT>
