<SECOND>AM-Nunn-Tower, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0628,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nunn Role In Tower Nomination Focuses New Attention on 1964 Accident</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 3 grafs, bgng ``Nunn repeated,'' with new Nunn quotes</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tower Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Sam Nunn's opposition to Defense
Secretary-designate John Tower has focused new attention on a 1964
incident in which a youthful Nunn pleaded guilty to leaving the
scene of a traffic accident.
   The Wall Street Journal in Tuesday's editions reprinted a Dec. 4,
1972, article from The Atlanta Journal detailing the Oct. 31, 1964
automobile accident based on Nunn's account and the official
accident report.
   ``If the Senate is entitled to pass judgment on John Tower's
personal history,'' the newspaper said in an editorial accompanying
the 1972 article, ``then the public is also entitled to know the
salient facts about those who judge Mr. Tower.''
   Nunn, D-Ga., is chairman of the Senate Armed Services Committee,
which voted 11-9 last week to reject Tower's nomination. Nunn and
the other 10 Democrats on the panel voted against Tower.
   According to police reports on the 1964 accident, Nunn had left a
Halloween party in his hometown of Perry, Ga., about 2:45 a.m. when
he swerved off the road and hit a parked car, then drove several
more blocks before going off the road and down an embankment.
   Nunn was charged with hit and run and leaving the scene of an
accident. Court records show he later forfeited a $115.50 bond on
the single charge of leaving the scene of an accident.
   Nunn, who has based his opposition to Tower's nomination in part
on allegations that Tower has a drinking problem, acknowledged in a
statement released by his office Tuesday that he had too much to
drink himself on the night of the accident 24 years ago.
   ``That evening, I had enough to drink so that both my driving and
judgment were impaired,'' Nunn, 50, said in the statement. ``I pled
guilty to leaving the scene, paid my fine, apologized to all
concerned and at the age of 26 learned a valuable lesson which I
have not forgotten.''
   Nunn repeated that statement later Tuesday in interviews with
Atlanta television stations and said he does not believe the
accident is relevant to the issue of the Tower nomination.
   ``The implication is that if I have an automobile accident in
1964, then I'm not qualified under the Constitution to render advice
and consent in 1989,'' Nunn said. ``I don't think that logic holds.
   ``I don't know that that is relevant to this, but I guess when
you're in this kind of fight, everything is fair game,'' he said.
</TEXT>
