<FIRST>r w AM-US-Sudan     02-28 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Sudan,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Calls on Administration to Reassess Sudan Aid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Foreign Relations Committee on
Tuesday urged the Bush administration to reassess future aid for
Sudan unless the government of the northern African nation improves
food deliveries to millions of hungry Sudanese.
   In a resolution adopted by the panel and referred to the full
Senate, the committee said another condition for aid should be
progress in negotiating a cease-fire with the rebel Sudan People's
Liberation Army to end nearly six years of civil war.
   The Sudanese army last week was reported to have given Prime
Minister Sadeq Mahdi a one-week ultimatum either to resign or begin
peace talks with the rebels.
   The Senate resolution _ and a similar one being introduced
Thursday in the House _ also calls on the administration to
cooperate with the Soviet Union in pressing the Sudanese government
and the rebels to settle their war.
   State Department officials say the United States has discussed
the Sudan crisis with the Soviets, but has not decided on joint
action.
   The resolution calls on President Bush to appoint a special envoy
to deal with Sudan.
   The Bush administration has put special emphasis on resolving the
Sudan problem, with Secretary of State James Baker issuing an urgent
call several weeks ago to the Sudanese government to allow foreign
relief shipments into famine areas.
   The United States and international relief agencies estimate that
some 2 million southerners are in dire need of food, and that more
than 500,000 died in 1988 from hunger.
   U.S. officials attribute the obstruction and delays of
international food deliveries to the fighting, to SPLA and
government restrictions, and to government inefficiency. Rebel
leaders have accused the government of withholding food from the
south as a form of genocide.
   The Senate resolution called on both the SPLA and the government
to refrain from using food as a weapon.
   The administration has asked Congress for $51 million for Sudan
in fiscal 1990 _ $45 million of it in economic and development aid
and $6 million for military projects. U.S. aid to the Sudan has been
dropping steadily in recent years as the coalition government has
lost some of its pro-Western orientation under the influence of a
strong faction of Moslem fundamentalists.
</TEXT>
