<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 1823EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Nicaragua     02-28 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua,0556</SECOND>
<HEAD>Assembly Begins Debate On Sandinista Bill To Pardon Guardsmen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associate Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Assembly took up a bill
Tuesday that would pardon nearly 2,000 soldiers of the former Somoza
regime to comply with agreements made at a Central American summit
Feb. 14.
   Assembly president Carlos Nunez said the leftist Sandinista
government also would ask the legislature to pardon 800 jailed
Sandinista army soldiers. That appeared aimed at mollifying
government supporters angered at the proposal to release men who
served the late President Anastasio Somoza.
   Of the 1,932 on the list submitted to the assembly Tuesday, 1,688
are in prison and the rest under house arrest or free on probation.
   They were members of the National Guard, as the army was called
under Somoza, whose pro-U.S. government the Sandinistas overthrew in
July 1979.
   Passage of the amnesty bill is assured because the Sandinistas
have 61 seats in the 96-member assembly to 35 for all opposition
parties.
   Release of the political prisoners is stipulated in the
agreements reached at the summit by President Daniel Ortega and the
presidents of El Salvador, Honduras, Costa Rica and Guatemala.
   They also agreed to draft a plan within 90 days to dismantle
rebel forces supported by the United States. About 10,000 rebels, or
Contras, and 11,000 family members live in camps in Honduras, near
the Nicaraguan border.
   In a National Assembly debate Tuesday, before the amnesty bill
was sent to committee, a member said the pardon and release should
coincide with the end of the Contra organization.
   Otherwise, ``we would be letting out 1,000 National Guardsmen,
who could quickly form a military force, in exchange for a simple
promise'' to disarm and relocate the Contras, said Carlos Cuadra of
the opposition Marxist-Leninist Popular Action Movement.
   The assembly president, one of nine members in the Sandinista
National Directorate, urged the committee reviewing the bill to
report by March but did not specify a date. Neither did he say when
the request to pardon the 800 jailed Sandinistas was expected.
   Ortega is anxious to comply with the summit agreements because he
seeks financial aid, particularly from the 12-nation European
Economic Community. Several ambassadors from EEC nations have said
publicly and privately that further aid depends on increased
democracy in Nicaragua.
   Foreign Minister Miguel d'Escoto is attending a meeting of Common
Market and Latin American foreign ministers in Honduras to discuss
European economic aid to the region.
   Since Washington cut off aid and imposed a trade embargo in 1985,
Nicaragua has depended on help from the Soviet bloc and Western
Europe. A new U.S. government report estimates Soviet assistance at
about $500 million a year.
   Nicaragua's economy is a shambles. Inflation surpassed 20,000
percent in 1988 and the cost of living increased by 97 percent in
January. A government austerity plan calls 30,000 layoffs and
tighter credit.
   At the Feb. 14 summit in El Salvador, Ortega promised free
elections and moved the date forward by 10 months to Feb. 25, 1990.
He began meeting with opposition groups after returning from El
Salvador.
   In February 1988 the U.S. Congress cut off Contra military aid.
U.S. humanitarian aid runs out March 31 and President Bush has said
he will seek an extension.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
