<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Executions     02-28 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Executions,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Interior Minister Denies Saying Political Prisoners Executed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two top Iranian leaders on Tuesday denied
Iranian dissidents were executed after rebels of the Iraqi-based
Mujahedeen Khalq, or People's Holy Warriors, pushed into the country
last summer.
   Iranian Interior Minister Ali Akbar Mohtashemi had been quoted
earlier as telling the Paris-based Al-Mostaqbal weekly that: ``All
those were captured or those who joined them were executed.
   ``They had declared war against the people ... they killed and
got killed,'' Montashemi was quoted as saying. ``Any group or people
that raises arms and kills people deserves to be executed.''
   But Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency quoted
Montashemi as saying Tuesday in Tehran that he had not made the
statements, but merely said that a large number of rebels were
killed when they thrust into western Iran in August.
   IRNA quoted Mohtashemi as saying the Al-Mostaqbal report was a
``product of the reporters' imaginings. ... In fact, the issue of
prisoners was not brought up in the interview at all.''
   In Paris, Iranian Parliament speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani denied
there were mass executions of Iranian rebel fighters, but said that
up to 5,000 were killed in a battle on the warfront following the
cease-fire with Iraq.
   In an interview on French TV, Rafsanjani said only ``certain''
jailed opponents had been killed.
   ``We have discovered that certain imprisoned hypocrites in Iran
were in contact with their fighting friends in Iraq,'' Rafsanjani
said in reference to the rebels. ``We killed them, but there
certainly were not 1,000. Any competent jurisdiction can easily
prove it.''
   The Mujahedeen Kalq has said hundreds of its supporters have been
arrested and executed inside Iran since an Aug. 20 cease-fire in the
8-year Iran-Iraq war.
   The National Liberation Army, the Mujahedeen Kalq's military
wing, has admitted it lost 1,000 fighters into the brief push into
Iran's Bakhtaran province shortly before the cease-fire.
   The rebels said in a statement sent to The Associated Press in
Cyprus Tuesday that they gave U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez De
Cuellar a list of the names of 1,634 Mujahedeen prisoners executed
by Iran.
   It said those executed were among 12,000 Mujahedeen prisoners
held in various Iranian prisoners. They included students, doctors,
engineers, army officers and a number of high-ranking clergymen.
   The statement said the wave of political executions was
continuing in Iran.
</TEXT>
