<FIRST>r p AM-WritingInEddie     02-28 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Writing In Eddie,0516</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Democrats Flock to Support Their Hero, Others' Dracula</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Chicago Mayoral, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Slowly but surely, voters filed into Serbian Hall
Tuesday, most of them taking Republican ballots in a precinct where
Democrats once were royal and the local prince was an alderman named
Edward Vrdolyak.
   A Republican now, Vrdolyak has lost two consecutive political
bids and his comeback effort as a write-in candidate for the GOP
mayoral nomination led a Chicago Tribune editorialist to label him
the ``Count Dracula of Chicago politics.''
   Vrdolyak, who represented this Southeast Side ward of heavy
industry and working-class neighborhoods for 16 years as a Democrat,
launched his latest bid less than a week ago.
   And in the neat wood-and-brick community hall on the grounds of
St. Simeon Serbian Orthodox Church, it looked like things were going
his way.
   ``We're going to get several thousand votes, thanks to a lot of
our people supporting me,'' Vrdolyak said, shaking hands with a few
supporters at the hall. ``And to those that aren't, I apologize for
getting into the race late after they have already made commitments,
but we'll get 'em next time.''
   The 10th Ward, with its primarily white, ethnic constituency, has
been loyal to Vrdolyak, a former Cook County Democratic Party
chairman. Some voters say that's because Vrdolyak has been loyal to
them.
   All the mayoral candidates talk about fighting crime and
promoting education, but top Democratic contenders Richard M. Daley
or Mayor Eugene Sawyer, cannot get the job done, said Creita Sadzak,
54, who wrote Vrdolyak in Tuesday.
   ``If Eddie gets in, then Eddie is going to do it,'' she said.
``It's not Fast Eddie any more,'' she said, referring to the moniker
hung on Vrdolyak for years. ``It's Ready Eddie.''
   The GOP endorsed Herbert Sohn, a doctor and attorney who has made
three unsuccessful bids for Congress.
   Whichever Republican is on the April 4 general election ballot,
the prospects do not look good.
   Republicans in this traditionally Democratic city haven't found
their way into the mayor's office since the 1930s.
   Voting for Vrdolyak required writing the words ``mayor'' and
``Vrdolyak'' and putting an ``x'' in a box, which political analysts
predicted would be too difficult for some people.
   Vrdolyak, who lost his GOP bid for circuit court clerk last fall,
countered that the thousands of pieces of instructional literature
sent to likely backers would help him get enough votes to beat Sohn.
   Vrdolyak cast his own ballot earlier in the day at St. Simeon,
which sits on a carefully manicured lot among bungelows in the
shadows of an industrial complex.
   One of the first people voters encountered at the hall was GOP
election judge Patricia Hansen, 53, who said she was Republican even
before Vrdolyak's switch.
   ``I always said, `Why should I be lost among the many when I can
stand out among the few,''' she said. ``I was considered a prominent
Republican.
   ``Now, I'm lost among the many.''
</TEXT>
