<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 1918EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     02-28 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms in Dixie, Light Snow around Great Lakes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A slow-moving cold front stirred up thunderstorms, high winds and
at least one tornado in parts of Georgia and Alabama on Tuesday, as
up to 10 inches of snow fell in northwest Montana and lighter snow
fell around the Great Lakes.
   In Georgia, a tornado was sighted in Needmore and a mobile home
was knocked off its foundation in Butler as thunderstorms moved
through the south-central part of the state.
   High winds accompanied the storms in eastern and central Alabama,
overturning a car in Montgomery. South of the cold front, warm and
humid air was trapped over Florida, with gusts clocked at up to 30
mph.
   Light rain fell from eastern North Carolina to the Middle
Atlantic states. Snow was reported from central Virginia to central
New Jersey, but with no significant accumulations.
   A low-pressure system over northern Michigan spread light snow
across northern Wisconsin, much of Michigan and northern Indiana.
Parts of the High Plains, from western Kansas to eastern Colorado
and Montana, also reported 1 to 2 inches of snow.
   Heavy snow occurred in parts of northwest Montana, where 8 to 10
inches of new snow fell near Marion Mountain, west of Kalispell.
Blowing snow limited visibility for travelers. Gusty winds and
temperatures hovering around zero produced wind chills of 40 below
at Minot, N.D., and 31 below at Cut Bank, Mont.
   Light rain fell over the Pacific Northwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from minus 2
at Cut Bank to 84 at Fort Myers, Fla. The morning low for the nation
was minus 9 at Alexandria, Minn.
   Wednesday's forecast called for showers and a few scattered
thunderstorms from South Carolina to Florida. Rain also was expected
in western parts of Washington and Oregon, with snow from the
Washington and Oregon Cascades to the the Dakotas, the upper
Mississippi Valley, the Great Lakes and New England.
   High temperatures should range from zero to 10 degrees from
northern Montana to North Dakota and northern Minnesota; from the
teens to the 20s from the northern Rockies to South Dakota, Iowa and
the Great Lakes; the 50s and 60s from most of California to New
Mexico, Texas, the Gulf Coast states and the Carolinas, with highs
in the 70s and above in the southern tip of Texas, Southern
California, the desert Southwest and Florida; and be in the 30s and
40s elsewhere.
</TEXT>
