<FIRST>u w AM-NorthTrial 4thLd-Writethru a0733 02-28 0936</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-North Trial, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0733,940</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Trial Halted Over Secrets; Lawyer Alleges Fraud</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Restores first reference to Owen's lawyer in 9th graf, During
the...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oliver North's Iran-Contra trial ground to a
halt and was thrown into confusion Tuesday by documents introduced
in court as classified but made available in uncensored versions to
a private activist group.
   North lawyer Brendan Sullivan asked the judge to throw out all 12
criminal charges in the case, asserting prosecutors were guilty of
``a fraud on the defense.''
   U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell said he was ``not trying to
look for sanctions'' against anyone but was concerned about
``getting to the bottom of what's going on'' regarding the use of
classified information at the trial.
   ``My concern is whether this presents an example of looseness in
governmental dealings with this problem of classified information,''
the judge said during a lengthy afternoon hearing. He wondered aloud
whether all the pretrial work on rules for handling such information
would have to be done over.
   He said declaring a mistrial and starting over with a new jury
was ``out of the question.''
   The new stumbling block was the discovery that 10 memos
introduced in the trial with names and other information blacked out
had long ago been turned over, uncensored, to the Christic Institute
in connection with a lawsuit filed several years ago by the group
against North and several other people. The institute is strongly
opposed to administration policy in Central America.
   The memos had been written by Robert Owen to North during a
two-year period when Owen acted as a courier between North and
rebels fighting the government in Nicaragua.
   With the issue far from settled and creating unforeseen
implications for other classified material, the judge ordered that
the jury return Wednesday morning. Sullivan had asked for another
day to argue out of the jury's hearing, saying ``I'm not sure what
the rules are.''
   But Gesell said ``the longer the jury is not in that box, the
more difficult it is to revivify the case. I get very, very worried
about hauling citizens into the jury box all the time and not give
them anything to do.''
   During the three-hour hearing, chief trial prosecutor John Keker
disclosed that an inter-agency intelligence group had decided
Tuesday morning that it would no longer regard the Owen memos as
classified. The same group had censored the documents in the first
place _ after they had been turned over to Christic by Thomas
Hylden, Owen's lawyer.
   Called to the witness stand, Hylden said that at a conference
with prosecutors on Feb. 10, he noticed they were working from a
censored version of one memo and remarked that his copy was uncut
and that he had given a copy to the Christic Institute.
   Michael Bromwich, a member of the prosecution team who was at
that conference, said he called in security expert Allen Stansbury
who told him he would retrieve Christic's copy. But Bromwich said he
then forgot about the matter until the defense raised it late Monday
night.
   Stansbury, the security director of the independent counsel's
office, said he contacted the Justice Department about the Owen
memos having gone to a ``litigant in Florida'' which he now knows is
the Christic Institute. He said he thought of trying to retrieve the
documents but wanted to check further with Justice Department
superiors before doing anything.
   Bromwich said it was his understanding that a document could be
classified even though it was in the public domain already.
   ``For 2 1@2 weeks, a jury has been ready to try this case and
hasn't been able to try it,'' said Gesell. ``Now I hear we are
dealing with classified documents that can be classified ex post
facto.''
   Amid the discussion over government secrets, Gesell sent the jury
home early on Friday, again after the noon recess on Monday and at
the start of the day Tuesday.
   Gesell noted that he had a continuing motion from the defense
relating to ``whether or not a fair trial can be given'' under rules
set by a law governing disclosure of state secrets at trial.
   ``The government is simply unable to manage the classified
information at issue here in a manner that permits a fair trial,''
Sullivan said Tuesday in a motion filed with the court.
   Instead of revealing the ``critical fact'' that the memos had
been made available in uncensored form, he said, the independent
counsel ``hid it and, incredibly, insisted that the court and the
defense treat these already-public documents as classified.''
   Although the dispute went to the heart of the secrecy issues
woven through the fabric of the trial, the specific issue was
mention of the name of a high Costa Rican official, former security
minister Benjamin Piza. It was blacked out in the court document,
but was on the public record in the Christic suit.
   Later Tuesday, the Christic Institute, which strongly opposes
U.S. government policy in Central America, released the documents.
In the Aug. 25, 1985 memo central to the dispute, the fact that it
concerned a meeting with ``Ben and Johnny'' had been censored in the
version at the trial to read ``Costa Rican officials.'' Ben
apparently was Piza, Johnny apparently John Campos. The words
``another Costa Rican official'' masked ``a colonel in the civil
guard, Col. Jose Ramon Mendero Quesada.''
   North, a retired Marine lieutenant colonel, faces 12 felony
charges, including allegations he lied to lawmakers to cover up his
secret efforts to help the Contras when such assistance was banned
by Congress.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
