<FIRST>r a AM-IrishStew     02-28 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Irish Stew,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>Irish Officials to Shun San Francisco's St. Patrick's Day Parade</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Denis is cq in 9th graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Irish government officials say they will
boycott the city's St. Patrick's Day parade because the grand
marshal is the local leader of an organization that supports the
outlawed Irish Republican Army.
   Parade organizers said the grand marshal was elected by a
cross-section of the city's large Irish community and the
controversy would not dim their celebration.
   Irish Consul-General Brian Nason said neither he nor the Lord
Mayor of Cork, San Francisco's sister city, will attend or
participate in the parade.
   ``It would be like going to a party with the IRA,'' Nason said of
standing on the reviewing platform with grand marshal Dan McCormick
on March 12.
   For years, Irish government representatives have turned their
backs or stepped off the reviewing stand when parade units of Irish
Northern Aid pass by. McCormick is president of the local chapter of
the Irish Northern Aid, a national organization dedicated to
supporting the IRA.
   Controversy erupted in New York City several years ago when
Michael Flannery of Irish Northern Aid served as grand marshal of
that city's parade, the biggest St. Patrick's Day parade in the
United States.
   This will be the first year that officials refuse to attend San
Francisco's parade.
   Despite Nason's declaration, parade officials are determined to
carry on with their plans.
   ``I have no intention whatsoever of making any changes,'' said
parade Chairman Denis Guiney. ``Let the parade continue as it is ...
I do not like politics in the parade ... Under no circumstances will
I be a party to the removal of the grand marshal.''
   Similarly, a spokeswoman for Mayor Art Agnos said Agnos still
plans to ride in the parade.
   ``As far as I know at this time, it's on his schedule to do,''
said spokeswoman Eileen Maloney, calling Nason's boycott ``serious
protocol for them. (But) I don't know what it means to us.''
   ``Generally, in San Francisco's parades a broad spectrum of
political opinion is not unusual,'' Maloney said.
   The Irish Republican Army is an outlawed, predominantly Roman
Catholic guerrilla group that has been fighting for more than 20
years to end British rule in Northern Ireland and unite the
Protestant-dominated province with the Irish Republic. But
Protestants in Northern Ireland, who outnumber Catholics in the
region, oppose unity with the Irish Republic, which is
overwhelmingly Roman Catholic.
   McCormick was elected grand marshal by a 2-to-1 margin by the
United Irish Societies, a group of about 30 local Irish civic and
cultural organizations.
   Vivian McDonagh, executive editor of the Irishman Newspaper, an
independent monthly publication, defended McCormick as more than a
leader of the Irish Northern Aid. She noted that he is a member of a
fife and drum corps and a former plumber's union official who helped
numerous Irish immigrants land jobs.
</TEXT>
