<FIRST>r a AM-BoneMarrow     02-28 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bone Marrow,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governor Says State Will Pay Costs of Boy's Operation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE RECHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State Medicaid will pay for a bone-marrow
transplant that could save a 6-year-old boy's life, Gov. Judd Gregg
said Tuesday as he tried to defuse embarrassing reports that the
state wouldn't pay.
   ``This is not a new policy,'' Gregg said at a statehouse news
conference called to clarify the state's position on paying for
Derek Annese's transplant. Reports to the contrary were the result
of a ``communications breakdown,'' he said.
   Gregg's assurances apparently silenced the public outcry, but not
the disagreement that arose when the boy's doctor and lawyer were
told it would take private donations to foot the bill.
   Boston Globe reporter Bob Hohler said he stood by last Sunday's
story that became the subject of talk shows and a donation drive.
Hohler said he discussed the case with several state officials,
including Health and Human Services Commissioner Mary Mongan, Gregg
spokesman Brian Grip and state Medicaid Director Phil Soule.
   ``None of them said the operation was covered,'' Hohler said.
``And Soule said it wasn't covered, and when I asked him who changed
the rules two years ago to drop coverage, he told me, `I guess I
did.'''
   But Gregg said the Globe story was ``inappropriate in its
representation'' of the state's position.
   Speaking directly to Hohler at the news conference, Gregg said,
``I can't say that you are correctly reflecting Soule's comments.''
   Gregg indicated that the confusion might have resulted because
the state covers indirect costs associated with a transplant, but
not the actual surgery.
   Ron Eskin, a New Hampshire Legal Assistance lawyer representing
the boy, said there was no breakdown in communication.
   ``I regard that (the governor's statement) as a total reversal of
his position, and that's great,'' he said. ``I'm not criticizing the
governor. I'm just saying we're not all crazy out here.''
   Soule was on vacation and could not be reached for comment
Tuesday.
   The boy and his mother also could not be reached; they were
concluding a vacation at Disneyworld in Florida.
   Doctors say Derek, who lives with his mother and two brothers in
Nashua on about $800 a month on public assistance, needs the
transplant to stay alive.
   About $150,000 is needed to pay for the operation,
hospitalization and other expenses, according to the Globe.
   Gregg said the state waited until Tuesday to go public on the
matter ``until we could get all the numbers.''
   He said the state's Medicaid money will take care of more than
$100,000 for hospitalization and other costs other than the surgery.
   The surgery will cost between $10,000 and $25,000, Gregg said,
adding that he and the Executive Council will use discretionary
funds to help pay some of that amount.
</TEXT>
