<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-SouthAfrica     02-28 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-South Africa,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Church Report Asks Tough British Policy on South Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British church leaders on Tuesday urged the
Conservative government to adopt a tough policy against South
Africa, including an immediate ban on air links.
   In a report released Tuesday, the leaders said Britain is
encouraging South Africa to believe change is not urgent.
   ``Apartheid will simply reform, adapt and survive,'' it said to
Britain's policy of ``mild diplomatic pressure and waiting for
economic growth.''
   The report was drawn up by the British Council of Churches, the
main representative body of Christian churches in Britain, and a
voluntary organization, Christian Aid.
   British exports to South Africa, official figures show, rose by
nearly 20 percent to $1.4 billion in the first nine months of last
year, compared with the same period in 1987.
   Britain is South Africa's third-largest trading partner, behind
Japan and West Germany.
   The report said Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's government
largely stuck to the letter of 15 relatively mild sanctions _
ranging from a longtime ban on arms sales to a ``voluntary ban'' on
promoting tourism, but not the spirit.
   ``The message brought home to the South African government is not
that change is urgently needed, but that Britain regards these
measures lightly,'' said the report.
   Mrs. Thatcher argues her policy increased British influence for
change in South Africa. She says sanctions would hurt South African
blacks most, harden white resistance to change, be circumvented and
cost jobs in Britain.
   The church report said the British government encouraged trade
with South Africa.
   ``There have been computer and radar sales which could be of use
to the military,'' it said.
   ``The voluntary ban on the promotion of tourism (agreed in
mid-1986) appears to have been carried out only through the dispatch
of two letters to tourist federations, and is not monitored by the
government.
   ``British Airways heavily advertises its South African flights,
including a link to the United States of America which replaces the
direct flights banned by the U.S. Congress.''
</TEXT>
