<FIRST>r a AM-HollywoodWars     02-28 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hollywood Wars,0558</SECOND>
<HEAD>From One Hollywood to the Next, Everybody's Mad at Tinseltown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hollywood officials from across the
country made it clear Tuesday that they don't want to pay royalties
to California's Tinseltown for the use of their own name.
   The Hollywood Chamber of Commerce in California is seeking a
trademark on use of the community's name, but 11 other Hollywoods
held a summit here to plot opposition to the ploy.
   ``It's ridiculous. It's really a joke, if you want to know the
truth,'' said Rodney Thompson, a county commissioner from Hollywood,
Md. ``It would have ramifications down the road which would be hard
to swallow.''
   James Ross Dover, representing Hollywood in northeast Georgia, a
rural town that dates back to 1807, was agitated by what he called
the arrogance of the West Coast entertainment enclave, which is
actually a neighborhood within the city of Los Angeles.
   ``My heart's aching from the anxiety that's being caused,'' Dover
said. ``Let's kindle the fire a little bit hotter because I'm hot.''
   Mara Giulianti, mayor of this seaside city of 125,000, organized
the protest after winning a 30-day extension on review of
California's trademark application, which was proposed in 1986.
   California officials say they're aiming only at commercial and
marketing use of the name, but Hollywood, Fla., city attorney Maria
Chiaro said the restrictions could also extend to ``educational and
legislative activity.''
   ``They would own the name,'' Ms. Giulanti explained, wearing a
rhinestone ``Hollywood'' on her jacket lapel. ``Any restriction of
our ability to promote ourselves ... any infringement of our name
should not be allowed and will not be allowed.''
   The Hollywoods represented were in Florida, Maryland, Alabama,
Texas, New Mexico, South Carolina, Mississippi, Georgia, Louisiana,
Illinois, and Arkansas.
   The Hollywood representatives agreed to work with trademark
attorneys to force Hollywood, Calif., to prove ownership of the
name, and agreed to draft a resolution for a joint fight and form an
unofficial sister cities program.
   Just to prove that some Californians are sympathetic to the other
Hollywoods, Marian Gibbons of Hollywoood Heritage Inc., the historic
preservation group for Hollywood, Calif., attended to show her
support.
   She carried a letter from the Sunset Plaza Civic Association,
representing about 400 households in the Hollywood Hills.
   ``It is our understanding that trademarks protect one's invention
or creation. It is obvious that the Hollywood Chamber of Commerce
did not create or invent Hollywood, rather the other way around,''
the association wrote to the U.S. Patents and Trademark Office.
   Ms. Gibbons confirmed that Hollywood, Calif., got its name from
an estate near Chicago, where Hollywood is now part of the village
of Brookfield, Ill.
   The Hollywood, Fla., meeting room was decorated with artwork and
essays from grammar school students who wanted to protect their
city's name.
   ``I love Hollywood because I like to shop 'til I drop. I like to
swim in the sea. I also like to go to a candy store. I like the
school the best,'' wrote second-grader Debb Lippman in an essay on
the theme, ``What Hollywood means to me.''
   Hollywood promoters distributed T-shirts and bumper stickers that
said ``We're the real Hollywood'' and a 7-foot costumed egret
attended as the Florida city's mascot.
</TEXT>
