<FIRST>r w AM-DerwinskiConfirmation     02-28 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Derwinski Confirmation,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Closed-Door Session Focuses on South Korean Incident</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Edward J. Derwinski said Tuesday his
confirmation as head of the new Veterans Affairs Department was
proceeding smoothly despite questioning by Senate panelists about an
incident with a South Korean defector.
   Emerging from a closed-door session of the Senate Veterans
Affairs Committee, Derwinski said his conclusion was based on ``just
my vibes'' and the nature of the committee's questions, which he
said went over old ground.
   ``As far as I'm concerned, it was a progressive, positive
meeting,'' Derwinski said. ``I'm perfectly confident that as a
result of this meeting, my confirmation is coming along nicely. I
don't see anything, as a result of this meeting, detrimental or
negative.''
   Derwinski's optimism was shared by the committee's senior
Republican, Frank Murkowski of Alaska, who said the nominee was
``healthy and handles himself well.''
   But chairman Alan Cranston, D-Calif., said he would rather wait
until Wednesday's session before commenting. The committee takes up
the nomination in open session Wednesday afternoon.
   The department is being formed on March 15 by elevation of the
Veterans Administration to Cabinet status. Derwinski has been
nominated for both the jobs of administrator of the VA and the
secretary of the department.
   Derwinski, until recently undersecretary of state of security
assistance, science and technology, has admitted telling the Korean
embassy in 1977 that an agent was about to testify before a House
committee of which he was a member.
   The committee was looking into the ``Koreagate'' scandal in which
the Korean government paid large bribes to members of Congress in
return for favorable action on matters important to Korea.
   The Korean agent, Sohn Young Ho, was spirited away from his New
Jersey home by FBI agents just a half-hour before colleagues from
the Korean Central Intelligence Agency arrived.
   After his congressional testimony, he was placed in the
government's protected witness program under a new identity.
   In 1978, Derwinski denied being the source of the information and
declined to answer grand jury questions. But he admitted it in 1983,
in testimony before the Senate Foreign Relations Committee
considering his nomination as State Department counselor after 12
terms in the House as a Republican from Illinois.
   Derwinski said he answered all questions ``to the fullest extent
of my recollection.''
   Derwinksi has said it did not occur to him that he could be
putting the agent in danger. He has said he did not even know Sohn's
identity.
