02-28 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Smokeless Cigarette, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0785,0501</SECOND>
<HEAD>R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Withdraws Premier Cigarette</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to ADD estimated cost of developing cigarette
and cost of national distribution; picks up 2nd graf pvs, ``The company
...'' A version moved on financial wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN PRICE WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumers didn't like them, so R.J. Reynolds
Tobacco Co. is withdrawing its Premier brand ``smokeless''
cigarettes after five months on market testing.
   Industry analysts speculated that RJR spent $200 million to $325
million to develop and launch Premier, while the aborted national
rollout of the product would have increased the cost to about $1
billion.
   The company said Tuesday in a statement that ``while smokers are
very interested in the concept, the current product has not achieved
adequate consumer acceptance.''
   ``The two primary areas that the test showed us we have to work
on is taste and the aroma,'' company spokesman David Fishel said.
``All I can say for competitive reasons is that we learned a lot in
the test marketing that we will be able to use later on.''
   R.J. Reynolds had test-marketed Premier in Arizona and eastern
Missouri.
   ``They're terrible. They're nasty. They're beyond nasty,'' Mark
Padgett, an employee at a 7-11 store in Phoenix, said shortly after
the cigarette hit the market in October.
   Premier was advertised as ``the cleaner smoke'' because, the
company said, it substantially reduced certain compounds found in
the smoke of tobacco-burning cigarettes and virtually eliminated
cigarette ashes and smoke.
   Several health organizations, including the American Medical
Association, asked the Food and Drug Admininstration to ban sale of
the cigarette. The AMA said Premier was a drug-delivery device, not
a cigarette.
   The cigarette works by heating instead of burning tobacco.
Smokers light a carbon heat source at the cigarette's tip. During
inhalation, air is heated by the smoldering carbon and passed over
an aluminum-encased flavor capsule.
   ``We are pleased to see R.J. Reynolds withdrawing Premier from
the market,'' Dr. James H. Sammons, executive vice president of the
AMA, said in a statement Tuesday. He said the AMA would continue to
pursue its request with the FDA, which has not issued a ruling yet.
   ``This probably makes that a moot petition,'' said Bill Grigg, a
spokesman for te FDA in Washington. Grigg said FDA lawyers would
have to review the situation.
   Last year, Reynolds refused a request from the Arizona Board of
Pharmacy to voluntarily withdraw the cigarette.
   Reynolds said Tuesday that it had no plans to reintroduce Premier
or a similar product ``unless we have fully addressed the issues
raised in the test markets.''
   Fishel said the company had used small groups to test Premier
before moving into the two-state test markets. Asked if the results
of the test-marketing differed from the reaction of small groups,
Fishel said, ``I think that's a safe statement.''
   Reynolds' major cigarette brands are Winston, Salem, Camel,
Vantage, Doral, Century, More, NOW and Ritz.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890228-0169 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 2107EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0767 02-28 0838</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0767,0863</SECOND>
<HEAD>Early Results Indicate Likud Posts Gains</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE results in some races, comment from
leaders. No pickup. Further results not expected until after 12:30 EST</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The right-wing Likud bloc scored major upsets
over the left-leaning Labor Party Tuesday in nationwide municipal
elections billed by Likud as a referendum on the Arab-Israeli
conflict, initial results indicated.
   In the key race in Jerusalem, pro-Labor Mayor Teddy Kollek was
re-elected to a sixth term but failed to win a majority in the city
council as religious parties doubled their representation.
   Throughout the country, ultra-Orthodox parties scored gains,
repeating their success of the November parliamentary elections.
   In Israel's Arab sector, Moslem fundamentalists ousted the
communist leadership of the second-largest city, Umm el Fahm,
sparking fears that anti-Israeli sentiments are spreading among
Israeli Arabs.
   Palestinians in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip were barred
from entering Israel Tuesday as an election security measure, police
said. In clashes in the occupied lands, Israeli troops fatally shot
a 25-year-old Palestinian and wounded four others, according to the
army and Arab doctors.
   The death brought to 387 the number of Palestinians killed in the
14-month-old uprising. Seventeen Israelis have also been killed.
   With about 43 percent of the vote counted, Likud appeared to have
won in several Labor strongholds, including the southern port city
of Ashdod and the city of Beer Sheba in the Negev Desert.
   About 48 percent of Israel's 2.7 million voters went to the
polls, down from 55 percent in 1983, as many Israelis spent the
sunny day on beaches and in parks instead of casting their votes.
   At stake were 147 races for local council and mayor. In 1983,
Labor won in 54 towns, compared to 26 taken by Likud. The remainder
went to local slates or religious parties.
   Labor leader Shimon Peres, finance minister, appeared
disappointed. ``There is always a place for soul searching. We'll do
it after we know the final results,'' he said on Israel army radio.
   Labor leaders had insisted that only local, not national issues
were at stake in the vote. But a sweeping defeat would further
accelerate Labor's decline as a national political force. Labor,
once the dominant party in Israel, has failed to win in the past
four national elections.
   Likud minister Ronni Milo claimed victory for his party and
suggested that success on the local level further strengthened Likud
on the national level.
   ``Maybe this is an indication of where Israeli politics are
going,'' Milo, minister for environmental protection, said on army
radio.
   Voters cast two ballots, one for mayor and the second for a party
slate.
   In Jerusalem, Kollek won 64 percent of the vote, while his ``One
Jerusalem'' slate, a Labor affiliate, received about 11 or 12 of 31
council seats, down from 17 in 1983, TV projections said.
   Religious parties more than doubled their votes, from 8.9 percent
in 1983 to 19.6 percent.
   Kollek, re-elected to his sixth term, said he would try to govern
with a minority in the council rather than form a coalition.
   The results ``will not help the proper administration of the
city,'' the 77-year-old Kollek said on Israel television.
   Kollek lost the majority in the council in part because of the
boycott by east Jerusalem's 80,000 Arab voters, traditionally Kollek
supporters. Fewer than 2 percent of the Arabs went to the polls,
compared to 18 percent in 1983.
   The boycott was ordered by the pro-PLO leadership of the
Palestinian uprising in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip. The
leaders called a general strike Tuesday to enforce the order and
urged Palestinians to punish those ignoring the boycott.
   ``I think each one of the over 3,000 Arabs who (has voted) is a
hero and should be given a medal,'' said Kollek.
   In Tel Aviv, Israel's second-largest city, Mayor Shlomo Lahat of
Likud won re-election to a fourth term with more than 50 percent of
the vote. Religious parties in Tel Aviv increased their vote from 10
percent in 1983 to 15 percent.
   But Lahat vowed that he would not succumb to demands by religious
parties, such as closing places of entertainment on the Jewish
Sabbath.
   In the port city of Haifa, a Labor stronghold for decades, Mayor
Arieh Gurel won 43 percent to narrowly defeat his Likud challenger,
Rami Dotan.
   The victory of the Islamic Movement in Umm el Fahm, a city of
more than 20,000 in northern Israel, sparked concern among Israeli
leaders.
   ``The Islamic Movement is a dangerous movement, and this reflects
what is happening in the Middle East,'' said Uzi Baram, Labor's
outgoing secretary- general.
   Results from other Arab towns were not yet available, but in the
past most have been run by communist or left-wing groups.
   About 10,000 police, civil guardsmen and volunteers were posted
at polling stations in case of violence.
   Police reported 152 election-related incidents, most related to
improper distribution of campaign material or ballot violations.
Twenty-four people were arrested.
</TEXT>
