<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon-Israel 3rdLd-Writethru a0751 02-28 0756</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Israel, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0751,0775</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Warplanes Strike Guerrilla Bases in Lebanon</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADD 2 grafs on Beirut crossing reopens</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEI1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AINAB, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli warplanes struck Palestinian bases
in the Chouf Mountains southeast of Beirut Tuesday, killing two
guerrillas and wounding 34 people, including 26 children at a nearby
elementary school, police said.
   Panicked children aged 4 to 10, some with blood streaming down
their faces, ran screaming and sobbing from the school, a teacher
said. A blackboard in one classroom still listed Tuesday's subject
for discussion: ``The War.''
   Five of the children were critically hurt when rockets exploded
within 25 yards of their school, only yards from a guerrilla base.
In addition, eight other people were wounded in the raid on the
bases by six fighter-bombers.
   The guerrilla casualties were members of the Democratic Front for
the Liberation of Palestine, a Marxist group that is part of the
Palestine Liberation Organization, said a police spokesman, who
cannot be identified under briefing rules.
   Five of the wounded were militiamen of the leftist Druse
Progressive Socialist Party. They were manning a post near Ainab, a
mountain village 9{ miles southeast of Beirut.
   The air strike coincided with the front's 20th anniversary and
came five days after the guerrilla group lost three fighters in an
attack on Israeli-backed militiamen in south Lebanon.
   The spokesman said the Israeli warplanes struck at 11:28 a.m. and
also hit bases belonging to Syrian-backed guerrilla factions near
the Druse villages of Shemlan, Aitat and Baysour.
   The fighter-bombers swooped down through clear skies for at least
three bomb and rocket runs in what an Israeli military spokesman in
Jerusalem said was a raid on a headquarters of the front.
   Palestinian, Druse and Shiite Moslem fighters fired anti-aircraft
guns at the raiders from positions in the mountains and around
Beirut airport, but no hits were reported.
   ``All our planes returned safely, and the targets were
destroyed,'' the Israeli spokesman said.
   The children were wounded by shrapnel and glass shards when two
rockets exploded within 25 yards of Ainab's government-sponsored
elementary school on the second floor of a two-story house.
   In one classroom, the youngsters were discussing the war as part
of Tuesday's lesson when the jets screamed in, an instructor said.
   ``All of a sudden glass started spraying the room,'' said teacher
Raja Jaber, who suffered head wounds. ``There was panic everywhere.
The children started screaming as blood streamed down their faces.
One of them cried, `Miss, it hurts!'
   The tree-ringed guerrilla base _ a two-story stone house and two
olive-green tents _ took several direct hits.
   Suheil Natour, a spokesman for the front, told The Associated
Press the guerrilla faction will ``step up ... military strikes
against Israel's occupation forces.''
   An Israeli Foreign Ministry official said the front's attack
Thursday was ``another example of the inability of the PLO to
fulfill its declared statement of stopping terror.''
   State Department spokesman Charles E. Redman said in Washington
that the Thursday incident and Israel's air strike underscored a
need for security arrangements to protect Israelis and Lebanese.
   ``We deplore the loss of life and needless suffering of innocent
people on both sides,'' he said.
   The U.S. designated contact with the PLO, Ambassador Robert
Pelletreau, criticized the Thursday raid as having a negative impact
on the 2-month-old U.S.-PLO dialogue and on prospects for
Israel-Palestinian talks.
   However, Redman said the State Department is still examining
whether the Thursday raid showed PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat broke
his promise in December not to engage in terrorism, which led the
United States to begin direct meetings with the PLO.
   The Israelis have charged that guerrilla raids launched since
then have undermined that declaration. The PLO says Arafat's
renunciation of terrorism does not include halting attacks on
military targets in Israel or Israeli-occupied territory.
   The Israeli raid was the third on targets in Lebanon this year.
By police count, at least 128 people were killed and 356 wounded in
25 Israeli air raids on Lebanon last year. There were no casualties
reported in the two raids earlier this year.
   In Beirut, rival Lebanese military forces on both sides of the
dividing Green Line on Tuesday reopened a crossing linking the
Christian and Moslem sectors that was closed for five years.
Pedestrians and motorists streamed across the Port Crossing, which
zigzags through the war-ravaged harbor area.
   Two other crossings in the center of Beirut have long been choked
by traffic and three other gateways in downtown Beirut and its
eastern suburbs remain closed.
</TEXT>
