<FIRST>u p AM-ChicagoMayoral 4thLd-Writethru a0790 02-28 0715</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chicago Mayoral, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0790,0733</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Daley Leads Sawyer in Early Returns</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New to dash with 23 percent of precincts reporting, GOP results,
quote from Sawyer aide; pickup after dash, `Most political ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard M. Daley jumped to an early lead Tuesday
as he sought to oust Mayor Eugene Sawyer and capture the Democratic
nomination for the office held by his father for 21 years.
   Following a campaign that many observers found tame by Chicago's
raucous standards, turnout in the primary election was lower than
expected, the Chicago Board of Election Commissioners said.
   The lower turnout appeared to favor Daley, since early
indications from an elections official who declined to be identified
were that black turnout was running about 10 percentage points
behind white voting.
   Daley jumped into the lead in very early returns from
predominantly white wards on the city's Southwest and Northwest
sides. With 23 percent of the city's 2,911 precincts reporting, he
had 122,144 votes or 63 percent to Sawyer's 69,348 votes or 36
percent. Three other candidates divided the remaining votes.
   The Republican primary, normally a non-event in Chicago politics,
was turned topsy-turvy by former Democratic Alderman Edward
Vrdolyak's last-minute write-in campaign. With 16 percent of the
precincts reporting, he had 1,320 votes, or 35 percent, to the
GOP-endorsed candidate Herbert Sohn's 1,748 votes, or 47 percent,
but some precincts were not immediately reporting the write-in
votes. Businessmen William Grutzmacher and Kenneth Hurst each had 9
percent.
   Because of the difficulty of counting write-in votes, the outcome
of the Republican race might not be known before Thursday.
   Adding further to the maneuvering, the two primary winners will
face a third opponent in the general election _ Timothy Evans, a
black alderman who is mounting a third-party bid on The Harold
Washington Party ticket.
   Sawyer needed heavy black turnout in order to duplicate the
victories of the late Harold Washigton, who became the city's first
black mayor in 1983 and four years later, the first since the elder
Daley to win re-election.
   Sawyer campaign manager Reynard Rochon said he was disappointed
with the turnout.
   ``In the last hour and a half of voting, there was a surge in
Sawyer voters,'' Rochon said. ``Whether or not that surge came up
high enough to offset the gap in the turnout between the white and
black votes, we don't know.''
   In both of Washington's primary victories, black turnout was 75
percent, and 98 percent of those votes went to the late mayor.
   Daley, 46, a three-term Cook County state's attorney, was making
his second bid for the seat once occupied by his father, Richard J.
Daley, the legendary big-city boss who died in office in 1976.
   The younger Daley lost his 1983 bid in the Democratic primary to
Washington, who died in office in 1987.
   Sawyer, 54, who had been an alderman for 16 years, was appointed
acting mayor by a bitterly divided council a week after Washington
died.
   A Daley victory Tuesday, followed by another in the April 4
general election, would mark the first time a white has ousted a
black mayor in one of the nation's largest cities. The winner of the
general election will serve until 1991.
   A newspaper poll a week ago had Sawyer gaining on Daley but still
8 percentage points behind. Daley held a 7 percentage point lead in
a late poll sponsored by a local newspaper and television station.
   Thirty-one of the city's 1,406 polling places opened late in
light snow, but skies cleared and temperatures climbed into the 20s.
Tuesday afternoon, a circuit judge ordered the 31 locations to stay
open an exta hour.
   Sawyer voted about 9 a.m. near his South Side home, telling
reporters, ``I'm glad it's finally over.''
   Vrdolyak, 51, voted about the same time at a church in his South
Side ward and Daley cast his ballot about an hour later at a
recreation center a block from his home, saying ``I'm confident
about today.''
   Also on the Democratic primary ballot were former state
legislator James Taylor, 59, Sheila Jones, 38, a disciple of jailed
political extremist Lyndon LaRouche, and Alderman Lawrence Bloom,
who withdrew too late to have his name removed from the ballot.
</TEXT>
