<FIRST>u w AM-ChildhoodInjuries 1stLd-Writethru a0715 02-28 0659</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Childhood Injuries, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0715,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Homicide Leading Cause of Injury Deaths Among U.S. Infants, Study
Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To CORRECT figure from thousand to 100,000, subs 17th graf:
Counting all....</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More very young children die from murder than
from any other category of injury-caused death, according to a new
study by researchers at Johns Hopkins University.
   The study, released Tuesday, says that from the years 1980 to
1985, a total of 1,250 children under one year of age died of
homicide, a finding that stunned researchers who compiled the
report, said Anna E. Waller of the Injury Prevention Center at Johns
Hopkins.
   ``The rate of homicide for that age group was very steady across
each of the six years,'' she said. ``The data probably has always
been there, but nobody has looked at it in just this way before.''
   Murder accounted for 17 percent of all of the injury deaths among
children in the age group, she said. The homicide death rate for the
infants was 5.68 per 100,000 per year, fractionally higher than for
infants killed in vehicle accidents, the most common type of injury
deaths among all other age groups.
   ``We don't have any good explanation,'' said Ms. Waller.
   Of the 1,250 infants murdered, one-third were reported to have
died of what was called ``child abuse,'' which would include beating
and battering, she said. About 11 percent died of suffocation or
strangulation, 3 percent from drowning, 3 percent from stabbing and
about 5 percent from firearms.
   Ms. Waller said 6.5 percent of the murdered infants died of what
is called neglect-abandonment. This would include babies left alone
or neglected ``with intent to injure or kill.''
   The balance of the infants died of unspecified or unreported
homicide causes.
   Infant homicides were included in a massive study by the Hopkins
group of all types of injury deaths among children.
   Though there were declines in most categories, Ms. Waller said
suicides among children aged 10 to 14 more than doubled from 1980 to
1985.
   ``This is the one category where we saw a great increase,'' she
said. ``It went up each year. It is terribly shocking.''
   Suicides in the 10- to 14-year-old group increased from a rate of
.76 per 100,000 in 1980, to 1.61 per 100,000 in 1985. Most killed
themselves with guns or by hanging.
   ``Some of the increase may be due to a greater willingness to
classify deaths as suicides,'' Ms. Waller said. ``But I don't think
that is enough of an explanation for the increases that we saw.''
   The Hopkins study found that injuries continue to be the leading
cause of death among children under age 14, with such traumas
costing about 10,000 childhood lives a year.
   As a whole, motor vehicle-related accidents killed the most
children. The report said that 22,174 children died in such
accidents during the six years studied, about 37 percent of all
injury-related child deaths.
   Other major causes of death were drowning, house fires,
suffocation, accidental shooting, falls, choking on food or other
objects, poison, electrical accidents and farm machinery accidents.
   Counting all causes, the average injury death rate among children
for the six years was about 19.3 per 100,000.
   For ages 1 to 4, injuries accounted for 44 percent of all deaths.
The rate was 51 percent for ages 5 to 9, and 58 percent for ages 10
to 14.
   In 26 states, injuries received as a passenger in a motor vehicle
were the leading cause of death for children 14 and under.
   For the same age group, house fires were the leading cause of
injury death in 11 states, drowning in 10 states, and pedestrian
accidents in Massachusetts, New York and Rhode Island.
   In the District of Columbia, homicide was the the leading cause
of death among children up to the age of 14.
   The study was published in the March issue of the American
Journal of Public Health.
</TEXT>
