<FIRST>r a AM-DrugRing     02-28 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Ring,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Feds Bust Up International Drug Ring</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight people were charged Tuesday with running a
sophisticated drug ring that exported cocaine to Italy, where it was
traded for heroin that was shipped to U.S. drug dealers, federal
authorities said.
   A lengthy investigation by U.S., Italian and Canadian law
enforcement authorities resulted in the arrests on Monday at seven
locations in the city and on Long Island, law enforcement officials
said.
   The investigation centered on an Italian crime organization
called N'drangheta which is similar in structure to the Mafia and is
heavily involved in shipping heroin into the United States, said
Assistant U.S. Attorney Andrew C. McCarthy.
   The crime group imported heroin into the United States paid for
with cocaine, which was smuggled out of the country and shipped to
Italy, where it is in great demand, McCarthy said.
   The drug barter system to a large extent eliminated the trail
that would have been left had cash been used to pay for the heroin,
he said.
   The defendants allegedly shipped at least some cocaine to Italy
through the mail, authorities said.
   Last Thursday, two of the defendants charged Tuesday allegedly
mailed a box containing about 14 pounds of cocaine to Italy.
   However, drug agents who learned of the plan through a wiretap
intercepted the shipment of drugs, authorities said.
   Defendant Vincenzo Restagno, 24, who lives in Toronto, few there
a few days earlier from Italy with $350,000 in Italian currency,
which authorities say was brought to the United States and used to
buy cocaine.
   Searches and arrests, which went late into the night on Monday,
produced numerous weapons as well as drug paraphernalia, officials
said.
</TEXT>
