<FIRST>u a AM-AgingAirliners-Orders     02-28 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Aging Airliners-Orders,0515</SECOND>
<HEAD>Replacing Aging Jets Won't Be Easy, Analysts Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING a0810 to fix category code. A version also moving
on the financial wire.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Aging Airliners, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The crisis over aging jetliners should mean more
new orders placed with manufacturers, some industry analysts say.
But others ask whether new orders will solve airlines' problems.
   ``At this point, pouring more orders into the funnel isn't going
to make more airplanes come out at the bottom,'' Wolfgang H.
Demisch, an aerospace strategist at the New York office of Union
Bank of Switzerland, said Tuesday.
   ``The greater risk is that in this rush suppliers will be
overstretched and can't deliver as quickly as expected,'' Demisch
said. ``Already there are components in tight supply, and that's not
going to get much easier.''
   Reacting to the Aging Aircraft Task Force's recommendation that
the Federal Aviation Administration order $800 million in mandatory
maintenance, many analysts predicted the pressure to replace older
planes would increase.
   Paul H. Nisbet of Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. said airlines
saw the need to replace planes several years ago as maintenance
costs began rising and began placing orders accordingly.
   ``I think a lot of orders seen in the last two or three years
have been for replacement,'' Nisbet said. ``Before that orders were
just for traffic growth.''
   Nisbet said that of the 600 to 700 new plane orders he sees in
each of the next few years as many as 200 to 300 will be to replace
older planes.
   ``The replacement cycle has begun,'' he said.
   Boeing Co.'s stock has held firm in the $60 range during the
latest incident involving a plane it built, a United Airlines 747
flying from Honolulu to New Zealand. Its forward fuselage ripped
after takeoff.
   Nine passengers were sucked from the plane and hurled to their
deaths. Investigators have focused on a forward cargo door as a
likely cause.
   George Shapiro of Salomon Brothers Inc. in New York said
consumers haven't blamed carriers or Boeing for the United incident,
the crash of a British Midland Airways 737, which killed 44; or for
the Aloha Airlines 737 which lost part of its cabin in flight,
killing a stewardess.
   ``There's no question Boeing is going through a string of
unfortunate troubles, from crashes, holes developing in its planes
in flight, and with quality problems on new aircraft,'' he said.
   ``But Boeing has more planes out there than any other
manufacturer and they are getting older,'' Shapiro said in an
interview with the Seattle Times.
   Boeing officials have said repeatedly that there is no connection
between the recent spate of accidents, and that their timing is the
result of coincidence and not quality problems on Boeing's assembly
lines.
   Demisch said manufacturers Boeing, McDonnell Douglas and Airbus
Industrie already face challenges in meeting commitments already
made. All three manufacturers are enjoying a boom in aircraft orders.
   For some models, orders placed today won't be fulfilled until
1996, he noted.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
