<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     02-28 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five Reported Killed In Rocket Attacks In Eastern Afghanistan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Long-range artillery fire and rockets
blasted residential areas in Afghanistan's eastern Nangarhar
province, killing five people, state-run Radio Kabul said Tuesday.
   The broadcast, monitored in Islamabad, said some victims were
killed in the provincial capital of Jalalabad, about 40 miles west
of the Pakistani border. Rockets also fell in Rodat and Mazina,
southeast of Jalalabad, it said.
   The attacks reportedly occurred during the previous 24 hours. The
radio blamed them on ``criminals,'' an apparent reference to
U.S.-backed Afghan rebels.
   Also in eastern Afghanistan, Moslem rebels shelled a communist
radio station after it broadcast repeated taunts and insults, a news
agency said.
   Agency Afghan Press, a private Pakistani news service which
favors the resistance, said the rebels prepared to attack troops
holding the besieged city of Khost on Feb. 24 but communist
``agents'' leaked the plans.
   The radio warned Khost residents that ``troublemakers'' were
preparing to attack.
   ``Abuse and filthy language were repeatedly used against the
mujahedeen (holy warriors) in the broadcasts, and the puppet
administration kept on posing the challenge,'' the agency said.
   Rebels responded by blasting the station with ``half a dozen
shells'' from a heavy gun and the radio has been silent since, the
agency said.
   It said 24 mujahedeen were killed in fighting last week around
Khost. It gave no figures for communist casualties.
   The guerrillas, headquartered in Pakistan, have been waging a
decade-long battle against Afghanistan's ruling communists.
   Moscow ended nine years of military intervention in Afghanistan
on Feb. 15. The Soviet Union sent troops into the Central Asian
country in December 1979 to replace one communist government with
another.
   Afghan President Najib, who uses only one name, established a
state of emergency within three days of the Soviet withdrawal.
</TEXT>
