<FIRST>r a AM-People-Brown     02-28 0209</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Brown,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Free James Brown' Song Sent to Radio Stations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A local record producer and a songwriter are
deluging the nation's radio stations with a pop-funk single calling
for the release of soul singer James Brown from prison.
   Brown, the 55-year-old, self-proclaimed ``Godfather of Soul,'' is
serving a six-year sentence in a South Carolina prison on an array
of charges stemming from a two-state chase Sept. 24.
   The song ``Free James Brown'' was picked up by 386 ABC-affiliated
radio stations last week, and 1,700 copies of the single were being
sent to other stations nationwide this week.
   ``Free James Brown'' calls for the release of Brown, and includes
such verses as ``Butane James ... the man has too much soul.''
   Record producer Ron Deutschendorf said he has spent nearly $5,000
getting the song recorded and distributed. He and songwriter Robert
Lusson hope the record will start a movement to have Brown released
or transferred to a halfway house.
   Brown is known for such songs as ``Papa's Got A Brand New Bag''
and ``Living in America.''
   ``James Brown is a national treasure,'' Deutschendorf told USA
Today. ``He was instrumental in the development of pop music. I
don't think they would have treated Elvis this way.''
</TEXT>
