<SECOND>AM-Big East-Playboy, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0720,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Playboy's Controversial Big East Conference Issue Hits Newsstands</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead to CORRECT spelling of newsstand; SUBS 5th graf, ``The
Big ...,'' to CORRECT that University of Connecticut, sted Connecticut
College, is member of Big East.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY STERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOUTH ORANGE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Administrators at Big East schools
adamantly opposed Playboy's attempts to recruit students to pose for
its pages, but the magazine succeeded and the results hit the
newsstands Tuesday.
   Administrators at all nine Big East Conference schools, six of
which are Roman Catholic, barred Playboy photographers from
interviewing on campus and did not allow advertising in campus
publications, said Elizabeth Norris, a spokeswoman for the
Chicago-based magazine. Some area hotels also prohibited interviews.
   ``All this publicity just backfires on the schools by getting the
word out,'' she said, adding that sales have been known to increase
as much as 600 percent in areas featured in an issue.
   She said Playboy expects to exceed the standard monthly
circulation of 3.4 million issues, but would not specify how many
extra issues had been prepared.
   The Big East Conference comprises Boston College, Georgetown
University, Providence College, St. John's University, Seton Hall
University,and Villanova University _ all Catholic schools _ and the
University of Connecticut, University of Pittsburgh and Syracuse
University.
   ``It's such a strange way to represent your school,'' said Cathy
Liathead, a 20-year-old junior at Seton Hall in South Orange. ``The
students don't really support it, but I don't think anybody believes
anything should be done against them.''
   One of the models in the issue, Kimberly Adamonis, 22, of Rhode
Island's Providence College, said she is proud of her decision. She
said her boyfriend, now her husband, encouraged her to go to the
Playboy interview.
   ``I do respect Providence College, but you've also got to have
dreams and ideals for yourself,'' she said.
</TEXT>
