<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 2247EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u p AM-DaleyProfile     02-28 0579</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Daley Profile,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>Younger Daley Struggling to Escape His Father's Long Shadow</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhotos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard M. Daley is short and stocky and, on
occasion, stubborn. Unmistakably his father's son.
   But as he stands within striking distance of the fifth-floor City
Hall office occupied for 21 years by his father, the late Richard J.
Daley, he can proudly say he got there the old-fashioned way _ he
earned it.
   To be sure, he has benefited from the name, the lucrative
assignments while he was a young attorney in private practice, his
election to the Illinois Senate at age 29, and the successful bids
for three terms as Cook County's top prosecutor.
   But the 46-year-old Daley, who defeated Mayor Eugene Sawyer in
Tuesday's Democratic primary, has suffered because of the name as
well. Critics have dogged his every step up the political ladder,
suggesting his achievements have been little more than an accident
of birth.
   ``If his name wasn't Richard Daley, he'd be working in the Post
Office,'' said Rob Warden, editor of Chicago Lawyer.
   Both assessments miss the point, said Eugene Kennedy, a Loyola
University professor, veteran political analyst and author of
``Himself,'' a biography of the elder Daley.
   ``There is an old Chinese proverb that says, in essence, `Grass
grows short under a big tree.' And plenty of sons are considered
failures when measured against their fathers,'' said Kennedy.
   ``The truth is, there's nobody like his father. ... But Rich has
acquired a confidence in himself and his judgment that resemble the
father in some ways. And he's overcome enough adversity on his own _
the loss of a young son, the loss in his first (mayoral) run in 1983
_ to establish a separate identity, to start the long climb out from
under his father's shadow,'' Kennedy said.
   The eldest of seven children, Daley cut his political teeth
working as an 18-year-old page for the Illinois delegation to the
1960 Democratic National Convention.
   Twelve years and a law degree later _ he passed the bar exam
after a third try _ Daley's political career began in earnest in the
Illinois Senate.
   He was criticized in his early years, labeled ``his father's eyes
and ears.''
   But Daley showed more acumen than many gave him credit for,
forging cautious alliances with reformers _ opponents of his
father's vaunted Democratic machine _ and championing social-welfare
legislation affecting nursing homes and abolishing taxes on certain
foods and medicine.
   His father's death in 1976 _ several months into a sixth term _
caused an irreparable rift in the political organization the
longtime mayor had so zealously guarded.
   As a result, four years later, the younger Daley ran for Cook
County state's attorney as an outsider against Alderman Edward
Burke, the party's endorsed candidate.
   Daley clobbered Burke, then twice won re-election as the county's
top prosecutor. Along the way, he proved himself a savvy campaigner,
able to use his name and his father's cronies, but receptive to new
ideas and alliances.
   That knack he may have gotten from his father.
   State Sen. Howard Carroll, who was a law school friend, recalled
that Daley carried a dictionary ``so he could look up any word he
didn't know.
   ``And while he was looking up that word, he'd always look for
another word he didn't know on the same page so he could learn a new
word,'' said Carroll.
   ``I think he got that from his father.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890228-0186 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 2337EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-WarDead     02-28 0187</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-War Dead,0192</SECOND>
<HEAD>Military Identifies Six War Dead, Names Four</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The remains of six U.S. servicemen recently
returned by the Republic of Vietnam have been identified, the U.S.
Pacific Command announced Tuesday.
   They were among 23 remains returned by the Vietnamese last Nov.
3, the command said.
   The other remains are still undergoing analysis in an attempt to
determine identification, officials said.
   The names of four of the identified were released, but the
families of two asked that the names be withheld, the command said.
   Identified were Navy officers Cmdr. Charles E. Barnett of
Houston, lost May 23, 1972; Cmdr. Clarence O. Tolbert, Tishomingo,
Okla., lost Nov. 6, 1972; Lt. Cmdr. Robert T. Hanson Jr., Toledo,
Ohio, lost Feb. 3, 1966; and Lt. Frederick M. Kasch, San Diego,
Calif., lost July 2, 1967.
   Full military honors were scheduled for Thursday morning when the
remains of five of the six are scheduled to depart Hickam Air Force
Base for Travis Air Force Base in California for their final journey
home, the command said.
   Barnett's remains have already been taken to California, the
command said.
</TEXT>
