<FIRST>r a AM-TraderBanned     02-28 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trader Banned,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trader Fined $1.125 Million, Banned From Board Of Trade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chicago Board of Trade has levied a $1.125
million fine against a man convicted of devising a scam that
involved wearing disguises to back out of ill-fated deals in the
trading pits.
   Thompson Sanders also was banned for life from the exchange, but
his attorney says he'll appeal.
   The commodity exchange's decision comes four months after a
federal judge sentenced Sanders to six years in prison and fined him
$300,000 for masterminding a scheme that involved disguising a
trader in a wig and makeup to make illegal transactions in the
Treasury Bond pit.
   Prosecutors said that because of the disguises, Sanders and three
others were able to pocket more than $300,000 from good trades while
backing out of losing trades without detection.
   The BOT fine of $1.125 million imposed on Sanders is the maximum
penalty that exchange rules allow for his 15 rule violations.
   At the time of his conviction, U.S. District Judge Marvin Aspen
said Sanders' crimes represented ``the tip of the iceberg'' and that
because of loose regulations, the BOT was a potential ``cesspool''
of corruption.
   Since disclosure last month of the FBI investigation into fraud
at Chicago's futures exchanges, the BOT has increased the maximum
fine from $75,000 to $250,000 per violation. The BOT also has
extended the period during which former members could be subject to
discipline, from 30 days to five years.
   In addition, the exchange said it would spend $1 million to
improve its computerized surveillance system.
   Sanders, free on $300,000 bond, has appealed the criminal
conviction. He also will appeal the BOT decision on grounds that the
board does not have jurisdiction over him, said his attorney,
Stephen Senderowitz.
   ``Sanders is not a member, nor was he at the time he was charged
in the criminal case or in the exchange disciplinary proceeding,''
Senderowitz said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
