<HEAD>For release Fri PMs March 3, or thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>New United Church Head Nominated In Transitional Time</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A United Church of Christ committee has chosen
the Rev. Paul H. Sherry of Chicago as its nominee for the presidency
of the 1.7 million-member denomination as it enters a transitional
period.
   The long-term post is an influential office among America's
mainline Protestant bodies.
   Filling it comes as new ecumenical strides and headquarters
changes are being considered by the historic denomination whose
roots go back to the early American Pilgrims.
   Sherry, 55, who heads a church-renewal organization in Chicago,
was nominated after a year long search by a nominating committee
from among six finalists.
   The results were announced last week by church headquarters here.
   He was nominated to succeed the Rev. Avery D. Post, 66, who plans
to retire this fall after holding the top office for 12 years, or
three four-year terms.
   The election is to be at the biennial meeting of the
denomination's general synod June 29-July 4 in Fort Worth, Texas.
Other nominations may be made from the floor of that top
deliberative body, involving more than 700 delegates.
   They also are to consider recommendations that the church move
its headquarters from New York to Cleveland, which some agencies are
resisting.
   Delegates also are to act on a proposal for full communion with
the 1.2 million-member Christian Church (Disciples of Christ),
providing for mutual recognition of members, ministry and
celebrations of the Lord's Supper.
   Picking a new president also comes amid friction between an
evangelical wing wanting more emphasis on winning souls to Christ
and a long-predominant liberal wing stressing work for social
justice.
   The denomination, a 1957 merger of the Evangelical and Reformed
Church and Congregational Christians stemming from the colonial
Puritans, also is grappling with an ``identity problem'' to shape a
more distinctive image.
   The 18-member nominations committee began its search in January
1988, after Post disclosed he would not run again. It initially had
a pool of 46 potential candidates, 39 men and seven women.
   They were suggested by various sectors of the church across the
country. The list had been pared down to five men and one woman who
were interviewed at the committee's meeting in Cleveland.
   Concerning Sherry, the Rev. Patricia Ross of Portland, Ore., who
chairs the nominating committee, said, ``We feel he brings just the
right combination of experience, skills and visiion to lead our
denomination into the 1990's.''
   The committee also nominated Doris R. Powell of Berkeley, Calif.,
for another national office, director of finance and treasurer.
   Sherry, in a statement, said of his stance:
   ``I am committed to reach out to all people, whatever their
background or circumstance; to nurture the church's congregational
and institutional life; to hold high the ecumenical vision and to
help build a society of peace with justice.''
   Sherry has been executive director since 1983 of Chicago's
church-related Community Renewal Society, managing a staff of 55 and
a current budget of $3 million.
   It aids congregations and community groups, does social-justice
advocacy work, runs training workshops for ministers, lay leaders
and theological students, and a camp and center for children.
   Sherry, who has been a host on religion talk shows in Chicago and
New York, travels extensively as a guest speaker. He previously
worked in New York for the church's domestic missions arm, the Board
for Homeland Ministries.
   Earlier he had served seven years as a parish pastor in Hasbrouck
Heights, N.J., and Reading, Pa.
   Ms. Powell, 38, was nominated from a pool of 15 candidates of
whom three were interviewed, to replace Charles Lockyear of
Pleasantville, N.Y., who is finishing seven terms _ 28 years _ as
church treasurer.
   She currently is studying theology at Berkeley's Pacific School
of Religion and previously was manager of accounting systems for
Suntec Industries, Inc., in Rockford, Ill., for four years.
   She earlier had worked for seven years as a budget analyst and
accounting supervisor for Sundstrand, Hydro-Transmission Division in
Ames, Iowa. Before that, she was a certified public accountant in
her native St. Louis and Detroit.
   The six finalists from whom Sherry was chosen included two
blacks, the Rev. W. Sterling Cary, 61, of Westchester, Ill, and the
Rev. Yvonne V. Delk, 49, of Union City, N.J., head of the church
social-action arm since 1981.
   The other three were the Rev. Robert G. Kemper, 53, of Western
Springs, Ill.; the Rev. Otto E. Sommer, 58, of Yarmouth, Maine, and
the Rev. Frederick R. Trost, 53, of Madison, Wis.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs March 3.</NOTE>
