<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 1306EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a AM-ReligionToday Adv03   02-28 0918</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Religion Today, Adv 03,0946</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri AMs, March 3, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Pope And U.S. Archbishops Meeting To Iron Out Relationships</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: This first of two articles about next week's papal discussions
with U.S. archbishops deals with problems on the American scene. A second
article, looking at Vatican talks with other national heirarchies, is BC-Vatican-Bishops,
moving as b0614 for Sunday, March 5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Intended to ease strains between the Vatican and
U.S. Catholicism, an extraordinary summit meeting convenes next week
between American archbishops and Pope John Paul II.
   He calls the concentrated four days of talks a ``fraternal
encounter.'' Archbishops say they expect a friendly, mutually
cooperative mood.
   ``This isn't shaping up as a confrontation but rather as a
helpful exchange of views among church leaders looking for ways to
work together effectively,'' says Cardinal Joseph Bernardin of
Chicago.
   Several of the earlier tensions have faded, but others remain,
such as the handling of dissent from church regulations and the
status of the bishops' national organization itself.
   ``That, in a way, is perhaps most important,'' says the Rev.
Thomas J. Reeske of Washington, D. C., whose research has made him a
leading authority on attitudes of U.S. bishops.
   He added in an interview:
   ``The issue is whether episcopal conferences have the right and
authority to teach and make decisions that have an impact on the
life of the church in the United States, or whether all the
decisions are to be made in Rome.
   ``The trend has been toward centralizing decisions in Rome.''
   Differences with the Vatican both on approaches to dissent and
the rights of the bishops' national conference showed up only at
their meeting last November.
   The Vatican intervened to get them to postpone acting on their
document, ``Doctrinal Responsibilities'' on dealing with dissent.
Also, the bishops disapproved a Vatican draft, minimizing the role
of bishops' conferences.
   It was returned as unsuitable even as ``a basis for discussion.''
   The bishops and the Vatican also temporarily differed over makeup
of the summit meeting itself. They, in 15 regional sessions last
fall, had elected representatives to attend, but the Vatican said
no, it wanted only archbishops.
   That was ``another slight'' of the bishops' conferences, Reese
said, adding their elected representatives would have had ``some
kind of mandate,'' but that's not directly the case with the
archbishops.
   Twenty-one of the 35 U.S. participants in the March 9-11 Vatican
meeting were appointed by the present pope. The agenda says they'll
have more than 12 hours of open discussion with him and heads of his
cabinet, the Curia.
   The theme, in generalizing Vatican terminology, is
``Evangelization in the Context of the Culture and Society of the
United States of America with Particular Emphasis on the Role of the
Bishop as Teacher of the Faith.''
   The opaque language refers to the impact of Christian values on
society and culture, a special concern of the pope. Examining that
``big picture ought to be a positive thing,'' Reese said. ``The
danger is the talk will just be in the abstract.''
   Reese of Woodstock Theological Center at Washington's Georgetown
University, has individually interviewed the country's archbishops
for his forthcoming book, ``Archbishop: Inside the Power Structure
of the American Catholic Church,'' to be published in May by Harper
&amp; Row.
   He predicted ``conflict will be minimal'' at the Vatican meeting.
   On various matters, such as the pope's insistence on individual
confession before first communion and his criticism of a previously
extensive practice of giving general absolution without confession,
Reese said:
   ``The bishops have sort of caved in. It's no longer a big
problem. On a lot of issues, the bishops' conference has given up
its way of doing things. Basically it's doing what the Vatican
wants.''
   Bishops, at the Vatican's behest, banned special services for a
homosexual organization, Dignity, in many dioceses. Under Vatican
and other criticism of a document on AIDS, the bishops last spring
decided to write another one.
   Other issues also have receded since U.S. bishops first suggested
the meeting in 1986 when their then president, Bishop James Malone
of Youngstown, Ohio, cited ``a growing and dangerous disaffection''
from the Holy See.
   That was at a time of extensive resentment at the Vatican's
curtailing authority of Seattle's Archibishop Raymond Hunthausen,
since restored.
   Differences still persist _ though now partly mollified _ between
U.S. Catholic educators and Vatican proposals for closer church
supervision over Catholic colleges and universities.
   Of the upcoming meeting, the pope has said it will deal with
impressions both of his 1987 visit to the United States, and a 1988
series bishops' visits with the pope.
   Several bishops say the visits had a mostly positive, upbeat
tone. The pope is bullish on the U. S. church, says Archbiship John
L. May of St. Louis, president of the National Conference of Bishops.
   However, the pope has pressed his insistence on doctrinal
conformity, saying of the U.S. scene:
   ``Certain positions on the so-called `right to dissent' have had
harmful repercussions on the moral conduct of a number of the
faithful. There is a tendency on the part of some Catholics to be
selective in their adherence to the church's moral teaching.''
   The pope also says he wants ``more systematic efforts'' on behalf
of natural family planning, more emphasis on the church's ban on
contraception, widely practiced among U.S. Catholics, and efforts to
revive weekly Mass attendance, now down to an average 52 percent.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, March 3</NOTE>
