<FIRST>a a AM-ReligionRdp Adv03   02-28 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Religion Rdp, Adv 03,0580</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri AMs, March 3, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRINCETON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Religion still is the most trusted
institution on the American scene, but the military now holds almost
as much confidence and the U.S. Supreme Court is close behind.
   These are among the latest rankings of the comparative
trustworthiness of 10 insitutions in Gallup polls.
   For more than a decade until 1985, religion had stood alone at
the top of the list, but the military has been edging up since 1981,
barely topping religion in 1986, but slipping a bit behind in 1988.
   Confidence in the Supreme Court also has been climbing, with 56
percent of Americans now having ``a great deal'' or ``quite a lot''
of trust in it. That compares to 58 percent in the military and 59
percent in religion.
   Other institutions and percentages of confidence in them are
banks, 49; public schools, 49; newspapers, 36; Congress, 35,
televsion, 27; organized labor, 26; big business, 25.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Methodist Publishing House
says advance orders for the denomination's new hymnal, to start
rolling off the presses in April, have passed the 2 million-mark.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief executive of American Baptist Churches
says mainline Protestantism is suffering from an ``ecclesiastical
malaise'' that ``touches almost every point in our denominational
and ecumenical life.''
   The Rev. Daniel Weis, in in a sermon at New York's Riverside
Church, compared mainline Protestantism to the Prophet Ezekiel's
vision of a ``valley of dead, dry bones.''
   However, he said ``these bones can live'' through ``our
transformation as a people revitalized by the spirit.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Churches need to recover a ``sense of
Sunday,'' says the Rev. Gordon Lathrop of Lutheran Theological
Seminary at Philadelphia.
   ``Sunday is everything,'' he told leaders of the Evangelical
Lutheran Church in America. ``Sunday matters.'' He criticized making
Sunday a ``marketing technique'' by designating it as some limited
type of Sunday, such as ``youth Sunday, women's Sunday or
multicultural Sunday.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   NEW YORK _ A U.S. Catholic Conference official says viewers
concerned about fighting sleaze on television should seek a
coalition with responsible advertising executives.
   Richard Hirsch, director of the conference office for film and
broadcasting, suggests contacting him regarding to whom and where to
write as a part of such a campaign.
   He made his statement after NBC abolished its standards division,
which monitored program content, saying that if this step wins more
audience for NBC without ``flack from viewers,'' CBS and ABC are
likely to do the same.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Talking with youth about questions of faith
differs little from talking with anyone else, the Rev. Will Willimon
of Duke University told a conference of adult leaders with youth.
   ``We may have a crisis of faith,'' he said, ``but it's not just
with youth.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The International Jewish Committee on
Interreligious Consultations has expressed ``deep regret'' that
Roman Catholic leaders have not met a Feb. 22 deadline, set in an
agreeement two years ago, for closing a Carmelite convent at the
former Auschwitz concentration camp in Poland.
   The organization said that until the convent is moved outside the
Auschwitz grounds, discussions planned with Vatican representatives
on anti-Semitism and the Holocaust cannot move forward.
</TEXT>
