<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 1310EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-Vatican-BishopsAdv05     02-28 0774</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Vatican-Bishops Adv 05,0794</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, March 5, or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Pope Setting Pattern Of Direct Dealing With Bishops</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   During his 10-year pontificate, John Paul II
has summoned Dutch bishops to Rome in an attempt to settle a serious
rift and called Brazilian bishops over liberation theology. Now it
is the Americans' turn.
   More than 30 U.S. archbishops and two Eastern rite metropolitans
will take part in a special four-day meeting at the Vatican March
8-11.
   The initiative for the meeting came from the Americans in 1986,
when relations between the U.S. church and the Holy See appeared
particularly tense. But in the end it was the pope who wanted the
meeting held, according to Vatican spokesman Joaquin Navarro.
   After the pope's visit to the United States in 1987 and a series
of private talks at the Vatican involving American bishops last
year, the U.S. side no longer believed the special meeting was
necessary, Navarro said.
   ``But the pope insisted on the idea,'' he said.
   While the whole range of issues involving the church in America
is likely to be discussed, the main theme is expected to be the role
of bishops.
   ``What bishops should be doing, out preaching the Gospel in a
secularized society, is what I believe the meeting is about,'' said
one senior Vatican official, speaking on condition his name not be
used.
   He said the pope does not want bishops to be managers, but rather
ardent proponents of church teaching.
   Speaking out on unpopular issues may be difficult, the official
said, but added that in the pope's view ``if we keep saying that
you'll never get anywhere.''
   It was the pope's concerns about the leadership roles of bishops
that led him to convene a synod of Dutch bishops in 1980 and summon
21 members of the church hierarchy from Brazil, the world's largest
Roman Catholic country, in 1986.
   John Paul has also announced a special synod of bishops from
Africa, the continent where the church has experienced its most
rapid growth. The date and location must still be fixed.
   Vatican officials are also not excluding meetings with bishops
from other countries where there are particular problems or ferment.
   ``Such meetings with bishops should be seen as a natural thing,''
said Navarro.
   Each country has its special problems, he pointed out, adding
``there's no prescription for all the countries of the world.''
   During his pontificate, John Paul has revived the practice of ad
limina visits, or visits by bishops to the Vatican every five years.
That largely fell into disuse under Pope Paul VI. John Paul clearly
likes to deal directly with his prelates to get his message across,
just as he likes to go directly to the people through his
pilgrimages abroad.
   The pope summoned the Dutch bishops to Rome because the church
was split into conservative and liberal factions over issues such as
celibacy and the role of women in the church. The meeting was
classified as a synod, a more formal gathering than the Brazilian
and U.S. meetings in that it requires follow-up action by the
bishops and the Vatican.
   While there is no evidence the synod has dampened dissent among
Dutch Catholics, a series of papal appointments has given the
conservative factions control of the leadership.
   The Brazilian church was also divided between progressives and
conservatives, although the leaders generally support liberation
theology, which emphasizes the church's commitment to the poor. The
Vatican has condemned some forms it says resemble Marxism, and the
pope told the prelates they should not try to substitute for
politicians.
   The meeting ended with a joint statement by the prelates and the
Vatican stressing the importance of unity and pledging full
adherence to church teaching.
   Navarro said the U.S. meeting should not be viewed as
confrontational and that he didn't expect the pope to review the
past. Making a business analogy, Navarro said John Paul would take
the approach of a corporation head asking his people ``where do we
go from here.''
   The pope delivered his major address of the September 1987 U.S.
pilgrimage to bishops in Los Angeles, challenging them to crack down
on Catholics who dissent from church teaching. He called it a
``grave error'' to believe that one could differ with church
teaching and still consider oneself a ``good Catholic.''
   The Vatican has consistently rejected challenges to its teaching.
It recently criticized theologians who question the church ban on
contraception, in an attack apparently directed at 170
German-speaking theologians who signed a letter disagreeing with the
Vatican on the issue.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, March 5</NOTE>
</DOC>
