<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     02-28 0828</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0863</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The economy will slow substantially in 1989 and
rising inflation and higher interest rates are likely to topple the
country into a recession before the end of 1990, the nation's top
business economists predict.
   The National Association of Business Economists said Monday that
a survey of its members found them slightly more optimistic about
growth prospects for this year than they were three months ago.
   But by lopsided numbers, the economists were still predicting
that the most likely date for the start of the next recession was
1990.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Shoe Corp. is taking off its shoes, the
company said in announcing a deal to sell its footwear division, the
company name and Cincinnati headquarters to a management-led group
for $422.5 million in cash.
   The purchase announced Monday excludes U.S. Shoe's LensCrafters
division, which operates retail eyeglass stores, and the women's
retail apparel division. Key executives of U.S. Shoe's footwear
division, including Howard Platt, an executive vice president who is
president of the footwear division, are leaders in the purchasing
group.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National Semiconductor Corp. said it
is selling its mainframe computer retailing business to Hitachi Ltd.
and a unit of General Motors Corp. for $398 million, a deal one
analyst called ``a great move'' for National Semiconductor.
   In announcing the sale Monday, the chip maker said it broke off a
tentative agreement with a Dutch company, Memorex Telex NV, for half
of National Advanced Systems.
   Hitachi, which will own 80 percent of the joint venture that is
buying National Advanced Systems, will gain a greater presence in
the U.S. mainframe market dominated by IBM, analysts said. National
Advanced Systems sells Hitachi computers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After more than two months of negotiations,
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. and federal securities regulators are
nearing an agreement aimed at settling the largest Wall Street fraud
case in history, sources said.
   The sides are said to be still haggling over whether the
investment firm must move part of its high-profile, big-money ``junk
bond'' financing division run by trader Michael Milken from Beverly
Hills, Calif., to New York.
   But Drexel has agreed to tighten internal controls to prevent
future securities law violations, to hire a consultant to monitor
the changes and to increase the size of its board of directors,
sources familiar with the negotiations said Monday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four former Du Pont Co. employees were
arrested in Switzerland and a fifth remained at large after an
alleged attempt to extort $10 million from the chemical giant in
exchange for documents on the production of spandex fiber,
authorities said.
   The arrests Monday of the Argentinian nationals in Geneva
followed an aborted meeting at which Du Pont was to pay $10 million
to the suspects in exchange for ``sensitive documents'' concerning
the production of Lycra, Du Pont's trade name for spandex fiber,
according to Joseph V. Corless of the FBI.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group led by Malaysian investor Vincent Tan
announced a $33-a-share tender offer for SSMC Inc., the maker of
Singer sewing machines.
   The group, Berjaya Corp. (Malaysia) Berhad, already owns slightly
less than 10 percent of SSMC's 7.1 million outstanding shares,
giving Monday's tender offer for the remaining stock a value of
about $211 million.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Florida's vegetable farmers surveyed heavy
losses in tomato, cucumber and potato crops after a record-setting
cold snap, but an industry official predicted shoppers will not face
shortages.
   Wayne Crain, marketing-production manager for the Florida Fruit
and Vegetable Association, predicted Monday that consumers would see
little loss of volume in popular vegetables such as lettuce and
tomatoes despite damage to winter and early spring crops.
   The state's $1.3 billion citrus crop reportedly came through the
frosty weather Thursday, Friday and Saturday nearly unscathed. The
temperatures did not stay low enough long enough to affect fruit on
the trees.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Prime Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone said three
of his aides had bought bargain-priced shares in the company at the
center of a stock-profiteering scandal, but he denied any personal
involvement in the affair.
   ``I regret my aides' purchase of shares occurred because of my
poor supervision,'' Nakasone said Monday in a nationally televised
news conference. ``But I am innocent and played no role in the
scandal.''
   The largest opposition party, the Socialists, expressed
dissatisfaction with Nakasone's remarks.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices turned mixed Monday and trading tailed off to its
slowest pace in six weeks in the aftermath of the market's recent
selloff. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 4.82 points to
2,250.36.
   The dollar strengthened against all major currencies after ending
weaker overseas. Gold prices declined.
   Bond prices rose slightly.
   Cotton futures prices surged; declines were posted in grains,
soybeans, precious metals and cattle prices; hog prices were mostly
lower and pork bellies were mostly higher. Oil prices were mixed.
</TEXT>
