<FIRST>r f PM-ScotchAds     02-28 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotch Ads,0460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Johnnie Walker Models Beckon Callers in New Outdoor Ads</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY11</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Johnnie Walker scotch plans to put its own
version of a personal ad on billboards in California.
   Starting in mid-March, Johnnie Walker ads featuring a tanned
bathing beauty photographed from the back will cover extra-large
billboards in the San Francisco and Los Angeles areas.
   ``My number is 415-391-3365. And I drink Johnnie Walker,'' the
ads in San Francisco will say.
   Callers will hear a recorded 40-second message from ``Susan'' who
says she liked Johnnie Walker ``on the rocks overlooking the surf at
Big Sur'' and who would ``love to go out and do some dirty dancing.''
   In the Los Angeles area, the ads will list a number in the 213
area code, and callers will hear ``Julie'' say she likes Johnnie
Walker on the rocks ``overlooking Laguna Beach'' and is ``crazy
about country rock, rollerskating in Venice, Tchaikovsky at the
Hollywood Bowl and slam-dunking at the Forum.''
   There also will be versions of the ads featuring a male model in
each city. Print ads based on the billboard approach are planned for
regional editions of magazines, including People, Esquire and Time.
   Schieffelin &amp; Somerset Co., the New York-based importers of the
scotch, plans to spend $3 million on the campaign in California,
which accounts for about 17 percent of the nation's scotch sales.
The campaign may be expanded to other markets later.
   John Morrell, a marketing executive for Johnnie Walker, said the
appraoch was designed as a parody of the personal ads and dating
services.
   He said the idea of posting a message on a billboard ``allows
outdoor (advertising) to be something that it hasn't been before.''
   Leo Greenland, chairman of Smith Greenland, Johnnie Walker's ad
agency, said the ads are designed ``to give the consumer a little
fun and involve them in our message.''
   He said that if people start talking about the ads, he hopes
liquor retailers will give Johnnie Walker more display space,
awareness of the brand will improve and sales will pick up.
   Morrell said combined sales of Johnnie Walker Black Label and Red
Label make it the second best-selling brand in the country behind
Dewar's scotch.
   One ad in the company's current campaign features two
swimsuit-clad women running on the beach with the headline, ``He
loves my mind. And he drinks Johnny Walker.'' The ads have generated
complaints of sexism and bad taste.
   But Morrell defends the company's approach and denies the ads are
sexist.
   ``We are on the leading edge, and there will always be a small
group of people who don't like a particular execution,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890228-0199 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 0201EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-HarcourtBraceJovanovich     02-28 0155</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Harcourt Brace Jovanovich,0159</SECOND>
<HEAD>HBJ Loses $71.5 Million In Fourth Quarter, $126.5 Million For Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harcourt Brace Jovanovich reported a loss of
$71.5 million in the fourth quarter of 1988, despite a $137 million
gain from the sale of the publishing company's magazine subsidiary.
   The loss compared with a profit of $81.4 million, or $1.36 per
share, in the same period of 1987, the Orlando-based company said
Monday. Net sales for the period were $392.8 million, compared with
$329.7 million for the 1987 quarter.
   The fourth quarter was the off season for company's theme parks,
and interest expenses rose to $84.4 million for the quarter,
compared with $78.5 million for the same quarter of the year before,
HBJ said.
   For all of 1988, HBJ lost $126.5 million, compared with 1987
earnings of $64.4 million, or $1.34 a share. Revenues for 1988
totaled $1.78 billion, up from $1.52 billion in 1987.
</TEXT>
