<DOCNO> AP890228-0200 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 0206EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-U.S.Shoe-Sale     02-28 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-U.S. Shoe-Sale,0522</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Dramatic Changes Planned For Spun-Off Footware Division</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The management of a group buying the United
States Shoe Corp.'s footwear division for $422.5 million says
dramatic changes are not in store for the Cincinnati-based division.
   The footwear division will retain its existing management, U.S.
Shoe's corporate headquarters and distribution facility in the city
as well as the U.S. Shoe name, officials said Monday.
   Division President Howard Platt, who will become president and
chief executive officer of the new shoe company, said the
acquisition by a group headed by Merrill Lynch Capital Partners
Inc., an affiliate of Merrill Lynch Capital Markets Inc., should not
result in any job losses among its 8,000 employees.
   ``We're not planning any reductions in the work force, other than
what occurs through the normal course of business,'' Platt said.
   The purchase excludes U.S. Shoe's Cincinnati-based LensCrafters
division, which operates retail eyeglass stores, and its women's
apparel retail division, based in Enfield, Conn., which operates the
Casual Corner, Petite Sophisticate and Caren Charles chains.
   These divisions will be retained by the former U.S. Shoe, which
said it will choose a new corporate name.
   U.S. Shoe shares fell $5.75 Monday to close at $20 in
consolidated New York Stock Exchange trading. It was the Big Board's
second-most-active issue.
   Analysts said the company's announcement failed to live up to
expectations by some that the entire company would be sold.
   Although the domestic shoe industry has been hurt in recent years
by foreign imports, U.S. Shoe's footwear business has positioned
itself as one of the industry's strongest players through a
combination of domestic and foreign production, he said.
   The division operates about 500 retail stores under the Hahn and
Bannister store name and through leased departments. It owns 20
women's shoe brands, including Calvin Klein, Capezio, Red Cross,
Selby, Liz Claiborne and Pappagallo.
   In 1988, the footwear division, which operates about 20
manufacturing and distribution facilities in the U.S., accounted for
about one-third of U.S. Shoe's $2.2 billion in sales and 57 percent
of the the company's $52 million in profit.
   The division's domestic production represents about 10 percent to
15 percent of the total U.S. production of moderately priced shoes,
Platt said.
   Platt said the buyout won't mean any slowdown in the division's
ongoing modernization program.
   He said Merrill Lynch's offer was the best of several bids
submitted for the shoe operation. He declined to say what other bids
were submitted.
   But each bidder specified that the division's current management
remain in place. ``This is a financially led buyout as opposed to a
management-led buyout,'' he said.
   About 35 division executives will be part of the ownership group.
The exact percentage of the company they will own won't be known
until Merrill Lynch completes its financing.
   Merrill Lynch has commitments for $160 million of equity and debt
financing and says it is ``highly confident'' it will secure the
remaining financing through senior bank debt.
   Completion of the sale is expected in about three months.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890228-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 0727EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     02-28 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises, Gold Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose against most major currencies in
calm European trading late this morning. Gold prices fell.
   Traders said the dollar was being sustained by short-covering, or
the buying of dollars to fulfill agreements to sell them, ahead of
the 8:30 a.m. EST release of U.S. fourth-quarter gross national
product figures.
   Traders also were buying dollars ahead of congressional hearings
by U.S. Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady and Federal Reserve
Chairman Alan Greenspan.
   The market was expecting preliminary GNP figures to show a modest
2.5 percent increase in U.S. economic growth in the final three
months of last year, slightly up from the original estimate of 2
percent growth.
   Traders said a neutral or worse-than-expected figures would be
bearish for the dollar because of an underlying downward trend.
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.7390 from $1.7440 Monday.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Monday's
rates, included: 1.8289 West German marks, up from 1.8150; 1.5597
Swiss francs, up from 1.5495; 6.2270 French francs, up from 6.1775;
2.0649 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0490; 1,347.50 Italian lire, up
from 1,339.62; 1.2005 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2025.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 1.15 yen to a closing 127.15 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 127.23 yen.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $386.70 a troy ounce,
down from $389 bid late Monday. At midmorning today, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $386.75.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $386.65, down from $390.25 bid late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $4.09 to close at a bid $388.85.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $5.86 a troy
ounce, down from Monday's $5.93.
</TEXT>
