<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 0803EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Steel-Restraints     02-28 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Steel-Restraints,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>VRA Extension Needed to Avoid More Steel Dumping, USS Head Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government should extend the current
limits on imported steel to avoid more dumping of the metal on U.S.
markets, a leading steel industry executive says.
   The current voluntary restraint agreement is to expire at the end
of September, and a five-year extension has been recommended to the
Bush administration.
   Without the renewal, President Thomas Graham of USX Corp.'s USS
Division said Monday, overseas steel producers will invade the U.S.
market.
   ``There's no doubt that foreign producers will revert to
large-scale dumping of heavily subsidized steel'' without a
restraints renewal, he said. ``We certainly can't tolerate a return
to past practices.''
   In the third quarter of 1984, shortly before the restraints
began, imported steel made up just more than 30 percent of the U.S.
market.
   Graham's comments came during the opening day of the week-long
annual congress of the Society of Automotive Engineers.
   He said the voluntary restraints renewal is essential if the U.S.
steel industry is to continue its two-year financial recovery.
   ``We can't afford to become giddy,'' he said. ``Two years of
profitability doesn't offset five years of losses.''
   Graham said the U.S. steel industry earned more than $2 billion
in 1988 and about $900 million the year before. But between 1982 and
1986, the industry lost $12 billion, an average of $2.4 billion
annually.
   The voluntary restraint agreement, which began in 1984, limits
the amount of imported finished steel to 18.5 percent of the U.S.
market, among other things. The American Institute for Imported
Steel said steel made overseas and shipped to the United States
accounts for about 17.7 percent of the market, below the current
limit.
   The imported steel association, which supports an elimination of
the restraints or a two-year extension instead of five years, has
claimed that the limits reduce supply thereby increasing prices for
U.S. steel, something the domestic steelmakers like.
   But Graham dismissed that contention.
   ``It's not an issue of protectionism,'' he said, ``it's an issue
of legal trading practices.''
   Graham also said USS is prepared to file legal papers if the Bush
administration rejects a voluntary restraints extension.
   ``We need enabling legislation from Congress before the Bush
administration has the ability to act,'' he said. ``We see ourselves
as prudent businessmen.''
   He declined to say when any legal moves may be taken, adding that
an earlier agreement barred the industry from filing trade
litigation while a voluntary restraint was in effect.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890228-0206 </DOCNO>
