<FIRST>r f PM-Polaroid-Shamrock     02-28 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Polaroid-Shamrock,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamrock Seeks Injunction Against Polaroid Stock Buyback</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shamrock Holdings Inc. has asked a
Delaware judge to prevent Polaroid's directors from exercising proxy
rights on $300 million of preferred stock that Polaroid sold last
month to a friendly investment group.
   Shamrock's lawyers on Monday also asked Vice Channcellor Carolyn
Berger of the Delaware Chancery Court to block the Cambridge,
Mass.-based company's $1.125 billion stock buy-back plan, saying it
would give management an unfair advantage in an imminent proxy
battle.
   Berger took both arguments under advisement. Her rulings could
have a major impact on the takeover and proxy battle being waged by
Shamrock, a radio and television concern based in Burbank, Calif.
   Polaroid has defended itself against Shamrock's hostile
$45-a-share takeover bid by offering $50 a share for 22 percent of
its own stock. Polaroid's offer expires March 20, which ensures that
shares tendered by that date will be controlled by management at the
May 9 annual meeting.
   Shamrock attorney Michael Rauch contended that Polaroid's tender
offer should not be allowed before the meeting, at which the
company's entire board of directors is up for election.
   Rauch noted that Polaroid previously issued close to 10 million
shares to an employee stock ownership plan and sold more shares to
Corporate Partners L.P., a New York investment group formed to aid
companies warding off hostile suitors.
   ``Polaroid made a short-term merger impossible by issuing
stock,'' Rauch said. ``Now they've stacked the deck by removing the
one chance for stockholders to have a say'' at the annual meeting.
   But Polaroid attorney Frederick Schwartz said, ``We're performing
our duty (to the stockholders).''
</TEXT>
