<SECOND>BC-SDRC-Nissan,0192</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nissan, Ohio Firm Join In Forming Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILFORD, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Structural Dynamics Research Corp. and
Nissan Motor Co. Ltd., the big Japanese automaker, have formed a
joint company to provide engineering consulting services in the Far
East, it was announced Tuesday.
   The joint venture marks the first time Nissan has teamed up with
an overseas company to launch a new business activity, the
announcement stated.
   Nissan owns 70 percent of the new company called ESTECH Corp. and
SDRC owns 30 percent.
   Kinji Shono, general manager of Nissan's Business Development
Office, has been named president of ESTECH. Additional staff members
will be supplied by both firms.
   ESTECH, to be based in Yokohama, Japan, will provide engineering
consulting and problem-solving techniques related to product design
and manufacturing. Initially, the majority of services will be
conducted for Nissan.
   In addition to forming the new company, Tokyo-based Nissan has
selected SDRC as its preferred vendor for mechanical computer-aided
engineering software, on a worldwide basis.
   SDRC is an international supplier of mechanical computer-aided
engineering software and services used by automotive, aerospace and
industrial manufacturers.
