<FIRST>u f PM-Eastern-Machinists     02-28 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Machinists,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Returns To Court Against Union `Slowdown'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines and its Machinists union were in
federal court trading charges of contract violations as a Friday
strike deadline loomed ever closer.
   Eastern on Monday asked a federal judge for permission to
subcontract some repairs to catch up on a growing backlog. The
carrier also accused the Machinists of engaging in illegal work
slowdowns and refusing to accept mandatory overtime requests.
   U.S. District Judge C. Clyde Atkins ordered the Machinists to
prepare their response to the injunction request by today, and said
he would schedule a hearing shortly after listening to their
testimony.
   Eastern said Monday that 36,000 man-hours usually are enough to
service four to six planes, but union workers are now taking 97,000
hours, increasing their backlog by almost 15 engines above the
company's operating plan.
   The Machinists in turn have blamed Eastern and Frank Lorenzo, the
chairman of Eastern's parent Texas Air Corp., for delays in putting
planes back on line.
   ``Mr. Lorenzo has taken most of the newer aircraft from Eastern's
fleet and put them over at Continental (Airlines),'' said union
spokesman Wally Haber. ``The ones we have over here are old ones
that need a lot of work.''
   At a Feb. 17 hearing on the same issues, Atkins ordered the union
to accept overtime while telling Eastern to stop farming out its
plane repairs. Eastern claims that the union has violated that
order, and wants to begin contracting out again.
   On another front, the Machinists once again called on President
Bush to create an emergency board empowered to declare a 60-day
cooling-off period when the current one ends at midnight EST Friday.
   ``We are in favor of a presidential emergency board,'' Haber
said. ``We look forward to putting our case before a third party.''
   Eastern, which estimates its losses at $1 million a day, has
opposed the board because it fears another extension will simply
cost the carrier more money, said spokesman Robin Matell.
