<SECOND>PM-Morton Thiokol, 1st Ld-Writethru,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>Morton Thiokol Splitting Aerospace, Commercial Operations</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Recasts to move up Challenger angle, Add stock information and
other details, tighten</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Morton Thiokol Inc., manufacturer of the booster
rockets which were blamed for the space shuttle Challenger explosion
three years ago, says it plans to spin off its specialty chemical
business from its troubled aerospace operation.
   The plan, approved by the board of directors and announced on
Monday, would split Morton Thiokol into two companies: Thiokol Inc.,
the aerospace concern, and Morton International Inc., which would
include the speciality chemicals, airbags and salt businesses.
   The transaction is expected to be finalized July 1 pending
shareholders' aproval, according to company spokesman Tom Russell.
   Under the plan, shareholders would receive a tax-free
distribution of a share of Morton International stock for each
Morton Thiokol share. The company said it believes the stock of both
new companies will qualify for listing on the New York Stock
Exchange.
   Russell said the planned spinoff had nothing to do with the
Challenger explosion.
   Morton Thiokol manufactured the rocket boosters of the
Challenger, which exploded shortly after takeoff on Jan. 28, 1986,
killing the seven crew members. Investigators have blamed a failure
in the boosters on the explosion.
   Morton Thiokol has since redesigned the boosters, correcting
joint problems linked to the blast, and they have been used
successfully on two shuttle flights in recent months.
   ``The shuttle program is in very good shape, we're very confident
of redesign,'' Russell said.
   Morton Thiokol Chairman Charles S. Locke, said the spinoff ``will
allow investors to evaluate better the individual businesses and
their future outlook, enhancing the likelihood that the true value
of each business will be properly reflected.''
   Wall Street also appeared optimsitic about the plan. Morton
Thiokol rose $3.50 to $43.50 in late-morning trading today on the
NYSE.
   Locke said the specialty chemicals company is expected to have
fiscal 1989 assets of $1.4 billion and sales of $1.5 billion. The
aerospace business is expected to post $1.1 billion in sales this
year and have assets of $800 million, he said.
   The company said that S. Jay Stewart, Mortion Thiokol's president
and chief operating officer, is expected to be elected to those
posts at Morton International. Ed Garrison, group vice president for
aerospace in Ogden, Utah, is expected to be elected president and
chief operating officer of the aerospace company, it said.
   Morton Thiokol said special charges anticipated from the spinoff
will reduce estimated net income to below the range of $3.40 to
$3.60 a share.
   Morton Thiokol's fiscal 1988 net income totaled $145.3 million,
or $3.04 a share, on sales of $2.32 billion.
</TEXT>
