<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   02-28 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Gain On China Offer, Light Deliveries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened moderately higher
today on the Chicago Board of Trade, partly in reaction to the
Agriculture Department's offer of more wheat to China.
   The USDA announced late Monday that it had targeted the Chinese
for sales of an additional 2 million metric tons of wheat at
subsidized prices.
   Under previous authorizations in the government's Export
Enhancement Program, China has bought more than 7.4 million tons of
wheat for delivery in 1988-89. Only 10,000 tons remained in the
previous authorization issued on Dec. 30.
   Soybean and oat futures advanced in response to
lighter-than-expected delivery notices posted against the March
contracts. Higher soybean meal prices in Europe also supported the
soybean complex, analysts said.
   Corn's early gains mainly reflected spillover buying from the
neighboring grain and soybean pits.
   In early trading, wheat was 1} cents to 4{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.37 a bushel; corn was 1\ cents
to 1} cents higher with March at $2.71} a bushel; oats were 2{ cents
to 4{ cents higher with March at $2.03} a bushel; soybeans were 2{
cents to 4} cents higher with March at $7.62 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly lower in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .30 cent lower to .10 cent higher with April at
77.90 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .20 cent lower
with March at 82.72 cents a pound; live hogs were unchanged to .15
cent lower with April at 43.35 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .02 cent to .25 cent lower with March at 37.75 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures retreated on Monday while pork futures settled
mixed.
</TEXT>
