<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 1204EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Cannon-Golan     02-28 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Cannon-Golan,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>Golan Resigns From Cannon, Will Head Own Film Production Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Menachem Golan, who headed the Cannon Group
film company with his cousin Yorum Globus for eight years, has
resigned to form his own film production company, Cannon announced.
   Golan and his cousin headed the Los Angeles-based film company
from 1979 until last April when Italian financier Giancarlo Paretti
took control.
   Golan will set up a new independent production company with about
$160 million he will receive under a four-year agreement with
Cannon, the company said Monday.
   Globus' future was not mentioned in the company's announcement.
   The change will allow Cannon's controlling shareholders, led by
Parretti, to fit the production firm into the group of companies and
film assets Parretti is acquiring.
   Paretti announced last Friday he had bought New World
Entertainment. Last month he founded Pathe Entertainment.
   According to the agreement with Golan, Cannon is to commit $159.6
million to Golan's new company to finance 17 motion pictures. The
company is to provide $3 million a year for operating expenses in
addition to a $6 million fund for developing projects.
   Golan is to receive 20 percent of the net profits of each film
his new company makes and will buy the name and logo of 21st Century
Distribution Corp. from Cannon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
