<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 1258EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-AgingAirliners 2ndLd-Writethru f0058 02-28 0797</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Aging Airliners, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0058,0816</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Recommends $800 million In Work On Older Airlines</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs pvs 4th graf, Some major, with 3 grafs on news conference</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of aviation industry and government
safety experts recommended today $800 million worth of mandatory
work on older airliners to ensure safety of the nation's aging
airliner fleet.
   The unprecedented program, if adopted by the Federal Aviation
Administration, would affect more than 1,300 early Boeing 747, 737
and 727 models at a cost of over $600,000 each.
   The Aging Aircraft Task Force's working group on older Boeing
airliners drew up its final recommendations this morning just prior
to a news conference releasing the details. The Air Transport
Association, which represents major airlines, organized the task
force.
   Clyde Kizer, an ATA vice president, said none of the recommended
work, which would involve planes flown by foreign carriers as well
as U.S. airlines, was considered urgent. ``There are no dangerous
aircraft out there flying right now,'' he told reporters.
   Representatives of Delta and United, who also participated in the
news conference, said much of the work had already been done on
their airliners and they anticipated no immeidate large expenses.
   Some other major airlines also have made many of the changes
recommended by the task force.
   ``Widescale modification or replacement of structural material,
fittings and skin are being recommended on the basis of service
experience,'' said a final draft of the report, which follows nine
months of meetings and examination of more than 700 service
bulletins issued by Boeing.
   The recommendations adopt 150 of the bulletins and consolidate
them into the form of one massive service bulletin to be issued by
Boeing and presented to the FAA for possible adoption as an
airworthiness directive.
   The difference in a manufacturer's bulletin and an FAA
airworthiness directive is that FAA orders are mandatory. Airliner
operators will be given varying times to accomplish the changes,
based on the amount of service an aircraft has had.
   Other groups from the task force are looking at service
recommendations affecting McDonnell Douglas DC-9s, DC-8s and DC-10s
and airliners manufactured abroad to see what modifications will be
needed to maintain their safety. Results of their work are expected
before the end of the year.
   The average age of the nearly 3,000 U.S. airliners is about 13
years, with half the planes in many major airlines' fleets well over
15 years old, according to Avmark, an appraisal and consulting firm.
   The task force recommendations, if adopted by the FAA, would be a
departure from a system that has relied primarily on inspection
orders, with repairs made subsequently when needed.
   Among the 150 participants on the task force are the FAA,
representatives of major airlines belonging to the Air Transport
Association, professional airline mechanics organizations, foreign
airlines and regulatory bodies, and the National Aeronautics and
Space Administration.
   Both Boeing and McDonnell Douglas, along with several airlines
and the FAA have been examining the problems of the aging
international airliner fleet, but this is the first time government
and industry have gotten together on such a large scale to tackle
the issue.
   Boeing head F. A. Shrontz said in Washington last week that his
company's airliners are built to last forever if properly maintained.
   Old airliners are rarely scrapped because low aviation fuel
prices, steadily increasing air travel, the high cost of new
airliners and other factors have boosted the demand for old
airliners and their value.
   But airport noise reduction requirements and incidents of holes
ripping open in fuselages and of wheels and engines falling off of
older planes are putting increased pressure on airlines to phase out
their oldest models.
   Some airline critics have suggested that whole classes of
airliners be scrapped or that airliners be taken out of service
after a set number of flying hours or takeoffs and landings.
   Aviation experts say that the chronological age of an airliner
has less effect on its overall value and safety than other factors
such as the number of times its cabin is pressurized and
depressurized, the quality of the airline's maintenance program and
the environment in which it is flown.
   Increased concern over aging airliners was prompted by an April
1988 incident in which the top of the passenger compartment in an
Aloha 737 ripped off over Hawaii. A stewardess was killed in the
incident.
   The recommendations came four days after a hole ripped open in
United Air Lines' oldest 747, sending nine passengers hurling to
their deaths 17 minutes after takeoff from Honolulu. But
investigators in that incident said they found no signs of metal
fatigue that is often a factor in damage to older airliners and were
focusing on the possibility of a faulty cargo door.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890228-0222 </DOCNO>
