<FIRST>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     02-28 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0414</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher In Uninspired Trading, Gold Falls</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMs planned by 5:30 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar finished higher in uninspired
European trading Tuesday following news of slower-than-expected U.S.
economic growth and continued high inflation.
   Gold prices were lower.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the dollar was unable to sustain
early highs following news that the U.S. gross national product
expanded at an unrevised seasonally adjusted rate of 2 percent in
the fourth quarter of 1988. The market had been expecting an upward
revision to 2.5 percent.
   Dealers said the market also sold dollars on news that the
implicit GNP deflator, a measure of inflation, rose 5.3 percent in
the fourth quarter.
   The market is now adopting a wait-and-see attitude ahead of
Wednesday's release of British trade figures and Thursday's meeting
of the Bundesbank, West Germany's central bank, to see what happens
with European interest rates, dealers said.
   Britain's trade figures will be watched closely because many
market players think a wider-than-expected deficit could force the
government to prompt another one-point hike in the commercial banks'
base lending rate, which stands at 13 percent.
   Dealers said both the dollar and the pound were helped by the
West German mark's weaker tone on Tuesday amid growing speculation
the Bundesbank might not raise key interest rates at Thursday's
meeting of its central bank council.
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.7430 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.7440 late Monday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Monday:
1.8230 West German marks, up from 1.8150; 1.5535 Swiss francs, up
from 1.5495; 6.1975 French francs, up from 6.1775; 2.0555 Dutch
guilders, up from 2.0490; 1,341.50 Italian lire, up from 1,339.62;
1.2005 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2025.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 1.15 yen to a closing 127.15 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted lower at 126.70 yen.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid price of $386.75 a troy ounce,
compared with late Monday's $389.00.
   In Zurich, gold fell to close at a bid $387.15 compared with
$390.25 late Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $4.09 to close at a bid $388.85.
   Silver bullion prices fell on the London market where the metal
was trading at a late bid price of $5.86 a troy ounce, compared with
Monday's $5.93.
</TEXT>
