<HEAD>Soybean Oil Leads Late Surge In Complex</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed higher Tuesday on
the Chicago Board of Trade, paced by a technically inspired surge in
the soybean oil market.
   Soybean futures also advanced sharply, with prices for deliveries
of this summer's crop posting the strongest gains.
   Soybean oil had opened lower in reaction to the morning posting
of a higher-than-expected number of notices of intent to deliver
soybean oil against the March contract.
   The large number of delivery notices, an indication of ample
supplies, was seen as a bearish signal. But prices did not fall
sharply, and ``if you're a trader, that's a good sign,'' said Walter
Spilka, a market analyst in New York with Smith Barney, Harris Upham
&amp; Co.
   ``Later in the session, some buying began to accumulate and that
fed on itself and we had a big surge in the end,'' Spilka said.
``The market put on one of its best performances since the summer.''
   Wheat and corn futures were supported by an improving export
picture, including the Agriculture Department's offer to subsidize
sales of 2 million metric tons of wheat to China.
   At the close, wheat was unchanged to 3} cents higher with March
at $4.36\ a bushel; corn was } cent to 2{ cents higher with March at
$2.72{ a bushel; oats were 4 cents to 5{ cents higher with March at
$2.04} a bushel; soybeans were 5\ cents to 11 cents higher with
March at $7.62{ a bushel.
