<FIRST>r f BC-ZZZZBest     02-28 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-ZZZZ Best,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former ZZZZ Best Associates Sentenced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three former associates of fallen business
virtuoso Barry Minkow were sentenced to up to three years in jail
for taking part in the ZZZZ Best fraud case.
   U.S. District Judge Dickran Tevrizian on Monday sentenced Norman
Rothberg, 52, of Marina del Rey, who turned Minkow in then accepted
money to keep quiet, to one year and one day in prison for his
conviction on five counts of fraud.
   Daniel B. Krowpman was sentenced to three years in prison for
taking $600,000 in profits from the fraud. The judge also fined
Krowpman $5,000 and ordered him to serve five years probation when
he is released from prison.
   Krowpman loaned Minkow money to start the ZZZZ Best carpet
cleaning company when Minkow, now 22, was just 16 and operating out
of his parents' garage, according to trial testimony.
   U.S. Attorney James Asperger said Krowpman submitted falsified
documents that helped Minkow with his scheme.
   Edward Krivda was sentenced to 60 days in a halfway house for his
role in supplying carpet to ZZZZ Best. He also was ordered to
perform 300 hours of community service and placed on three years'
probation.
   Krivda and Krowpman both pleaded guilty to a variety of charges.
   Dozens of men were convicted or pleaded guilty in the $25 million
bank and investment scam. Minkow, who faces up to 403 years in
prison, is to be sentenced March 13.
</TEXT>
