<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 2024EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-GM-Hughes     02-28 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-GM-Hughes,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>GM Paying $975 Million In Class H Stock Dispute With Hughes Institute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. said Tuesday it will spend
$975 million to buy blocks of stock from the Howard Hughes Medical
Institute to settle a dispute stemming from the automaker's 1985
purchase of Hughes Aircraft Co.
   The institute, a philanthropic organization founded by the late
billionaire recluse, had complained to GM officials that it wasn't
satisifed with the performance of GM's Class H common stock.
   GM said it would pay $675 million in cash and $300 million in
notes to buy 35 million shares of the stock, which was created to
help finance the $5.2 billion purchase of Hughes Aircraft in June
1985.
   The medical institute now owns 99.5 million, or about 78 percent,
of the outstanding shares of GM Class H stock.
   The agreement resolves a dispute that went to arbitration late
last year. GM Treasurer Leon Krain refused to disclose the reasons
for the arbitration, which kicked in under terms of the 1985 Hughes
deal.
   GM reportedly was seeking a rebate on what it paid for Hughes
because the company lost some Defense Department contracts it had
before the purchase was made.
   The institute in December complained about light trading of the
Class H stock, which made up the bulk of its assets, and that the
price of the shares appeared mainly tied to a $30-a-share price
guarantee.
   When Hughes Aircraft became GM Hughes Electronics Corp., the
automaker promised to pay the institute the difference between $30 a
share and the average price for Class H stock during the last
quarter of 1989. That provision was canceled by the agreement.
   The new agreement calls for a series of stock purchase and sell
options for GM and the institute from 1991 to 1995. If all are
exercised, the medical institute would hold about 9.5 million
shares, or 7.5 percent, of the outstanding Class H stock.
   The agreement requires that the institute hold its Class H stock
until each option deadline passes.
   GM Chairman Roger B. Smith said the company, which has reported
that it has $6.8 billion in cash on hand, could afford the stock
purchase plans called for in the agreement. He said the agreement
will provide the institute with cash liquidity it had sought.
   Bob Potter, spokesman for the Bethesda, Md.-based medical
institute, said the $675 million in cash go into an investment fund.
The remaining $300 million is to be split between two notes.
   Money generated from the investment fund will go to a variety of
projects, including medical research, Potter said. In a statement,
institute chairman George Thorn said the money will allow better
planning of research and other capital expenditure programs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890228-0232 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 1634EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-S&amp;LCrisis     02-28 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;L Crisis,0489</SECOND>
<HEAD>Breeden Tries To Sell Independent Bankers On Bush Proposals</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Stands for AM-S&amp;L Plan listed on the Late News Advisory.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's point man on the savings
and loan crisis urged a group representing smaller banks Tuesday to
enthusiastically support the administration's plan for rescuing the
thrift industry even though they may have reservations about some
aspects.
   Richard C. Breeden, who oversaw drafting of the president's plan,
told a meeting of the Independent Bankers Association of America
that quibbling over details of the plan could dangerously delay
urgently needed action.
   The administration has estimated the cost of rescuing insolvent
or teetering S&amp;Ls at $90 billion and the weak one-third of the
industry is losing money at the rate of $40 million a day.
   ``At $40 million a day, we shouldn't launch into a six-month
debate,'' Breeden told the bankers, meeting at the Anaheim Hilton
Hotel. ``We simply have a huge problem and we simply have to get on
with it.''
   The president has proposed spending $39.9 billion of tax money
over the next decade to finance the bailout. Additionally, savings
and loans and to a lesser extent banks would pay more for their
federal deposit insurance.
   Members of the independent bankers group, which represents
community banks with assets of $100 million or less, have objected
that higher insurance premiums would place a disproportionate burden
on them.
   They also have complained that the president's plan does little
to remedy what they see as inequities between regulation of their
industry and the credit unions with which they compete.
   One aspect of the plan that has drawn little opposition is the
president's proposal that federal regulators should rein in what
many see as overly aggressive management in the thrift industry.
Under the Bush plan, the Federal Home Loan Bank Board, which
oversees the S&amp;L business, would be placed under control of the
Treasury, as has long been the case with bank regulation.
   ``Critical decisions of the bank board over the last decade
concerning capital adequacy, capital averaging, accounting rules,
chartering standards and other areas of thrift supervision do not
seem to have adequately protected the public marketplace and the
taxpayers,'' Breeden said.
   ``As a result, we must instill accountability at the top to help
prevent a repetition of this situation.''
   The president's aide drew sustained applause from the bankers
when he reminded them the president wants to spend an additional $50
million a year to prosecute dishonest thrift managers.
   ``The president is determined to see that those who have caused
massive losses to American society through criminal wrongdoing will
be sought out, pursued relentlessly and placed behind bars where
they belong for a long time,'' Breeden said.
   A congressional study found fraud played some role in up to
one-third of thrift failures to date.
</TEXT>
