<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   02-28 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market rose Tuesday in what analysts
described as a reflex response to last week's sharp decline.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 8.03 points to
2,258.39.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 9 to 5 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
911 up, 531 down and 516 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board totaled 147.43 million
shares, up from 139.90 million in Monday's session.
   ``It's kind of a physical, knee-jerk pop,'' said Larry Wachtel,
an analyst for Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   Market-watchers cautioned against attaching undue significance to
a pair of government economic reports released Tuesday, since they
referred to a past period.
   The Commerce Department reported that the economy grew at a
sluggish annual rate of 2 percent in the final three months of 1988
as the worst deterioration in the trade deficit in more than two
years offset unexpected strength in consumer spending.
   The trade shortfall climbed to $32 billion in the period, as both
U.S. exports and imports hit record levels.
   ``I wouldn't read too much into this whole thing,'' said Michael
Metz, an analyst for Oppenheimer &amp; Co. ``They (stock traders) are
almost looking for an excuse to rally.''
   Despite the news of sluggish growth in the fourth quarter, the
market's underlying anxiety about inflation persists, analysts said.
That concern was a big factor in last week's slide, which hammered
the Dow Jones average down 79.28 points.
   Wall Street sniffed at congressional testimony Tuesday by Federal
Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan, who warned that interest rates will
remain high unless Congress and the administration do a credible job
of cutting the budget deficit.
   The Fed chairman has appeared on Capitol Hill numerous times in
the past week or so, and market participants seem to have grown
blase about his statements.
   ``They sort of brushed right by that,'' said Bob O'Toole, manager
of over-the-counter trading at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Among actively traded issues on the NYSE, Texaco rose ~ to 51~,
AT&amp;T was up [ at 30\, Coca Cola advanced ~ to 47} and Columbia
Pictures, the subject of revived takeover speculation, jumped 1 to
16}.
   US Shoe fell { to 19{, continuing Monday's slide. Traders'
expectations of a possible takeover or other transaction were
chilled Monday by news that the company agreed to sell its footwear
division.
   Emhart slipped [ to 40\, General Electric was down \ at 45}, IBM
declined [ to 121{ and Burlington Resources dropped 1| to 46.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 178.00 million shares.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market gained $8.42 billion, or 0.30
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
0.54 to 162.49.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index advanced 1.24 to 333.48, and
S&amp;P's 500-stock composite index was up 1.04 at 288.86.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market rose
0.77 to 399.71. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 322.47, up 1.05.
</TEXT>
