<FIRST>u f AM-Sears-Closings 1stLd-Writethru f0251 02-28 0663</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sears-Closings, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0251,0683</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nation's Largest Retailer Gets New Prices, New Look</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Minor editing throughout.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CO1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER C. KENT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The store sound system played ``Don't
Worry, Be Happy,'' managers maneuvered via walkie-talkie and
hundreds of workers armed with price tag guns scrambled through a
closed Sears store Tuesday to remake the image of the nation's
biggest retailer.
   In Columbus as elsewhere, Sears, Roebuck and Co. stores closed
their doors to undergo the nuts and bolts work demanded by the
company's new retailing strategy for attracting more customers.
   By reopening time at noon Wednesday, workers nationwide were to
have rolled back prices on 50,000 items representing an estimated
1.5 billion pieces of merchandise in more than 820 stores, in
addition to changing signs, taking inventory and cleaning up.
   ``The worst was the screwdrivers,'' said Chris Skinner, a
Brookhaven High School freshman who spent much of the day repricing
baby booties and toddlers' dresses. ``You had to take them all down,
clean each one by hand, then put them all back.''
   The cash register rings about 3,000 times a day in the
100,000-square-foot store, but the only sound Wednesday was the
clicking of pricing guns and muffled sounds of store officials
keeping in touch via 15 walkie-talkies.
   About 100 high school students worked for $5 an hour to help
company officials in shirt sleeves and scores of others with the
changeover.
   ``It's the most exciting thing I've ever been involved in in
Sears,'' said Bob Dumas, manager of the Northland Mall store and a
30-year Sears employee.
   ``It's no longer that old sea of yellow,'' he said, referring to
Sears' old yellow-with-black-lettering sale signs. Many new signs
touting Sears' new, lower pricing policy are red and blue, although
in apparel they are magenta and gray.
   At the Northland store, 700 workers scrambled to the tune of
``Don't Worry, Be Happy,'' as they marked down items such as a twin
canopy bed from $269.99 to $99.00. A Diehard automobile battery is
now $64 instead of $72. And a Craftsman power drill is now $32.62
instead of $59.99.
   Sears' new strategy meant reductions on 75 percent of its own
brands and 1,000 other brand names it now carries.
   ``I don't think they had any choice. They lost their customer
base,'' said Karen Sacks, an analyst with Standard and Poor's Corp.
in New York. ``I think Wednesday will be a madhouse at Sears. But
will they be able to re-educate their customers not to come in just
for a sale?''
   Men's department manager Marilyn Stone said they would.
   ``Our customers are aleady asking about the changes,'' she said,
adding that the company has more brands, better quality and fewer
items that are 100 percent polyester.
   Monroe Greenstein, analyst with the investment firm Bear Stearns
in New York, said the strategy paid off in Wichita, Kan., where
sales rose 15 percent when Sears tested the idea was last fall.
   ``And Sears will invest in an advertising campaign that, to not
hear about it, you would practically have to be comatose,''
Greenstein said.
   Columbus managers, dressed in work clothes, distributed 700 rolls
of pricing gun tape, enough to make about 350,000 new tags, and
handed out 30,000 new signs, including some that hang from ceilings
and those to be placed on bins of hardware.
   Workers dusted off palm trees that hovered alongside sparkling
racks of tropical pre-teen apparel and pulled washers and dryers
from their places to repaint the walls and changed the price tags on
lightbulbs.
   New displays featured new brands that Sears will offer.
   Display supervisor Todd Skeie said the displays were ``looser''
and ``livelier'' than they ever have been. He said better products
and being allowed to display items above the cornice on the wall for
the first time improved the store's looks.
   ``You should always keep up with the times,'' said employee Karen
Jackson. ``You don't want to be in the back seat forever.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
