<FIRST>r f AM-MortonThiokol     02-28 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Morton Thiokol,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>Morton Thiokol Stock Up After Split Announcement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Morton Thiokol Inc. stock rose sharply
Tuesday in the wake of the company's announcement that it is
splitting its aerospace and commercial operations.
   The Chicago-based company announced Monday it planned to return
the name Thiokol Corp. to its aerospace group and create a new
specialty chemical, airbag and salt company to be called Morton
International Inc.
   The move is expected to be final July 1, provided the Internal
Revenue Service rules it will be tax-free and the stockholders
approve, company officials said.
   Morton Thiokol stock rose $2.25 to close at $42.25 in New York
Stock Exchange trading Tuesday.
   Industry analysts applauded the company's decision.
   ``I'm a little surprised, but this is a positive (move) for the
company and a benefit for shareholders,'' said Robert Bartels of
William Blair &amp; Co.
   Bartels said the aerospace business had depressed the price of
the company's stock.
   Morton Thiokol's aerospace group was forced to undertake a $500
million redesign of the space shuttle booster motor following the
1986 Challenger explosion, which was blamed on a faulty booster
joint.
   But Bartels said the drag on the stock would exist even without
the Challenger disaster because of the nature of defense work today
_ lower spending demanded by Congress.
   Morton Thiokol stockholders will receive a share-for-share
distribution of Morton International stock. Company officials said
the stock of both companies likely will qualify for listing on the
New York Stock Exchange.
   The Utah-based aerospace group, which manufactures the shuttle
booster motor and other defense propulsion systems, was acquired in
1982 by Morton Norwich and the merged company was called Morton
Thiokol Inc.
   The action is expected to have little change on the Utah
operation, headquartered in Ogden, said aerospace group president Ed
Garrison, who will stay on as president and chief operating officer
of Thiokol Corp.
   Indeed, he said, Thiokol plans to bid on a $2 million-plus
shuttle booster contract that would stretch through the mid-1990s.
   The company, which employs about 7,500 workers at its
manufacturing and testing facility near Brigham City, is the state's
largest private employer. Another 500 to 600 workers affiliated with
the Utah operation are based at Cape Canaveral, Fla.
   The aerospace operation has a total of more than 12,000 employees.
   Morton International plans to maintain a presence in Utah,
keeping its salt manufacturing facility at the Great Salt Lake and
maintaining the Ogden plant where 350 people manufacture inflatable
airbags for automobiles.
   But Garrison said the aerospace company retains 40 percent of the
solid rocket propulsion industry's business and anticipates further
success.
   ``Sales are expected to be more than $1 billion for 1989,''
Garrison said. ``We will wind up with a very strong company.''
   The company has said the new Thiokol is expected to have sales of
about $1.1 billion and assets of $800 million, while Morton
International would have an estimated 1989 sales of $1.5 billion,
assets of $1.4 billion and 8,000 employees.
</TEXT>
