<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 1910EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-HomeSales 1stLd-Writethru f0150 02-28 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Home Sales, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0150,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sales Off But Prices Rise</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs to CORRECT that sales declined, sted rose 6th graf, `Home
prices</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Also moved on general news wires
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of existing homes fell 7.4 percent in
January, the biggest decline in two years, as activity returned to
more normal levels following a December sales spurt, a real estate
trade group reported Tuesday.
   The National Association of Realtors said that existing
single-family homes were sold at a seasonally adjusted annual rate
of 3.63 million units in January following a 5.7 percent rise in
December to a rate of 3.92 million.
   It was the biggest one-month drop since a 13.3 percent drop in
January 1987 and left the pace of sales at its slowest point since
July.
   Analysts, however, said they were not overly concerned, noting
that the December sales pace had been the fastest sales rate in two
years. Even with the January setback, sales were still 13.4 percent
above where they were in January 1988.
   ``Overall, January's activity shows signs of another strong year
for home sales,'' said Ira Gribin, president of the Realtors. ``The
market is now dominated by the volume of buyers, many of whom are
repeat purchasers in their peak income years.''
   Homes prices continued to rise in January, even with the decline
in sales. The median price of a home rose 3.2 percent to $91,500.
   John Tuccillo, chief economist for the Realtors, said the price
increase would have been even larger if it had not been for an
increase in sales volume at the low-end of the price range as buyers
altered their choices due to rising mortgage rates.
   Mortgage rates, as tracked by a national survey done by the
Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp., hit 10.78 percent last week with
many economists expecting them to soon pass 11 percent.
   The month-to-month sales decline was led by a sharp 12.6 percent
drop in the South, which fell to an annual rate of 1.31 million
units.
   Sales in the West declined by 8.6 percent to an annual rate of
640,000 units while sales in the Midwest fell 5.9 percent to an
annual rate of 950,000 units.
   The Northeast was the only region of the country posting a sales
increase from December to January, a 1.4 percent rise to annual rate
of 710,000 units.
</TEXT>
